<FIRST>r w PM-Lobbyists     05-18 0564</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lobbyists,Bjt,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>For Lobbyists, Schmoozing's the Name of the Game</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT M. ANDREWS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shoes shiny as mirrors, white teeth framed in
sincere smiles and fingers groping for buttonholes, members of the
American League of Lobbyists gathered to practice their
bread-and-butter art of schmoozing.
   Lobbyists seem to be everywhere in Washington, trying to
influence legislators or government policy-makers to give their
clients a break. It's a tough job, especially if the client is
unsavory or his cause unpopular. Often, success depends on knowing
whose name to drop, which elbow to squeeze.
   It also can be highly lucrative. ``We don't starve,'' said
public relations executive Marc L. Apter, whose diverse clients
include State Farm Insurance and the West African nation of Togo.
   Apter was lobbying the lobbyists for business Thursday when more
than 100 members of the league _ representing special-interest
groups from Mobil Oil Corp. to the National Rural Electric
Cooperative Association to Girl Scouts of the USA _ held their
annual conference here.
   They dutifully attended lobbying workshops on taxes, labor
unions, the environment, foreign trade and Medicare. But they
seemed happiest when they were schmoozing over cocktails and lunch.
   It's such idle chatter that sometimes yields valuable tips and
contacts in Washington's network of influence salesmen.
   Among these garrulous birds, the usual plumage seems to be dark
blue suit, white shirt and red or yellow ``power tie.'' Hair is
trimmed tidily short. Laughter is boisterous, but when the talk
turns serious, lobbyists crouch forward from the waist and stare in
each other's eyes.
   Their hands flutter in the air, jingle pocket change, brush
foreheads, clamp onto hips, yank at noses. With hardly a break in
the chatter or a sideways glance, they extract business cards from
coats or wallets _ already bulging with other people's business
cards _ to exchange for yet another.
   What makes a good lobbyist?
   Eugene F. Rowan has been one for 15 years. He was J.C. Penney's
vice president for federal government relations until he retired a
few years ago to become a free-lance lobbyist, using an office in
the Washington law firm of Patton, Boggs &amp; Blow. His biggest client
is the National Association of Chain Drug Stores, whose president
is former Nixon White House press secretary Ronald Ziegler.
   ``First of all, you've got to have credibility. Your word must
be something that a member of Congress can rely on. You can't
misrepresent anything,'' Rowan said.
   ``It's crucial that you know your subject matter. And you have
to be able to live and deal with the culture of Capitol Hill. Most
of the time you don't control the agenda or the timetable, which
frustrates a lot of business executives. Availability is important.
You only see Sen. Sorghum when he wants to see you.
   ``You have to be a good salesperson, really. You try to make eye
contact and keep it. It's important to be natural. No poses or
role-playing or backslapping. They are very good at seeing through
that kind of thing.''
   Rowan deftly snatched a business card from his overstuffed
wallet. ``There's nothing worse than being caught on the Hill
without a card,'' he said.
   In a room full of conservative neckties, Rowan was the only
lobbyist who wore a bow tie.
   Was this part of his shtick?
   ``No,'' he replied. ``I can't spill gravy on this tie.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
