<FIRST>u w AM-Baker-Missiles 1stLd-Writethru a0707 05-18 0704</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Baker-Missiles, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0707,680</SECOND>
<HEAD>Baker Says He Will Try To Bridge Gap With West Germans</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: to UPDATE with Kohl-Bush conversation and report of German flexibility,
INSERT two grafs after 7th pvs, `We would...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III said
Wednesday he wanted to reach an accommodation with West Germany
over nuclear missiles, but insisted the weapons were an essential
deterrent to Soviet attack.
   Baker took the hard-line stance as he awaited the arrival of
West German Defense Minister Gerhard Stoltenberg, who was headed
here from Bonn for meetings with Defense Secretary Dick Cheney on
Thursday and Baker on Friday.
   Stoltenberg also will meet with Brent Scowcroft, the national
security assistant to President Bush. Scowcroft has expressed
concern about lowering NATO's nuclear capability.
   Baker indicated he did not intend to give ground and said he
hoped the West German official would bring ``an evolving position''
from Bonn.
   The West German government, supported by several of the NATO
allies, is pushing for negotiations between the United States and
the Soviet Union to reduce and possibly eliminate nuclear missiles
on both sides with a range of up to 300 miles.
   Baker said the missiles have helped keep the peace with the
Soviet Union for nearly 40 years and were essential as a deterrent
to war.
   ``We would like to find a way to bridge this gap,'' Baker said
on a U.S. government-sponsored telecast to Western Europe. ``But we
want to find a way that is consistent with maintaining our resolve,
with maintaining our will, with maintaining our strength, with
maintaining the strategy of flexible response which has provided
Europe with peace for 40 years.''
   West German Chancellor Helmut Kohl telephoned President Bush on
Tuesday, White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said. Although
Fitzwater gave no details of the call, The New York Times reported
in its Thursday editions that Kohl indicated his government was
willing to take a more flexible approach on the missile question.
   The newspaper, citing unidentified Western diplomats, said that
under the new approach, talks on short-range missiles might not
begin until significant progress was made in reducing conventional
arms in Europe, where the Soviet bloc has a large advantage.
   The West German government also is resisting a joint
U.S.-British effort to more than triple the range of Lance missiles
to just below 300 miles. All U.S. and Soviet missiles with ranges
between 300 and 3,000 miles were banned under a 1987 treaty.
   The U.S.-built Lances now can hit targets from about 75 miles.
Most of the 88 launchers, carrying about 700 single-warhead
missiles, are based in West Germany.
   Baker said he understood the West Germans' concern that their
country might become a battlefield in a tactical nuclear war
between East and West. But he said the Warsaw Pact had a big edge
in short-range nuclear weapons and had been making them more potent.
   ``Nuclear weapons are part of a defensive strategy,'' Baker said
of NATO's rocket arsenal. ``We ought to move very, very slowly
before we abandon that strategy.''
   Under questioning from West European correspondents, Baker did
not predict a resolution of the rift with West Germany before the
summit meeting is held in Brussels May 29-30. Bush will attend with
the leaders of the 15 other NATO governments.
   Baker said he hoped Stoltenberg would bring some new approaches
from Bonn.
   ``For the most part,'' Baker said, ``we'll be listening to
Gerhard Stoltenberg when he comes to Washington to see what he has
to say. We are very interested in what we hope will be an evolving
position by the West German government on this issue.''
   At the White House, presidential spokesman Marlin Fitzwater
said, ``We're still discussing the matter. We continue to hope that
we could reach some kind of agreement before the NATO summit; but
if not, we'll discuss it there or later.''
   He added, ``We don't want to speculate on what we might accept.
Our position has always been: first, we should proceed with the
conventional arms talks until we can achieve a parity, and then
we'll discuss or address the situation with regards to SNF. We are
not prepared to go beyond that at this point.''
</TEXT>
