<FILEID>AP-NR-05-18-89 0153EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-HUDProbe     05-18 0716</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-HUD Probe,720</SECOND>
<HEAD>Consultant Defends Fees Earned Under Embattled Housing Program</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENISE CABRERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Consultants who collected big fees for work
connected to a federally subsidized housing program told a
congressional panel the payments were justified, as senators
complained the program was riddled with improprieties.
   Former Massachusetts Sen. Edward Brooke, who received $183,000
for consulting work on two low-income housing projects in
Massachusetts, told a Senate committee Wednesday that he ``had no
special pipeline'' into the Department of Housing and Department to
influence contract awards under the housing program.
   Brooke also said it was ``understandable'' that developers
sought assistance in competing for financing under the Moderate
Rehabilitation Program, which he said was under-funded.
   Brooke and three other consultants appeared Wednesday before the
Banking Committee. It was the first time they had testified
publicly since they were named in a highly-critical report by the
Department of Housing and Urban Development's inspector general.
   The report found the low-income housing renovation program was
poorly managed and its undocumented selection process was riddled
with favoritism.
   The document alleged developers and housing authorites seeking
money for projects selected consultants who did little more for the
unusually high fees than make a few phone calls or write to their
former colleagues.
   ``Not only did I advise clients on HUD policies and procedures,
but on state and local programs, and tax and housing legislative
changes affecting low-income housing development and financing,''
said Brooke.
   ``There were not only a few calls but dozens and dozens of calls
over a period of four years,'' he said.
   Brooke said he had ``no influence in the (Reagan)
administration'' and hadn't known any of the HUD officials he dealt
with before he met or spoke with them in connection with the two
projects.
   Committee Chairman Donald Riegle, D-Mich., called the consultant
contracts a form of ``looting'' that demonstrated a disturbing
pattern at HUD.
   ``I want to find out about every project that was done in the
country. I don't want just the tip of the iceberg,'' said Riegle,
calling for a review of all projects awarded contracts through the
program during the 1984-1988 period covered by the inspector
general's audit.
   The inspector general said no evidence of criminal wrongdoing
has been discovered in the audit, but the report has been referred
to the Justice Department for review.
   Housing Secretary Jack Kemp last month suspended 1989 funding
for the program following release of the inspector general's report
and said Tuesday that he would restart the program next month and
issue new guidelines.
   Meanwhile, Sen. Daniel Moynihan, D-N.Y., on Wednesday introduced
a bill that would establish regulations for a competitive award
process, give the housing secretary greater control over the use of
low-income housing tax credit and provide for annual updating of
the handbook used by field offices that administer the program.
   Judith S. Siegel, a Rhode Island developer who paid former
Interior Secretary James Watt $300,000 as a consultant for a
project in Essex, Md., complained that some of the information in
the inspector general's report was ``misleading'' and ``presented
out of context.''
   ``Mr. Watt did not receive a consulting fee for merely making a
few phone calls,'' said Siegel, adding that the Maryland project
had been ``in the state's pipeline'' two years before she hired
Watt.
   Siegel conceded that Watt ``could drive the federal bureaucracy
when it needed to be driven'' but said his fees ``were not paid
with any federal, state, or local funds.''
   Sen. Richard Shelby called the developer-consultant arrangements
``a situation of bare unadulterated influence-peddling'' for which
the taxpayers ultimately paid.
   The Alabama Democrat also took great pains to ensure that he was
not confused with a consultant of the same name who appeared before
the panel and defended the fees that he received.
   That Richard Shelby, political director of the Republican
Senatorial Committee, earned $442,000 in fees as a consultant to a
renovation project in Dade County, Fla., according to the inspector
general's report.
   Another consultant, Fred Bush, who has been nominated by
President Bush as ambassador to Luxembourg, admitted he ``did not
bring very much'' to the project in Puerto Rico for which he served
as a consultant. The consultant, who was paid $195,000 and still is
due another $65,000, is not related to the president.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
