<FILEID>AP-NR-05-18-89 0223EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Panama-Poor     05-18 0585</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Panama-Poor,0607</SECOND>
<HEAD>Poor Panamanians Feel Impotent</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Panama</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Many in the poor neighborhood of San
Felipe say they are suffering the wrath of the government for
giving a resounding ``No!'' to Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega in the
presidential election.
   ``The general and the Defense Forces are really angry with us
down here,'' said a man with two gold teeth enjoying a soft drink
in a small grocery store.
   ``They thought they bought our loyalty with contraband,
providing imported beer cheaply for us to sell, allowing drugs and
prostitition. Then when it came time to vote, everybody voted
against them.''
   The opposition, which says it won the May 7 election, called a
general strike for Wednesday to protest the government's
nullification of the balloting.
   But the strike did not take hold in San Felipe, Chorrillo or
Santa Ana _ three contiguous poor neighborhoods, where many
residents said they felt powerless after their vote was thrown out.
   ``We creamed the government here,'' said a woman in a worn
T-shirt and skirt, smiling broadly. ``Now there are more cops and
`toads' than ever.''
   Paid government informants are known as ``sapos,'' or toads.
   Nilda, who asked to be identified only by her first name,
indicated with her chin two police officers who stood across the
street watching.
   ``If they come in here to bother us after you leave I'm going to
tell them I love Duque more than his own wife and that I was
defending Noriega to the foreign press,'' she said, referring to
Carlos Duque, Noriega's hand-picked presidential candidate.
   ``Otherwise they arrest you and charge you $300 that you don't
have.''
   The strike slowed commercial and industrial activity slightly
elsewhere, but appeared to have been an overall failure.
   ``Businesses like mine buy today to sell today or tomorrow, a
little at a time. We don't have the effect of the big department
stores or wholesalers,'' said the grocery store owner, who wore a
white apron and a blue baseball cap with the Ford Motor Co. logo.
   The owner and four patrons said Noriega should pack up and get
out.
   ``He personally has become the problem,'' said the man drinking
the soft drink, who gave his name as Luis. ``He makes himself out
to be the big nationalist, but the country doesn't mean squat to
him. He only cares about his rackets.''
   In San Miguelito, another working class neighborhood on the
opposite edge of the capital, four women stood on the crest of a
rise in the road banging pots and pans to express their displeasure
with Noriega's continued rule.
   Irsa Herrera stooped to pick up some rocks and sticks and put
them in the road.
   ``We are going to block the streets,'' she declared. ``We want
Noreiga to go as soon as possible.''
   The other women added some spindly branches to the would-be
barricade.
   At the grocer's shop in San Felipe, Nilda said Panamanians could
do little to oust Noriega and would simply have to ``wait until he
makes up his mind to leave.''
   ``We're not fighters,'' Luis said. ``Panamanians are not the
kind of people to take to the streets to confront police and
soldiers.''
   There has been talk of holding new elections for a successor to
Manuel Solis Palma, the figurehead president whose term ends Sept.
1.
   ``But no one will vote if they have new elections,'' said Nilda.
``For what? So we can win again and they can annul it again?''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
