<FILEID>AP-NR-05-18-89 0623EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>d e BC-Theater     05-18 0326</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Theater,0340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lewis J. Stadlen Portrays S.J. Perelman</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: No PMs Planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In delivery, timing and wordplay-based humor,
but not in tone of voice, Lewis J. Stadlen's portrayal of humorist
S.J. Perelman sounds like Groucho Marx.
   Groucho talking might have been interesting for an evening at
off-Broadway's Cherry Lane Theater but ``S.J. Perelman in Person,''
which opened there Wednesday night, isn't very theatrical, to put
it kindly. Its high points are a slide show of Perelman's friends
during Hollywood screenwriting days and the remembered witticisms
of Dorothy Parker and George S. Kaufman. Its point of least
interest is Perelman helplessly putting together a child's truck on
Christmas Eve.
   The set, by Wes Peters, is a study painted brown. Of course
Perelman makes a pun of being ``in a brown study _ much like this
one.''
   Perelman, who died in 1979 at 75, wrote essays and parodies,
many for The New Yorker. They were collected in some 20 books. The
writer obviously loved to use words unexpectedly.
   ``I was reared and backhanded in Providence,'' Stadlen says. ``I
had to come to New York to be affronted.'' On the telephone, he
says, ``My friend, and I call you that in all insincerity.'' ``You
follow your own star,'' he intones inspiringly. ``I'll follow Hedy
Lamarr.''
   Bob Shanks wrote the one-man play based on Perelman's writings.
Shanks, an Indiana University graduate, has been an ABC programming
vice president and now is managing director of a television network
in Australia. He has written two books about TV and a novel. Ann
Shanks directed.
   Stadlen visually makes Perelman a bespectacled,
nondescript-looking man who brags about flamboyant female
encounters. His body language is good, despite the mustache,
particularly when he portrays a stripper removing a long glove.
   The actor's Broadway debut was as Groucho Marx in the musical
``Minnie's Boys,'' the memory of which probably worked against him
in portraying S.J. Perelman.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
