<FIRST>u w AM-US-Cambodia     05-18 0300</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Cambodia,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Aid Ban Shelved at Least Temporarily</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GENE KRAMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate Foreign Relations Committee on
Wednesday rejected a move to ban arms aid to any group in Cambodia
linked to the Khmer Rouge, which is part of a three-party
resistance coalition led by Prince Norodom Sihanouk.
   The amendment to the annual State Department authorization bill
had been proposed by Sen. Claiborne Pell, D-R.I., chairman of the
panel and was opposed by the Bush administration, which support's
Sihanouk's resistance effort against Vietnamese forces occupying
Cambodia.
   The six nations of the Association of Southeast Asian Nations
also registered strong opposition to such a ban.
   Sen. Alan Cranston, D-Calif., agreed before the bipartisan vote
to hold hearings in his Asian and Pacific Affairs subcommittee on
potential aid to the Cambodian resistance. Cranston said the issue
of Sihanouk's ties to the Khmer Rouge could be resolved in this
week's Sino-Soviet summit in Beijing.
   Beijing has been supporting the Khmer Rouge while Moscow backs
Vietnam, the country that invaded Cambodia in 1978 to end Khmer
Rouge rule and has declared it will end its 10-year occupation in
September.
   If the Khmer Rouge lose their Chinese support as a result of
decisions at the Beijing summit, ``it would be folly for us to
intervene ...'' said Cranston.
   The Khmer Rouge are blamed for more than 1 million deaths during
their 1975-78 rule over Cambodia.
   David Lambertson, deputy assistant secretary of state, told the
committee on Wednesday that the administration has not made a
decision yet on whether to seek lethal aid to Sihanouk's forces.
   Asked about a recent statement by Vice President Dan Quayle that
both overt and covert aid were under study, Lambertson assured the
senators no moves would be made without informing members of
Congress.
</TEXT>
