<FIRST>d a PM-BRF--TimeCapsule     05-18 0158</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Time Capsule,0164</SECOND>
<HEAD>Can't Open Time Capsule</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT WAYNE, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The contents of a 124-year-old time
capsule buried near the corner of Trinity Episcopal Church will
remain a mystery.
   The time capsule was to be opened Saturday at the climax of a
celebration of 150 years of an Episcopal presence in the city.
   Those plans had to be scrapped.
   ``We can't get it out. The wall would come tumbling down if we
pulled it out,'' said the Rev. Craig Kallio, pastor of the
450-member church. ``We won't be able to get the time capsule out
until we destroy the building.''
   That may be a long wait. The church is on the National Register
of Historic Places.
   Members laid the cornerstone and buried the box on April 15,
1865, the day after Abraham Lincoln was assassinated.
   No one considered digging it out until this year.
   ``We're just curious to find out what's in it,'' Kallio said.
</TEXT>
