<DOCNO> AP890518-0026 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-18-89 0257EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Alar     05-18 0498</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Alar,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senators Move to Ban Use of Chemical Alar on Apples and Other Foods</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX7</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four senators want Congress to ban the use of
the Alar on apples, even though apple growers say they intend to
halt application of the controversial chemical because of fears by
consumers.
   ``If we do not ban Alar from the market, American consumers, in
increasing numbers, will ban apples from their diet,'' Sen. Joe
Lieberman, D-Conn., told a news conference Wednesday where the bill
was unveiled.
   The bill would ban the use of the chemical manufactured by
Uniroyal on foods, effective as soon as the president affixed his
signature. Besides apples, Alar also is commonly used on grapes,
cherries and peanuts.
   The chemical, which enhances the appearance of apples and keeps
them from spoiling for longer periods, has been shown to cause
cancer in lab animals. It still could be used on commercially grown
flowers under the bill.
   The Food and Drug Administration estimated on March 16 that Alar
was used on 10 percent of the nation's apple supply.
   Sen. John Warner, R-Va., indicated he would not wait for the
measure to go through committee but instead would attempt to attach
it to another bill that is nearing floor action. ``The train is
under way,'' he declared.
   Other sponsors are Sens. Harry Reid, D-Nev., and Donald W.
Riegle Jr., D-Mich.
   There were initial denials from the Environmental Protection
Agency that Alar constitutes a health risk for consumers, but apple
sales have plunged in recent months amid concern about the chemical.
   Apples producers are facing a $100 million loss ``on the raw
crop'' this year as a result of unfavorable reports concerning Alar
and there has been an additional 30 percent drop in apple juice
sales, according to Derl I. Derr, president of the International
Apple Institute, based in McLean, Va.
   Derr said his group, composed of 23 state organizations
representing an estimated 90 percent of the nation's 15,000
commercial growers, favors taking Alar off the market but not by
legislative means. He said reducing the allowable amount to zero
would require an EPA finding that Alar poses an ``imminent hazard.''
   ``And if you think we have a bad market now, you should see what
it would be like then,'' Derr said. He said his group is urging
growers to stop using the compound and is hoping Uniroyal will
voluntarily halt sales.
   Earlier this week, Derr said apple growers are already planning
to eliminate Alar. ``By September of this year, the already low
levels of Alar will be reduced to virtually zero. Simply, the U.S.
apple industry is not going to use Alar.''
   None of the four senators is a member of the Senate Agriculture
Committee, which for years has balked at tough farm chemical
regulation recommended by environmentalists and consumer advocates.
   A similar bill was quietly introduced in the House earlier this
year, although no action has been taken on it.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
