<FIRST>r w PM-Wright-Poll     05-18 0381</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wright-Poll,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gallup Poll Says People Don't Care About Wright Probe</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Wright Probe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LISA M. HAMM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The ethics investigation of House Speaker Jim
Wright has attracted little interest among the public, despite its
dominance of newspaper front pages, says a Gallup Poll.
   Instead, people are more interested in the Alaska oil spill.
Sixty percent of those polled in a ``Newstrack'' survey released
Wednesday said they did not even know who Wright was, and only 15
percent of respondents said they were following the ethics
investigation of the Texas Democrat ``very closely.''
   The poll was conducted for the Los Angeles-based Times Mirror
media company.
   The only news story among seven selections that attracted more
apathy than Wright's tribulations was the resignation of Japanese
Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita in the wake of financial scandal.
   Only 12 percent of those polled could even identify Takeshita as
Japan's former leader, and just 6 percent of respondents said they
were following developments ``very closely.''
   But the Exxon Valdez's spill of 11 million gallons of oil into
Alaska's Prince William Sound has piqued the interest of the
public, the survey said. Fifty-two percent of respondents said they
were following oil spill developments ``very closely'' while 37
percent said they were watching ``fairly closely.''
   In fact, 36 percent of respondents said the Exxon Valdez
incident was the news story they were following most closely.
   On the other hand, 30 percent of respondents said they were
following the Wright probe ``not at all closely,'' and 43 percent
said the same of the Takeshita resignation.
   The seven news stories about which respondents were polled
included the Wright probe, the oil spill, the Takeshita
resignation, the alleged rape and beating by a youth gang of a
jogger in New York's Central Park, the Oliver North trial, the
Supreme Court's hearing on arguments in a Missouri abortion case,
and the explosion and fire that killed 47 sailors on the USS Iowa.
   The telephone survey of 1,239 adults was conducted from May 4-7
and had a margin of error of plus or minus 4 percentage points.
   The survey conducted by the Gallup Organization is the first of
a regular series to be done for the Times Mirror Center for Press
and Public Policy here.
</TEXT>
