<FIRST>r w PM-Budget-Glance     05-18 0266</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Budget-Glance,260</SECOND>
<HEAD>With PM-Budget Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are highlights of the fiscal 1990 federal
budget:
   Overall spending _ $1.165 trillion.
   Overall revenues _ $1.065 trillion.
   Deficit _ $99.7 billion.
   Deficit reduction _ Counts $28 billion in savings, roughly
evenly divided between spending restraint and new receipts.
   Taxes _ $5.3 billion in additional collections, specific taxes
to be determined later. Also, $500 million is expected from
stricter enforcement by the Internal Revenue Service.
   Other revenues _ $2.7 billion in higher user fees and $5.7
billion in asset sales, details still to be decided.
   Entitlements _ $8.3 billion in claimed savings from programs
that automatically pay benefits to qualified recipients. Of this,
$2.3 billion would come from Medicare, probably by restraining
payments to doctors and hospitals. In addition, $1.9 billion would
come from agriculture, $1.8 billion by moving the Postal Service
off-budget, $1.1 billion from federal pension and other programs,
$496 million from sales of veterans housing loans and $477 million
by taking credit from unused food stamps.
   Defense _ $299.2 billion, compared to $296.7 billion this year.
   Science and Space _ $14.1 billion, up from $12.7 billion this
year.
   Environment _ $17.4 billion, up from $16.8 billion.
   Agriculture _ $15 billion, down from $19.2 billion.
   Transportation _ $29 billion, up from $28.1 billion.
   Education _ $38.9 billion, up from $36.6 billion.
   Health _ $56 billion, up from $49.9 billion.
   Income security _ $145.6 billion, up from $137.2 billion.
   Veterans _ $30 billion, up from $29.6 billion.
   Law enforcement _ $10.1 billion, up from $9.1 billion.
   Foreign Affairs _ $16.7 billion, up from $11.5 billion.
</TEXT>
