<FIRST>r i PM-Portugal-Revolutionary     05-18 0349</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Portugal-Revolutionary,0363</SECOND>
<HEAD>Freed Revolutionary Welcomed Home by Fireworks and Friends</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OEIRAS, Portugal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Portugal's best-known revolutionary,
Otelo Saraiva de Carvalho, was greeted by cheering neighbors and
friends when he returned home today after spending five years in
prison.
   It was Saraiva de Carvalho who masterminded the 1974 revolution
that toppled almost 50 years right-wing dictatorship in Portugal.
   The Supreme Court of Justice ordered him free Wednesday after
throwing out his May 1987 conviction on charges of leading a
terrorist group in the early 1980s that pledged to seek ``a halt to
the unbridled advance of capitalism.''
   The court had accepted Saraiva de Carvalho's appeal that
authorities violated the constitution by making him await trial for
longer than the three-year maximum stipulated by law.
   The one-time chief of Portugal's revolutionary security police
had been serving a 15-year sentence.
   Saraiva de Carvalho _ known throughout Portugal simply as Otelo
_ was arrested in 1984 on charges of leading the left-wing group
Popular Forces of April 25, which was blamed for terrorist attacks
and at least 15 killings.
   Hundreds of supporters shouted ``Long live April 25!'' as
Saraiva de Carvalho emerged Wednesday from the prison in Tomar,
about 90 miles north of Lisbon. That was the date of the 1974
overthrow.
   More than 100 well-wihers set off firecrackers and cheered when
he arrived by car early today at his family's modest apartment in
this Lisbon suburb.
   Before entering the house to greet his wife and daughter, he
embraced two former revolutionary captains, Vitor Alves and Mario
Tome.
   Saraiva de Carvalho regularly wore his lieutenant colonel's army
uniform while in prison and consistently protested his innocence,
saying, ``Mine was without doubt a political trial.''
   Twice a presidential candidate, he was jailed in 1975 for an
alleged role in a failed left-wing countercoup but later released.
   RTP state television reported that 28 members of the Popular
Forces jailed with him also received notice of release.
   An additional 17 prisoners, in jail for less than three years,
will not be released, the Portuguese news agency Lusa reported.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
