<FILEID>AP-NR-05-18-89 0305EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-North-Contras     05-18 0503</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-North-Contras,0517</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report: More Signs of US-Honduran Deal on Contra Aid</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New doubts have been cast on Bush administration
claims that there was no deal between the Reagan administration and
Honduras on aid to the Nicaragua Contras, according to a report
published today.
   The New York Times says classified documents describe similar
dealings at the time with Guatemala and Costa Rica.
   The Times cites a classified December 1985 memo written by
Oliver North to his boss at the National Security Council, John M.
Poindexter. Poindexter was about to visit Honduras and meet with
Gen. Walter Lopez, head of the Honduran military.
   The memo, which earlier was released in heavily edited form by
the congressional committees which investigated the Iran-Contra
affair, referred to a decision by the Honduran military to cut off
the delivery of weapons to the rebels, The Times said.
   North wrote: ``From previous meetings with Lopez, it is obvious
that the Hondurans perceive the U.S.G. (United States government)
is `using' Honduras for its own political ends. They have learned
that we withhold our assistance ... in order to force concessions
from them. They are now using this same tactic with us as a means
of insuring that the U.S.G will `come through' for them.
   ``Lopez and his colonels recognize that the only leverage they
have over us is their covert support for the Nicaraguan
resistance,'' the memo said.
   Another document cited by The Times was written by Alan Fiers,
chief of the CIA's Central America Task Force. It was directed to
then-CIA Director William J. Casey and dated Oct. 23, 1986, shortly
before Congress voted to allow the agency to resume assistance to
the Contras.
   Fiers reported on a trip to Honduras, Guatemala and Costa Rica
to discuss logistical help for the Contra aid effort.
   ``The Hondurans ... agreed to fully support the program and to
allow supplies to begin moving as scheduled,'' Fiers wrote. ``They
were very clear as to what they seek in return: support for the
purchase of advanced aircraft, with those aircraft arriving as soon
as possible (within six months).''
   Fiers added: ``We must be as responsive as we need to insure
this cooperation, yet at the same time remain within the bounds of
propriety.''
   The Times said Fiers also wrote that in Guatemala, the CIA would
be paying for ``the Guatemalan program of internal support to
Nicaraguan political parties and working with them in structuring
this program.''
   ``In return for President (Vinicio) Cerezo's support, we will be
assisting him in establishing a public relations-media operation
designed to strengthen his image and democracy in Guatemala,'' the
memo said.
   Fiers wrote that officials in Costa Rica had deep concerns about
the Contra program but had agreed to support it ``politically and
diplomatically by taking the lead in criticizing Nicaragua and
insisting on a democratic form of government.''
   The memo added that the officials ``spent considerable time
discussing their financial problems, and asked for U.S.G. help in
negotiating a rescheduling agreement with U.S. banks.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890518-0035 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-18-89 0326EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-WashingtoninBrief     05-18 0520</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Washington in Brief,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gas Decontrol Bill Wins Senate Committee Approval</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Senate panel has moved the energy industry
one step closer to a long-sought prize it says will benefit
consumers as well as commerce.
   The Senate Energy and Natural Resources, by a 17-2 vote,
approved legislation Wednesday to lift remaining price controls on
natural gas by 1993,
   Experts generally agree that natural gas prices would be
unlikely to rise immediately in reaction to ending price controls,
since the market price currently is well below the controlled
price. Many industry officials predict, however, that growing
demand for gas in the 1990s would likely push prices substantially
higher.
   The full Senate may consider the bill, which is strongly
supported by the Bush administration, as early as next week. The
House passed a nearly identical bill last month with virtually no
dissent.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<NOTE>Bush Won't Block Possible Foreign Acquisition</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush has decided not to block the
possible foreign acquisition of Westinghouse Electric Corp.'s
interest in a joint venture with a European company.
   Bush made his decision after an investigation by an inter-agency
committee headed by Treasury Secretary Nicholas Brady, the
administration announced Wednesday.
   The latest review involved a joint venture between Westinghouse
and ASEA Brown Boveri LTD (ABB), a manufacturing firm based in
Switzerland. The joint venture, known as Westinghouse-ABB Power T&amp;D
Co., was created earlier in the year to manufacture and sell
high-voltage electrical transmission equipment.
   The president has the power to block foreign acquisitions of
American companies if the sales would endanger national security.
</TEXT>
