<FILEID>AP-NR-05-18-89 0518EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-AlcoholLawsuit     05-18 0499</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Alcohol Lawsuit,0514</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jim Beam Cleared in Birth Defect Lawsuit</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Candance is cq.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATIA BLACKBURN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jim Beam Brands Co. was cleared of negligence in
a lawsuit by a woman who said her son suffered birth defects
because she drank its whiskey during pregnancy.
   Harold and Candance Thorp of Seattle were seeking about $4
million in damages for lifetime assistance for their 4-year-old son
Michael, who is retarded and deformed.
   Mrs. Thorp, 39, testified she was an alcoholic who drank up to a
fifth of Jim Beam a day during her pregnancy. But she and her
husband insisted she would have stopped drinking had the bottles
carried a warning label for pregnant women.
   ``We're obviously disappointed with the verdict, but the jury
system operates,'' said their lawyer, Barry Epstein.
   Epstein said the U.S. District Court jury's verdict was not a
total loss. He said he didn't think Wednesday's decision would set
a precedent for similar cases.
   ``We feel that this litigation has created an awareness in the
public that, if it saves one child, it will all be worth it,'' he
said. ``We hope as a result of this case ... that (news of) the
dangers of alcohol will be spread far and wide.''
   He said no decision had been made on an appeal.
   Shannon Stafford, Jim Beam's chief lawyer, said he was
``obviously pleased'' but declined further comment.
   During the trial, Epstein had argued that Beam had an obligation
to warn the public about the health risks of alcohol consumption by
pregnant women.
   But witnesses for Beam said Mrs. Thorp had been warned
repeatedly by relatives and friends about the dangers of drinking
alcohol while pregnant and that she and other alcoholics would not
have heeded a warning label.
   Beam also contended that the boy's problems were caused by
heredity and neglect, not by his mother's alcohol abuse.
   The decision ``seemed so obvious,'' said Staci Gilbreth, a
22-year-old juror who had a baby in December. ``I was surprised
they were suing Jim Beam.''
   ``They could have sued everyone,'' said Geraldine Jackson, 32,
another juror, who referred to testimony that Mrs. Thorp had been
seen drinking beer in bars several times during her pregnancy.
   Jurors said they decided the danger of alcohol to developing
fetuses was common knowledge at the time of Mrs. Thorp's pregnancy
and said that was a factor in their decision to deny damages.
   About 1 percent of the infants born in the United States each
year, or 35,000 babies, are born with fetal alcohol syndrome. The
syndrome was identified in the United States by physicians at the
University of Washington in Seattle in 1973, although a French
doctor had pinpointed it several years earlier in France.
   Symptoms include slow growth, central nervous system impairment,
hyperactivity, mental retardation and distorted facial
characteristics.
   Starting in November, a new federal law will require all
alcoholic beverage containers to carry warnings about birth defects
and other health hazards related to drinking.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
