<FIRST>r i PM-NorthernIreland     05-18 0470</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Northern Ireland,0483</SECOND>
<HEAD>Local Elections Vote May Show Whether Moderates Gain Ground</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: First results expected about 9 a.m. EDT</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCUS ELIASON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Local elections may yield clues
to whether moderates have gained ground in the wake of a string of
bungled Irish Republican Army attacks.
   Counting of the votes in Wednesday's balloting began this
morning, but the province's complex system of proportional
representation meant first results were not expected for several
hours, and the final tally was due late Friday.
   Some 900 candidates are seeking the 566 seats on 26 district
councils in the British province where Protestants outnumber Roman
Catholics 3-to-2. Seventeen of the councils are controlled by the
two predominantly Protestant Unionist parties and the rest by
predominantly Catholic nationalist parties.
   Analysts say further gains by the nonviolent Social Democratic
and Labor Party, a moderate Catholic organization, at the cost of
Sinn Fein, the legal political arm of the outlawed IRA, may be due
to the IRA's bomb and bullet campaign to end British rule.
   IRA attacks have lately been claiming a number of so-called
innocent victims _ civilians not involved with the security forces.
   In the latest embarrassment to Sinn Fein, an IRA bomb attached
to a Belfast telegraph pole left a 3-year-old Catholic girl in
hospital with shrapnel in her foot.
   As voters went to the polls Wednesday, the headline in The Irish
News, the province's leading Catholic newspaper, said: ``BLOOD FROM
A BABY SIGNALS PROVO HORROR.'' Provo is a nickname for the IRA.
   The Social Democratic and Labor Party has posted some gains
since the November 1985 Anglo-Irish Agreement that gave the Irish
government a consultative role in the governing of Northern
Ireland. London and Dublin hoped the agreement would cut the ground
from under Sinn Fein.
   The mainly Catholic IRA wants to unite Northern Ireland with the
95 percent Catholic Republic of Ireland under socialist rule.
   On the Protestant side, the hard-line Democratic Unionist Party
faces allegations that former allies in a shadowy movement called
Ulster Resistance plotted to swap stolen missile technology from a
Belfast arms factory for South African guns.
   Ulster Resistance was formed to fight the Anglo-Irish Agreement
and was associated with Democratic Unionist Party leader Rev. Ian
Paisley, who says these links were subsequently severed.
   Also discomforting to the Unionist parties is a renewed outbreak
of sectarian killings by Protestant gunmen, the latest of which
claimed the life of a Catholic carpenter in Belfast on Monday.
   Malachy Trainor, 34, was buried Wednesday in his home town of
Kilkeel, and in his eulogy, Bishop Cahal Daly blamed the murder on
``the creeping oil slick of sectarianism.''
   He said many recent murders stemmed from ``plain, old-fashioned,
unreconstructed anti-Roman Catholic bigotry, based on outmoded
theologies long since left far behind by world Protestantism.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
