<FIRST>d a PM-BRF--StubbornPony     05-18 0189</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Stubborn Pony,0194</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pony Has to be Sedated for Removal from School</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ASHTABULA, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A stubborn pony brought to a third-floor
science classroom was trapped for five hours and had to be sedated
twice before firemen could carry it from the high school building.
   ``The pony went up the steps readily but would not come down
again,'' Fire Lt. Rick Balog said Wednesday.
   The 400-pound pony named Penny was finally freed Wednesday night
when 10 firemen and veterinarian William Lake, of Jefferson,
carried the sedated animal downstairs in a basket-like stretcher.
Balog said it took two tries to sedate Penny.
   ``The problem wasn't the pony's weight but the fact that she
wanted to kick like a bucking bronco,'' Balog said. ``We got a few
bruised shins, believe me.''
   Balog said Penny attended classes at Ashtabula High School all
day as part of a student's project for science courses. He said
students, teachers and administrators discovered at the end of the
day that Penny violently refused to walk down stairs.
   ``We don't do animal rescues, but it was hard to refuse,'' he
said. ``They were begging us.''
