<FIRST>r a PM-DropoutGrants     05-18 0314</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dropout Grants,0327</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pepsi to Provide $4.5 Million for Scholarships, Tutoring</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Students at two high schools with high dropout
rates can earn extra scholarship money by keeping their grades up.
   The four-year $4.5 million pilot program at the schools in
Detroit and Dallas will provide scholarships for students who earn
C averages, have good attendance and avoid disciplinary problems,
Pepsi-Cola Co. officials said Wednesday.
   Fifty teachers chosen at each school to tutor and counsel
children will receive $1,000 each.
   The program was announced in assemblies this week at
Southwestern High School in Detroit and L.G. Pinkston High School
in Dallas.
   The company hopes to encourage students to set and meet goals,
and give them enough financial assistance after graduation to help
them succeed, said Craig Weatherup, president of Pepsi-Cola, a
division of Pepsico Inc.
   ``We hope this program will serve as a model for other
corporations because we need their involvement,'' he said.
``Continued failure to make the benefits of our economic system
available to all of our citizens would be disastrous.'' Michigan
officials welcomed Pepsi's interest, though they said the state
already guarantees college tuition help for students below poverty
level who graduate from high school.
   At Southwestern, whose students are 80 percent black or other
minorities, the dropout rate is about 33 percent.
   Pinkston has a 99 percent minority enrollment, with more than
half the students from impoverished homes. Twenty-one percent of
Pinkston's students dropped out last year.
   The program will let students earn scholarship credit of $250 a
semester, beginning in the 1989-90 school year.
   A senior graduating in 1990 could win $500 in assistance, while
a ninth grader could earn a $2,000 scholarship by the time of
graduation in 1993.
   The funds are for accredited education or for other training
such as vocational school.
   Each school will receive an additional grant of $4,000 for
administrative costs.
</TEXT>
