<FILEID>AP-NR-05-18-89 0608EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-CoolMicrochips     05-18 0466</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cool Microchips,0481</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Process Announced for Forming Microchip Components at Lower Temperatures</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL HOLMES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AUSTIN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new process for forming ultrathin
components of microchips eventually will allow significantly more
information to be stored on them, University of Texas researchers
say.
   They announced Wednesday that their process lowers by hundreds
of degrees the temperature at which thin layers of crystalline
silicon material _ the building blocks of microchips _ can be grown.
   Although the process won't be fully felt in the microelectronics
industry for a decade, university officials called it a major
breakthrough.
   A.F. Tasch, a developer of the process and a professor of
computer and electrical engineering, said using lower temperatures
for crystalline silicon growth would allow much smaller transistors
to be built and many more transistors to be put on a single
microchip.
   The result: a chip that could hold substantially more data while
remaining the same size.
   He called it a major step in paving the way for the
microelectronics industry to go ``from millions to billions of
devices on a single chip.''
   ``If you want to make integrated circuits that have greater
computing power or store more information, you have to make
transistors smaller and smaller,'' Tasch said.
   ``The industry ... is reaching a point where these transistor
structures we are using today cannot be shrunk any smaller.
   ``In order to come up with new transistor concepts which work at
even smaller dimensions, whatever you build has to be done with
lower temperatures.''
   Tasch and his University of Texas colleague, S.K. Banerjee,
worked with a team at the Research Triangle Institute in North
Carolina to develop the process.
   Traditionally, making microchips involves a series of steps at
temperatures often exceeding 1,400 degrees Fahrenheit. The new
process allows single-crystal growth at temperatures as low as 300
degrees Fahrenheit.
   Tasch said the old heat level has limited the number of
materials and the size of the transistors that can be combined on a
single chip.
   ``If you have high temperature treatment like that used in
traditional fabrication, you cannot maintain these small
dimensions,'' Tasch said. ``All the details get washed out. The
high-temperature process causes the materials to mix.''
   Shrinking the size and improving the capacity of computer chips
topped a list of 22 technologies designated by the U.S. government
in March as critical to national security.
   ``We're talking about the ability to store the equivalent
information in a few sets of encyclopedias on a future microchip
the size of your thumbnail. Such chips will handle all of this data
at supercomputer speeds,'' Tasch said.
   Tasch and his co-workers, who began their project about 2{ years
ago, are scheduled to present their findings at the Electronic
Materials Conference at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology
next month.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890518-0047 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-18-89 0507EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Markets     05-18 0299</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0311</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Continues to Gain, Nikkei Falls</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar gained for a sixth day and closed today
at an 18-month high against the yen, while the key index on the
Tokyo Stock Exchange fell.
   The dollar finished at 138.88 yen, up 1.18 yen from Wednesday's
137.70-yen close. It was the dollar's highest close since 138.55
yen on Oct. 30, 1987.
   The dollar, which now has gained 4.44 yen in six trading days,
opened today at 139.45 and ranged between 138.60 yen and 139.48 yen.
   Daiwa Securities trader Mitsuhiko Kinugasa attributed the
dollar's surge to an improvement in the U.S. trade deficit.
   The United States reported on Wednesday that the deficit in
March fell to $8.86 billion from $9.82 billion in February.
   The dollar fell from its opening level, however, on dollar
selling by speculative investors and the Bank of Japan, which has
intervened to support the yen, Kinugasa said. The central bank
reportedly sold about $1 billion. It does not comment publicly on
its intervention.
   Kinugasa said the market still was expecting a stronger dollar.
   On the stock exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected
issues, lost 136.12 points, or 0.40 percent, to close at 33,856.33.
It gained 66.00 points on Wednesday.
   Investors were selling spot shares mainly for arbitrage, but
afternoon purchases by speculative investors helped erase some of
the losses, said Genjiro Sasaki, a dealer with New Japan Securities
Co.
   ``The market lacked buying incentives largely due to the yen's
weakness on the foreign exchange market,'' he said.
   The yen's downward trend and uncertainties about a possible rise
in Japanese interest rates left investors unable to determine the
likely direction of trading, he said.
   Trading was thin, with first section volume estimated at 600
million shares, down from Wednesday's 800 million.
</TEXT>
