<FILEID>AP-NR-05-18-89 0610EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-CarverHonored     05-18 0568</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Carver Honored,0586</SECOND>
<HEAD>Memorial for Author Erected at School</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICHOLAS K. GERANIOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>YAKIMA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Raymond Carver was a poor student with poor
prospects when he graduated from Yakima High School in 1956.
   Now his stories are taught in English classes, and this week the
late author became only the second graduate of the school to be
honored with a permanent display.
   The other is former U.S. Supreme Court Justice William O.
Douglas, another maverick who rose to prominence from low
beginnings.
   ``It's not often that you have a graduate go on to receive world
recognition for his work as a writer,'' Linda Brown, an English
teacher who led the drive for a Carver memorial, said Wednesday.
   ``It's sad when we are not recognized more fully by our hometown
and school while alive,'' she said. ``But it's better late than
never.''
   Monday's dedication was attended by Carver's widow, poet Tess
Gallagher, of Port Angeles.
   ``I think the things that started him on the road started
here,'' Ms. Gallagher said.
   The homemade, wood-framed memorial to Carver, who died of cancer
at age 50 last year, contains a photograph, some of his poetry,
some of his fishing lures, a fountain pen, a white rose, and a
handwritten note with a premise for a story.
   ``Argument between couple but narrator only sees back of man's
head the whole time,'' the note says.
   In a temporary display at the library are Carver's high school
diploma and a senior yearbook showing a cleancut young man whose
only listed activity was working on the school paper as a junior.
   The actual school building that Carver attended was razed years
ago. Davis High School was built on the site.
   It is perhaps fitting that Carver's memorial is at a school that
has both the state's highest dropout rate, over 50 percent
according to state figures, and a reputation for innovative
education programs such as three-day single-topic seminars for the
entire student body.
   Ms. Brown said Carver's life illustrates that students who get
the best grades are not always the most talented, and that people
mature at different rates.
   ``Many of the kids who drop out of schools ... are gifted
kids,'' she said.
   Carver was born in Clatskanie, Ore., and grew up in Yakima. His
father worked in a lumber mill and his mother was a waitress.
   He moved to California after graduation and began to be
published a few years later while an undergraduate at Humboldt
State. He later was a janitor at a Sacramento hospital, and for a
decade was an alcoholic. He later taught at Syracuse University in
New York.
   Widespread critical acclaim didn't come until the 1970s, and it
was only in the 1980s that a major outpouring of his books
appeared. The latest ``A New Path To The Waterfall,'' is due out
soon.
   His works were translated into 20 languages and near the end of
his life he was widely regarded as one of the nation's finest
writers.
   His writings reflected the desperate underclass, caught in
dead-end jobs with few prospects. Many were inspired by his
impoverished youth in Yakima, one of the reasons a BBC television
crew was in town recently filming a documentary on his life.
   ``Carver's life in Yakima was bleak, perhaps, but it was still
his home,'' Ms. Brown said. ``Ray Carver characters are the people
I've met in Yakima.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
