<FIRST>r a PM-AgentsArrested     05-18 0468</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Agents Arrested,0486</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Veteran U.S. Drug Agents Held on Bribery Charges</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two federal drug agents who thought they had
developed a scheme to take money from drug traffickers found
themselves targeted by an elaborate sting, authorities said.
   Federal investigators said they caught the two longtime Drug
Enforcement Administration agents with help from a confidential
informant who posed as a drug trafficker.
   The arrests came five weeks after another Miami-based DEA agent
was arrested on drugs charges.
   Agents Drew Bunnell and Al Iglesias didn't know the man was
taking orders from the DEA's own internal investigation unit,
according to Tom Cash, the DEA's special agent in charge in Miami.
   Bunnell and Iglesias appeared Wednesday before federal
magistrate. Both were charged with bribery, a felony punishable by
up to five years in prison.
   Bunnell, assigned to the DEA office in Ecuador, was ordered held
without bond pending a full hearing Monday. His arraignment was
scheduled for May 30.
   Iglesias, of the DEA's Miami office, was ordered released on a
$500,000 personal surety bond. His arraignment was set for June 6.
   The informant told each agent he had a large sum of money given
to him by drug traffickers, and that the money was to be used to
buy and transport cocaine into the United States, Cash said.
   ``Proper procedure would require agents in possession of this
information to immediately open an investigation and conduct a
reverse sting operation to arrest the traffickers,'' Cash said.
   Instead, he said, the two agents told the informant that they
would not investigate if they could keep the money. In return,
Iglesias and Bunnel allegedly promised to protect the informant
against retaliation.
   Bunnell had nine years' experience with the DEA and Iglesias 14,
officials said.
   Bunnell was arrested near Miami International Airport, and
Iglesias was arrested at his Miami home, said Michael A. Pavlick, a
senior DEA inspector in Washington.
   Both agents were placed on administrative leave with pay, Cash
said.
   Authorities said the investigation began in July 1988, when the
confidential informant told the DEA he had met with Bunnell in
December 1987 and discussed stealing cocaine money.
   The DEA then began monitoring telephone calls between the
informant and Bunnell, authorities said. The informant led Bunnell
to believe he had taken $215,000 in cocaine traffickers' money,
authorities said.
   Bunnell received $7,000 before his arrest, but had expected to
get $100,000, authorities said. The informant also gave Bunnell's
wife $5,000, authorities said.
   Iglesias got $700 in cash and an $11,000 Rolex Presidential
wristwatch ``purchased from funds which Iglesias believed were
taken from the drug traffickers,'' Cash said.
   In the previous arrest, agent Jorge Villar was arrested in
mid-April on charges of conspiracy to distribute cocaine and
conspiring to commit bribery. He was arrested with a former
Metro-Dade police officer.
</TEXT>
