<FIRST>r p PM-Giuliani     05-18 0382</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Giuliani,0393</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Federal Prosecutor Announces Run for New York City Mayoralty</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CATHERINE CROCKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former federal prosecutor formally announced
his candidacy for mayor by promising to combat violent crime on the
city's streets and corruption in its offices.
   In announcing his bid for the Republican ticket Wednesday,
Rudolph W. Giuliani stressed his 5{ years as U.S. attorney in
Manhattan, a post he left in January.
   He said none of his rivals ``understands the justice system, and
the criminal justice system in particular, the way I do.''
   Giuliani, 44, said he would hire more police, increase jail
capacity and seek to reform the juvenile justice system. To handle
increased arrests, he would add court space and prosecutors.
   ``Now is the time to take back our city from the violent
criminals on the streets and the white-collar criminals in their
office suites, from the drug dealers in abandoned buildings and the
crooked politicians who have abandoned their oath of office,'' he
said.
   Giuliani, who won a racketeering conviction of once powerful
Democratic boss Stanley Friedman, said he would make the
elimination of corruption in city government a priority.
   As a GOP hopeful running in a city where registered Democrats
outnumber Republicans 5-1, Giuliani compared himself to Fiorello
LaGuardia, another Italian-American and Republican who faced
similar odds when he won the mayoralty in 1933.
   Giuliani pledged that he, like LaGuardia, would ``kick out an
old, tired and corrupt administration'' and ``restore to New York
honest, decent and effective government.''
   Polls have shown Giuliani would defeat Mayor Edward I. Koch,
Manhattan Borough President David Dinkins, former Metropolitan
Transportation Authority Chairman Richard Ravitch and city
Comptroller Harrison Goldin. The first three have declared their
candidacy for the Democratic nomination; Goldin's formal
announcement is expected next week.
   Koch said he is not discouraged by the polls because he is
confident that his 12-year tenure as mayor will attract voters. He
said Giuliani ``knows nothing about government.''
   Giuliani's first hurdle is the Republican primary in September,
when he faces a well-financed challenge from the cosmetics heir,
Ronald Lauder.
   Last month, Giuliani won the endorsement of the city's Liberal
Party to assure himself a place on the November ballot. The city's
last Republican mayor, John V. Lindsay, did the same.
</TEXT>
