<SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0596</SECOND>
<HEAD>20 Tornados Whip Texas; Snow Falls in Rockies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Snow fell in the Rockies and temperatures dipped to freezing in
the Pacific Northwest early today, while thunderstorms soaked parts
of Texas following a night in which more than 20 tornadoes whipped
through the state.
   One of Wednesday's tornados killed a woman in Jarrell, 40 miles
from Austin, and demolished 33 houses there. Three people were
swept to their deaths in swollen Texas creeks and 50 suffered
storm-related injuries.
   Thunderstorms lingered over southeastern Texas, eastern Oklahoma
and western Louisiana this morning. Rain was forecast for today
from the Mississippi Valley across eastern portions of the Central
Plains, Oklahoma, eastern Texas, western Mississippi, western
Tennessee, western Kentucky, Illinois and Wisconsin.
   Thunderstorms flung golf ball-sized hail near Weimar and
nickle-sized hail at Houston and Vinson, Okla.
   An early morning thunderstorm spat golf-ball sized hail
southeast of Chatham, La.
   Storms drenched Freestone County, Texas, with 5 inches of rain,
and flash flooding washed out roads and bridges.
   Afternoon and evening thunderstorms also caused some flooding in
Ochiltree County of the Texas Panhandle, and in Texas and Beaver
counties of the Oklahoma panhandle.
   It also rained in the Red River and upper Mississippi valleys.
   Heavier rainfall totals for the six hour period ending at 2 a.m.
EDT included 4 inches at Houston; 1.74 inches at Fort Polk, La.;
.72 inches at Wenatchee, Wash.; and .54 inches at Dodge City, Kan.
   A cold front was bringing rainshowers east of the Rockies, with
snow reported in some of the higher elevations. A snow advisory was
in effect for the Cascades of Oregon and Washington.
   Strong and gusty winds also accompanied the cold front in the
Northwest.
   Fair weather prevailed across the rest of the nation.
   The high Wednesday was 100 degrees at Kingsville, Texas.
   Today's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms the length
of Mississippi Valley and across the eastern Plains, from Texas to
Wisconsin. Showers and occasional thunderstorms were expected in
Montana, with showers extending across the Pacific Northwest and
turning to snow in the higher reaches of the Cascades.
   Highs were expected in the 50s and 60s over the Pacific
Northwest; in the 60s along the California coast, northeastern
Minnesota and over the eastern Plains; in the 80s in much of New
York and the lower Great Lakes, northern Florida, the central Gulf
coast to northern Texas and New Mexico; in the 90s over Florida,
south Texas and the desert Southwest; and in the 70s elsewhere.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 33
degrees at Sexton Summit, Ore., to 82 degrees at Key West, Fla.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 67 partly cloudy; Boston 56 fair; Buffalo 54
fair; Charleston, S.C. 64 partly cloudy; Cincinnati 57 fair;
Cleveland 49 fair; Detroit 54 partly cloudy; Miami 76 fair; New
York 56 fair; Philadelphia 64 fair; Pittsburgh 60 fair; Portland,
Maine 49 foggy; Washington 56 fair.
   _Central: Bismarck 49 fair; Chicago 65 partly cloudy;
Dallas-Fort Worth 71 foggy; Denver 53 rain; Des Moines 66 cloudy;
Indianapolis 59 cloudy; Kansas City 61 rain; Minneapolis-St. Paul
64 foggy; Nashville 67 cloudy; New Orleans 76 cloudy; St. Louis 70
hazy.
   _West: Albuquerque 53 fair; Anchorage 34 rain; Las Vegas 72
fair; Los Angeles 59 cloudy; Phoenix 75 fair; Salt Lake City 56
fair; San Diego 61 cloudy; San Francisco 53 drizzle; Seattle 43
partly cloudy.
   _Canada: Montreal 55 fair; Toronto 54 fair.
