<FILEID>AP-NR-05-18-89 0653EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-LeasePostponement     05-18 0441</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lease Postponement,0451</SECOND>
<HEAD>Interior Chief Announces Alaskan Offshore Drilling Delay</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Tanker Spill, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Interior Department announced a year's
postponement of a Gulf of Alaska oil lease sale because of
environmental concerns, even though state officials said a sale
there posed little risk.
   A spokesman for Alaska Gov. Steve Cowper urged the federal
agency to reconsider a lease sale in Bristol Bay, the state's
richest fishing area, because the state believes it poses a much
greater potential ecological danger.
   Interior Secretary Manuel Lujan Jr. said Wednesday the gulf sale
proposed for August 1990, in an area known as Lease Sale 114, was
delayed because additional time is needed to assess damage from the
Exxon oil spill in Prince William Sound. The tanker Exxon Valdez
hit a reef and spilled nearly 11 million gallons of crude oil into
the sound March 24.
   Terence O'Malley, Cowper's spokesman, called the delay
``probably a good idea in light of Prince William Sound. ...
However, since there's probably not that great of a chance of oil
being discovered there the risk is minimal.''
   Alaska authorities want the Interior Department to reconsider
its Bristol Bay lease sale, ``where the risks of a catastrophic oil
spills are much greater,'' O'Malley said.
   Drilling has not started there, but nine oil companies last year
paid the federal government $95 million for the right to explore
for oil and gas.
   The state went to court to block the leases, but lost before the
9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals. It plans an appeal to the U.S.
Supreme Court if Congress or the Bush administration doesn't buy
back the leases.
   The environmental assessment for the gulf sale had been
scheduled for publication in September. If the Interior Department
decides next year to go ahead with a new review, additional public
comment will be sought.
   Lujan said Interior officials will work closely with Cowper and
local communities.
   The Los Angeles Times on Wednesday quoted Lujan aide Steve
Goldstein as saying the decision ``should not be read as a
cancellation'' of the lease project. ``This is a postponement to
gather information while new facts are coming to light.''
   Another aide, Mark Stephenson in Washington, D.C., said that the
delay should take about a year because it will take that long to
evaluate the Valdez spill impact.
   Lujan's official announcement came at the start of the Interior
chief's Western tour with an itinerary including the Golden Gate
National Recreation Area headquarters, the Presidio Army base near
the Golden Gate Bridge, Yosemite National Park, Las Vegas, the Fort
Irwin National Training Center and a meeting with California Gov.
George Deukmejian.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890518-0057 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-18-89 0714EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Japan-Scandal     05-18 0588</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Scandal,0607</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prosecutors Raid Homes, Offices of Two Politicians</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TETSUO JIMBO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prosecutors today searched the homes and offices of
two members of Parliament suspected of taking bribes in an
influence-peddling scandal that has generated a national leadership
crisis.
   Also today, officials of the ruling and opposition parties
agreed to summon former Prime Minister Yasuhiro Nakasone to testify
under oath in Parliament next Wednesday about his links to the
scandal.
   The opposition has been boycotting lower house sessions to
demand testimony by Nakasone, who was prime minister at the time of
dubious stock deals including some purchases by his own aides.
   The opposition position stiffened after the governing party
rammed the fiscal 1989 budget through the lower house in its
absence on April 28.
   The Tokyo District Public Prosecutors' Office searched various
offices and residences of the two legislators, Takao Fujinami, 56,
and Katsuya Ikeda, 51 _ who on Wednesday became the first elected
officials to be interrogated as suspects in the scandal.
   Prosecutors again summoned the two for questioning today.
   According to Japanese legal custom, summoning politicians for
interrogation is regarded as the equivalent of an arrest. Japanese
law protects lawmakers from being jailed when Parliament is in
session.
   Because prosecutors are required to disclose their suspicions to
obtain special permission from Parliament to arrest lawmakers, they
routinely delay pressing formal charges until completing repeated
summonses and interrogation.
   Prosecutors are expected soon to press formal charges, the
equivalent of an indictment, against Fujinami and Ikeda.
   Ikeda, former secretary general of the opposition Komeito (Clean
Government Party), and Fujinami, of the governing Liberal
Democratic Party, are suspected of receiving bribes from the
Recruit Co. information conglomerate in exchange for using their
political clout to help the firm.
   Fujinami, an eight-term member of the House of Representatives,
was chief Cabinet secretary under Nakasone. He once was considered
a rising star in the Liberal Democratic Party.
   Fujinami has acknowledged an aide in 1986 bought 12,000 shares
in Recruit-Cosmos Co., a property subsidiary of Recruit, at a
discounted price before the company's stock was publicly traded.
The transaction brought profits of about $191,000.
   Ikeda, a former journalist and four-term member of the House of
Representatives, was also involved in a purchase of Recruit Cosmos
shares through his brother, Yuzuru, who bought 5,000 shares in the
firm and gained about $73,530 from the transaction.
   In both cases, the politicians denied personal involvement in
the transactions, although it was later disclosed that the bulk of
the profits went into their bank accounts.
   Ikeda said Tuesday that he planned to resign his Parliament
seat. Governing party officials denied reports that Fujinami also
would resign, but they indicated he might have to do so if formally
charged.
   Komeito Chairman Junya Yano became the third party leader to
step down in the Recruit scandal on Wednesday.
   He follows Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita, who is resigning as
head of the Liberal Democratic Party and thus as prime minister,
and Saburo Tsukamoto, who stepped down in February as head of the
opposition Democratic Socialist Party.
   Governing party leaders still are trying to find someone
untainted by the scandal who is suitable to be the new prime
minister.
   Some 160 politicians, bureaucrats and businessmen bought
bargain-priced unlisted shares in a Recruit subsidiary and made
large profits when the price soared after public trading began.
   Of 17 politicians linked to purchases of Recruit shares, 11 were
members of the Cabinet of Nakasone, who was prime minister at the
time of the share transactions.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
