<FILEID>AP-NR-05-18-89 0727EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Philippines-Storm     05-18 0212</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Philippines-Storm,0219</SECOND>
<HEAD>First Tropical Storm Of Year Kills at Least 12</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tropical storm Brenda swept into the
South China Sea and headed for China today after killing at least
14 people, disrupting air service and leaving thousands homeless,
officials said.
   At least 43 people were missing in three storm-related accidents
at sea, officials said.
   The tropical storm, the first to hit the Philippines this year,
came ashore Wednesday on Samar Island with winds up to 63 mph and
passed about 10 miles south of the capital after sunset.
   The storm uprooted trees, interrupted electricity service,
ripped off roofs and flooded streets in greater Manila, which has
more than 7 million residents.
   Scattered damage was reported throughout southern and central
Luzon, the main Philippine island.
   Philippine Airlines canceled 50 domestic flights and the Coast
Guard prevented at least six ships from leaving the port of Manila.
   Officials said reports of damage and casualties were delayed
because Brenda knocked out communications to the Bicol region of
southeastern Luzon and to parts of the central Visayas islands
which bore the brunt of the storm.
   The weather bureau said Brenda was 230 miles northwest of Manila
this afternoon heading toward China at 9 mph and packing peak winds
of 69 mph.
</TEXT>
