<FIRST>r a PM-LATeachers     05-18 0519</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-LA Teachers,0535</SECOND>
<HEAD>Surprise State Budget Surplus Raises Stakes, Hopes In Teachers Strike</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE V. BIGELOW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A surprise state budget surplus has raised
hopes for an end to a four-day-old teachers' strike that has
crippled education for more than a half-million students in the
nation's second-largest school district.
   The state expects to receive an extra $2.5 billion in the next
two years, Gov. George Deukmejian said Wednesday. As much as $228
million of the surplus could go to the Los Angeles Unified School
District.
   Negotiators in the teachers' strike planned to resume
negotiations today.
   The third day of the strike Wednesday was marked by dwindling
student attendance, a report of a Molotov cocktail thrown at a
school and the arrest of a striking teacher who allegedly hit a
substitute teacher with a picket sign.
   Although educators had expected some kind of state budget
windfall, the size of the surplus came as a surprise to both sides
in the teachers' strike.
   Wayne Johnson, president of United Teachers-Los Angeles, reacted
to the news by changing the union's pay demand from a 21 percent
raise over two years to 26 percent raise over three years.
   ``This is very good news,'' Johnson said. ``If they don't want
to settle with us now, they just want to break the union.''
   But the district offered no change in its offer of a 21.5
percent raise over three years, citing the findings of a state
fact-finders report released Wednesday. The report said the
teachers should accept the district's proposal as fair and
reasonable.
   Board of Education President Roberta Weintraub said the report
``totally exonerates the board of education ... and I urge each and
every teacher to go back to work.''
   The report was prepared by attorney Geraldine Randall, who began
investigating the dispute last March when the 16-month contract
negotiation reached an impasse.
   She was selected jointly by the district and the teachers'
union, but Johnson dismissed the findings as biased against
teachers.
   After the governor's announcement, Ms. Weintraub said a meeting
had been called between district and teachers union officials. At
issue is how much money the district should expect to receive out
of the surplus.
   A ballot measure passed in November requires the state to give
schools virtually all revenue over a set spending limit. But
lawmakers have indicated they may try to send more of the excess
funds to other areas.
   More than 250,000 of the district's 594,000 students skipped
school in the nation's second-largest school district Wednesday.
   The teachers' union said 23,000 teachers, counselors, nurses and
librarians were honoring the picket lines. Striking teachers
account for almost two-thirds of the district's 32,000-member
teaching work force.
   The district said about 8,200 teachers came to work Wednesday,
about 3,000 fewer teachers than the approximately 11,250 who
reported to work Tuesday.
   About 12,250 teachers came to work the first day of the strike.
   Security was beefed up at Hollenbeck Junior High School on
Wednesday after three Molotov cocktail firebombs were thrown at the
school overnight. Nobody was injured and the school suffered only
superficial damage.
</TEXT>
