<HEAD>Two Men Nabbed by Undercover Mom Sent to Prison</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two men arrested after a woman went
undercover to nab the people supplying her daughters with drugs
have been sentenced to prison.
   Jimmy Ray Goddard, of Dallas, and Thomas Reed Wilson, of
Independence, each were sentenced Wednesday to 10 years on a charge
of criminal conspiracy to manufacture methamphetamine. Goddard was
sentenced an additional five years for possession.
   Goddard, 55, and Wilson, 53, pleaded guilty Feb. 28 in Polk
County Circuit Court to the charges after Pat Morrison, 44, went
undercover and infiltrated what police described as a major
methamphetamine operation.
   Their arrests came after police accompanied Morrison to a state
park west of Salem, where she arranged to sell chemicals to a
suspect.
   Morrison, a bartender, said she decided to get involved because
her daughters, ages 24 and 21, used methamphetamine and had been
reduced to living out of their cars.
   Morrison went on to organize Grandparents for Drug Free America
and has signed a contract for a television movie about her
experience.
