<FIRST>r w PM-US-Nicaragua 1stLd-Writethru a0523 05-18 0552</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Nicaragua, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0523,510</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush May Seek Contra Military Aid if Elections Not Fair</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Retransmits to show 1st-Ld Writethru, Recasts lead, SUBS 2nd
graf to CORRECT spelling of counselor, pics up 3rd graf pvs, ``The wider...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An official of the National Security Council
says the Bush administration may seek renewed military aid to the
Contra rebels if Nicaragua's Sandinista government holds power by
fraudulent means in next year's election.
   ``If it is perceived that they have stolen the election, then
our policy subsequently will reflect that,'' NSC counselor Peter
Rodman said Wednesday to the privately financed Commission on Free
and Fair Elections in Nicaragua.
   ``The wider this perception, then the stronger consensus there
will be for an appropriate policy afterward,'' Rodman said.
   The official was asked his reaction to the testimony of Senate
Republican leader Bob Dole of Kansas, who told the commission on
Tuesday he would favor ``significant military aid'' to the
U.S.-backed Contras if Nicaraguan President Daniel Ortega fails to
hold free elections as promised.
   ``I have nothing to add to what was part of the bipartisan
accord a couple of months ago, that the administration does reserve
the right to ask for such aid in the future if circumstances
change,'' he said.
   ``That's not part of our present policy, but the administration
has not given away its future right to ask for such things if it
seems appropriate,'' he added.
   The United States government provides non-lethal aid to the
Contra rebels in their fight to oust the Marxist-led Nicaraguan
government. Military aid was cut off last year.
   Asked by former Sen. Gaylord Nelson, D-Wis., commission
co-chairman, what U.S. policy would be if a fair election resulted
in an Ortega victory, Rodman replied, ``I hesitate to prejudge
everything we would do. I think there is a presumption that if
there is a fair election and we accept it as a fair election, that
makes a big difference in our attitude toward Nicaragua and
certainly our policy.''
   The commission, established by the conservative World Freedom
Foundation, is made up of three Democrats and three Republicans.
   Carl Gershman, president of the National Endowment for
Democracy, a private grant-making organization that receives an
appropriation from Congress, testified that the Nicaraguan election
process ``will not work, and indeed will be a farce, if there is
not concerted effort by the Central American presidents and by
others who are concerned about the situation to insist upon fair
rules.''
   ``So far, the fear is that there have been certain cosmetic
steps that have been taken, perhaps to improve the standing of the
government in Europe and elsewhere, but that there has not been any
real effort to sit down and establish an agreement,'' Gershman
said. ``Unless there is agreement on rules, it will undermine the
legitimacy of the whole process.''
   Elections are to be held in Nicaragua next February under a
regional peace plan that Managua made with the neighboring
governments of Costa Rica, El Salvador, Guatemala and Honduras.
   Paul S. Reichler of Washington, an attorney for the Nicaraguan
government who said he was speaking only for himself, said he
believes the Sandinistas will win the election. If they do not, he
said he believes they will turn over power to whoever does.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
