<FIRST>r i PM-Havel     05-18 0369</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Havel,0379</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dubcek Visits Havel In Czechoslovakia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Alexander Dubcek, leader of the
1968 Prague Spring reforms, was among dozens of well wishers who
visited playwright Vaclav Havel after he was released from jail.
   At a party today attended by at least 100 supporters, Havel said
he had a ``very interesting'' three-hour talk with Dubcek after he
was released on probation Wednesday. It was the first time the two
had met in 20 years.
   Dubcek was accompanied by Vaclav Slavik, a former leader who was
expelled from the party in a purge carried out by the current party
leader, Milos Jakes, after the Warsaw Pact invasion that crushed
Dubcek's reforms in 1968.
   Havel declined to give more details about his conversation with
Dubcek.
   Havel, whose works are banned in Czechoslovakia, was arrested
Jan. 16 at an unofficial memorial ceremony in Prague's Wenceslas
Square for Jan Palach, a student who committed suicide by setting
himself on fire in January 1969 to protest the crushing of reforms.
   Havel was sentenced on Feb. 22 to nine months in jail on charges
of incitement and obstructing a police officer. An appeals court
dropped the obstruction charge in March and reduced the sentence to
eight months. Havel was put on 18 months' probation upon his
release.
   For Dubcek, now a pensioner living in the Slovak capital of
Bratislava, the meeting with Havel marked the second time in three
days that he had met with opposition activists he once declined to
see in public. Dubcek was among 1,000 mourners who attended the
funeral Monday in Slovakia of opposition writer Dominik Tatarka,
who died last week, according to others who attended.
   Dubcek was ousted as party leader in April 1969 and expelled
from the party in June 1970 after a brief period as Czechoslovak
ambassador to Turkey.
   Authorities watched him closely for almost 17 years, but his
police guard was removed after Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev
visited Czechoslovakia in April 1987. Since then, Dubcek has
cautiously resumed political activity and was allowed to visit
Italy late last year.
   In a recent interview with Hungarian television, he condemned
the current Prague leadership for abandoning his reforms.
</TEXT>
