<FIRST>r a PM-Mayor'sBlood     05-18 0258</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mayor's Blood,0267</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mayor Apologizes for `Monkey Blood' Remark</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EAST ST. LOUIS, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The mayor has apologized for saying
he feared a transfusion of ``monkey blood'' during a planned trip
to Zaire, but said the flap has given him ``international status.''
   Mayor Carl E. Officer, who is black, said on May 3 that he would
bring his own supply of blood in case he needs a transfusion. He
said he feared receiving contaminated ``monkey blood'' from
Africans.
   On Wednesday, Officer called his remarks ``unfortunate and
uncalled for.''
   ``I have grievously erred,'' he said.
   Officer said he has received numerous complaints about his
remarks from Zairians living in this country ``and from persons in
all walks of life who are of African ancestry.''
   The mayor issued a formal, written apology ``to all African
people and to all natives of the United States of African descent.''
   ``I am truly sorry for offending persons for whom I hold so much
love and respect,'' the statement said.
   On Tuesday, Glenwood Roane, executive director of the
Zaire-American Research Institutute, which is a sponsor of the
trip, called Officer's remarks ``ignorant'' and said the mayor
``should consider himself uninvited.''
   But Officer said he has ``every intention'' of making the
two-week trip starting June 19 with 40 other mayors.
   Officer said he planned to be more careful about his public
comments.
   The controversy has ``elevated me from a local status to an
international status,'' he said. ``So as an international leader
now, I'm much more concerned about my status and my comments.''
</TEXT>
