<FIRST>r a PM-TroubledMayor     05-18 0402</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Troubled Mayor,0411</SECOND>
<HEAD>Federal Prosecutor Investigating L.A. Mayor's Ties To Indicted Financier</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. attorney's office in New York is
investigating Mayor Tom Bradley's ties to brokerage firm Drexel
Burnham Lambert and indicted financier Michael Milken, newspapers
reported today.
   The probe apparently is not directed specifically at the
embattled mayor but is part of a larger investigation into
politicians' links to Drexel and its former junk bond chief,
Milken, the Los Angeles Times and Herald Examiner reported in
today's editions.
   The U.S. attorney's office in Manhattan has subpoenaed records
of Bradley's dealings with Drexel as part of a probe into the firm
and Milken, who is charged with 96 counts of insider trading,
racketeering and securities fraud, the Times reported.
   The U.S. attorney's office also directed Los Angeles FBI agents
to interview a former top financial adviser to Bradley about the
mayor's ties to Drexel and Milken, the Herald Examiner reported.
   Bradley declined to comment Wednesday on the reports of the
latest investigation. In the past, he has acknowledged he made
errors in judgment in some of his private finances but has denied
any wrongdoing.
   ``Basically, they (FBI agents) asked me if I thought that the
mayor was capable of insider trading and if I knew of any evidence
of financial impropriety or if he got any stock tips,'' said Mark
Ross Weinberg, a former commodities broker.
   Weinberg, who said he advised Bradley from April 1983 to early
1985, told agents he never gave Bradley inside stock tips. ``I
don't believe Tom Bradley has a crooked bone in his body,''
Weinberg said he told the agents.
   The U.S. attorney would be at least the fifth authority
investigating the mayor, joining the Securities and Exchange
Commission, the city attorney, the City Council and the Fair
Political Practices Commission, a state watchdog group.
   Bradley has been dogged by accusations of conflict of interest
since his re-election last month to an unprecedented fifth term as
mayor of the nation's second-largest city.
   Allegations of conflict of interest surfaced when published
reports revealed the mayor was paid by two banks that were doing
business with the city. Since then, additional questions have been
raised about the mayor's stock deals.
   The Beverly Hills-based Milken is a major campaign donor and
fund-raiser for Bradley, who has lobbied to keep Drexel's junk bond
operations in Beverly Hills throughout the federal investigation of
Drexel and Milken.
</TEXT>
