<SECOND>PM-Law School Dog, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0531,0255</SECOND>
<HEAD>Seeing-Eye Dog Dons Cap and Gown For Mistress' Commencement</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 6th graf, `Jack Dean ...' to CORRECT name to Riley, sted
Dean.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHAMPAIGN, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Although law school student Karen
Frerichs will be recognized for her academic achievement at her
graduation, observers should have no difficulty recognizing her
companion, Lyric.
   She'll be the only dog in a cap and gown at the University of
Illinois commencement Saturday.
   Ms. Frerichs is blind. Lyric is her seeing-eye dog.
   Collegiate Cap &amp; Gown Co. of Champaign designed the special
attire for the 8-year-old German shepherd, which has spent the last
three years helping Ms. Frerichs around campus, sitting through
long lectures and study sessions.
   ``It was such a nice thing for them to do,'' said Ms. Frerichs,
a 28-year-old Kankakee native who has been blind since age 12.
``I'm not sure I could have done it emotionally without her.''
   Jack Riley, the law school's assistant dean, said Lyric may be
the first seeing-eye dog to last all the way through legal studies
to graduation.
   ``Most of them go kind of psychotic,'' he said. ``They get
stepped on and they get tired. And after a while, the students
leave them at home and just start using a cane.''
   But Lyric hung in there and even proved to be a help to other
students by keeping classes from running over.
   When the class bell rang, Ms. Frerichs said, Lyric got up, ready
to head out the door.
</TEXT>
