<FIRST>u i PM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru a0492 05-18 0741</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0492,0760</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Crackdown: Gazans Will Need Permit to Enter Israel</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts 3 grafs after 4th pvs, ``The death...'' to UPDATE with
14 Palestinians wounded. Pickup 5th pvs, ``The army...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a new crackdown, the army will require
residents of the occupied Gaza Strip to have special permits to
enter Israel and may extend the restrictions to Palestinians in the
West Bank, a military official said today.
   The unprecedented measure _ affecting 700,000 people _ came a
day after Parliament approved Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir's peace
plan calling for elections in the occupied lands to choose
Palestinian delegates for autonomy talks with Israel.
   Also today, an 18-year-old Palestinian from the West Bank
refugee camp of Dheishe died eight days after being shot in the
head during a clash with troops, the army said. Arab hospital
officials identified him as Ali Zghari.
   The death brought to 482 the number of Palestinians killed since
the December 1987 start of the Palestinian uprising against Israeli
occupation. Twenty-one Israelis have also been slain.
   At least 14 Palestinians were shot and wounded in clashes with
soldiers in the West Bank and Gaza Strip today, Arab reports and
hospital officials said.
   One was a 13-year-old boy listed in critical condition in
Tulkarem Hospital with a wound in the chest. He was shot at the
West Bank's Tulkarem Refugee Camp, where soldiers fired on youths
defying a curfew in effect for five days, according to Arab reports.
   Much of the West Bank and Gaza Strip were shut down by a general
strike called by the Moslem fundamentalist movement ``Hamas,'' or
zeal, to protest Israeli interference with mosques.
   The army, which imposed a general curfew on the Gaza Strip on
Monday, lifted the restrictions in Gaza City and several other
areas today but continued to bar all Gazans from entering Israel.
On Tuesday, authorities forced all Gazans still in Israel to return
to their homes.
   The closure and the permit requirements are part of a new army
crackdown on the uprising. In the West Bank, home to 1 million
Palestinians, troops have resumed arrest raids in isolated Arab
villages, a practice that led to many casualties and was abandoned
for several months.
   The new permits ``will improve our ability of supervising the
entry of Palestinians from the occupied territories to Israel,''
said the military official, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin indicated that Palestinians
active in the uprising would be denied permits.
   ``We distinguish between those Palestinians who would like to
continue their lives in a normal way regardless of what political
views or political aspirations they may have and those who
participate in violence,'' he told the Jerusalem Post newspaper.
   Rabin said the peace initiative and crackdown were part of the
same policy. The Palestine Liberation Organization and many
prominent Palestinians in the occupied territories have rejected
Shamir's peace plan because it does not provide for eventual
Palestinian statehood.
   Rabin said the new restrictions were meant ``to send a clear
message to the Palestinians: Forget about bringing about any
changes in the political initiative through stones or firebombs.''
   The military official said Palestinians convicted of serious
crimes, such as murder or armed robbery, would also be barred from
Israel but that details were still being worked out.
   Officials said 28,000 Palestinians have been convicted of crimes
in Israel in the past 10 years.
   Rabin said the army could start issuing permits by the end of
May, and expected the process to be completed within three months.
   It was not immediately clear whether Gazans would be confined to
the Gaza Strip until all permits have been issued.
   The closure will have the strongest affect on the 50,000 Gazans
who work in Israel and whose low-paying jobs in farming,
construction and municipal services are their only source of
income. About 60,000 West Bank Palestinians also work in Israel.
   In the past few days, officials in several Israeli cities have
debated proposals to fire workers from the occupied lands and hire
unemployed Israelis for higher wages.
   Tel Aviv Mayor Shlomo Lahat said today that only companies whose
employees are Israeli citizens will get contracts for street
cleaning. Currently, most Tel Aviv street cleaners are Gaza Strip
residents.
   ``To take the residents from the territories, and give them the
work we, the Israelis, don't want to do is unethical, unhealthy,''
Lahat said on Israel radio.
</TEXT>
