<FIRST>r a PM-ParkAttack     05-18 0245</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Park Attack,0250</SECOND>
<HEAD>Doctors Hope Facial Surgery Will Speed Jogger's Neurological Recovery</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Doctors performed surgery to repair broken bones
around the eye of a jogger who was raped and beaten in Central Park
and hoped it would clear up the woman's double vision and aid her
neurological recovery.
   A team of seven surgeons worked Wednesday to repair fractured
bones around the woman's left eye socket, said Dr. Robert S. Kurtz,
director of the surgical intensive care unit at Metropolitan
Hospital.
   The 28-year-old woman even joked about the surgery, Kurtz said.
   He said a neurologist asked the woman, ``What part of the body
do I work on?'' and the woman replied, ``The main course.''
   The woman, an investment banker, was attacked by a group of
teen-age boys as she jogged through the park on the night of April
19. She was comatose for nearly two weeks, but has made slow
progress since emerging from the coma, including being able to name
objects and helping to move herself from a stretcher to a bed.
   The woman's left eye had been pushed out of place when its bony
supports were fractured. Kurtz said doctors put the ends of
fractured bones together and used a small piece of bone from her
skull to move the eye back to its normal position.
   Doctors hoped the operation will ease her disorientation. But
Kurtz said the woman continued to have brain-function problems and
remained in serious condition.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
