<FIRST>r a PM-PunctureSpree     05-18 0277</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Puncture Spree,0283</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tire Store Manager Accused In Tire-Puncturing Spree</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOUNT HOPE, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The manager of the only tire repair
shop in town was charged after at least 14 cars and trucks had
their tires punctured, officials said.
   Donald Ellison, 28, manager of the Fayette Tire Shop, was
arrested Wednesday and charged with 14 counts of conspiracy to
destroy property in Saturday morning's spree, police said. A
teen-age boy was charged with destruction of property and
conspiracy.
   ``Everyone was pretty well mad Saturday morning,'' said Greg
Ayres, who had two tires punctured each on his van and car. ``It
was quite a sight to look down the parking lot and see all the cars
sitting on a slant.
   ``Most everybody went down there (to Ellison's shop),'' Ayres
said. ``It was the closest place around.'' The vandalized cars and
trucks were parked in an apartment parking lot and on several
streets in this town of 1,800.
   Also charged Wednesday was Shawn Smith, 18, of Mount Hope,
police said. Smith faces 14 counts of destruction of property and
one count of conspiracy to destroy property, said Police Chief
Garland Burke.
   The charges were filed after Smith turned himself in to the
Fayette County Sheriff's Department about 1 a.m. Wednesday, Burke
said. Police arrested Ellison at his home about seven hours later,
the chief said.
   Both suspects were arraigned before a magistrate and was
released on $5,000 bond, Burke said.
   Burke said Ellison was charged with conspiracy but not with
actually damaging the tires because police didn't have evidence
that he did the puncturing. He said he couldn't comment on how
Ellison was linked to the incident.
