<FIRST>r a PM-SuicideMixup     05-18 0233</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Suicide Mixup,0240</SECOND>
<HEAD>Desperate Calls To Craft Store Continue; Clues To Origin Scarce</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GRAND RAPIDS, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Desperate and depressed people
reaching out for help from a national suicide prevention hotline
have been instead dialing the number of a wholesale craft supply
business.
   The calls are fraying the tempers of LaVon Davis and her two
employees at House of France.
   ``It's very draining,'' she said of trying to handle suicidal
callers. ``I don't know if it's because of the calls but we're all
kind of on edge with each other ... rather irritable.''
   The calls apparently result from a mixup in which a national
suicide prevention hotline somehow published the number for Davis'
business.
   ``We got a call today from a man who said he saw the number on
channel 32 in Miami,'' Davis said Wednesday. There is no commercial
channel 32 in Miami although the number is used by various cable
companies.
   ``We told him we would try to get help for him,'' Davis said.
   The calls began about four weeks ago. Suicide prevention
agencies in the Grand Rapids area have given Davis their numbers to
pass along to callers.
   Davis said changing her business number is unfeasible because of
the potential of losing sales.
   ``I just hope that nobody does anything in the meantime,'' she
said. ``I guess it's on all of our consciences, every time the
phone rings.''
