<FIRST>u i PM-Panama 1stLd-Writethru   05-18 0842</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Panama, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0472,0870</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Newspaper Says U.S. Bribed OAS; Noriega Speaks Out</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with Noriega interview, government newspaper
saying U.S. promised to pay debt to get OAS resolution passed. No pickup.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-OAS-Panama, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto PAN1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOSEPH B. FRAZIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government newspaper today
claimed the United States bribed the Organization of American
States to pass a resolution calling for a transfer of power in
Panama.
   Panama's de facto ruler, Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega, said in a
radio interview that Washington's desire to get rid of him is
racially motivated.
   He also accused the U.S. Embassy in Panama of misinforming
President Bush about the situation in Panama since the May 7
presidential election. Foreign observers say the opposition won the
vote, but the government declared the election void.
   ``Panama asks for respect. It asks for freedom. For its
sovereignty. The time of empires has ended. Why does the United
States want an empire in Panama? Why? This is our only answer:
because we are black,'' the general told WBAI radio in New York in
a telephone interview from Panama.
   His comments, on WBAI's ``Undercurrents'' program, came after
the OAS unanimously approved a resolution Wednesday night to send
mediators to Panama in an effort to bring about a transfer of power
through democratic means.
   ``The United States must change its attitude here in Panama.
This is my message to your small radio station,'' Noriega said.
   The government newspaper La Critica contended that the United
States promised to pay its debt to the OAS of $50 million in
exchange for the passage of the resolution.
   It did not mention that Panama's foreign minister, Jorge Ritter,
supported sending in foreign ministers.
   A commentator on the government's Radio Nacional said if the
foreign ministers visit Panama, ``they must not come with the
proposal that Noriega leave because that is an internal Panamanian
affair.''
   The commentator, Rigoberto Paredes, said the ministers should
come to discuss ``the war of aggression the United States is waging
against us,'' and the freeing of Panamanian funds frozen in
American banks last year.
   Paredes is an influential member of Panama's National Assembly
and the former secretary-general of the military-run Revolutionary
Democratic Party.
   The United States has been trying to oust Noriega since he was
indicted last year in Florida on federal drug-trafficking charges.
Noriega denies the allegations and contends the United States wants
him out so it can renege on the Panama Canal treaties, which call
for control of the waterway to be turned over to Panama by 2000.
   As head of the Defense Forces, Noriega also is the de facto
ruler of Panama.
   The opposition called a general strike Wednesday to press for
his ouster, but merchants say fear, frustration and economic
hardship caused it to fizzle.
   Half the capital's businesses remained open, taxis and buses
operated normally and the few demonstrations were small.
   Many businesses in Panama are owned by foreigners, and some
owners said they feared problems with the government if they closed.
   ``We were closed for two months last year and we got nothing out
of it. The crisis got worse,'' said the owner of a furniture store
in the capital.
   ``I'm lucky if I make $7 a day. Last year when I closed for four
days I lost my apartment,'' said another merchant. ``I'd close
again if I thought it would make a difference.''
   Leaders of Panama's government-controlled unions condemned the
strike, and taxi drivers said they were told they could lose their
licenses if they did not work.
   ``We are not fighters. We are not going to go out into the
streets and confront the police,'' said a man sipping a soda in a
small grocery store.
   ``Noriega is willing to die here. He'll have to be carried out
of the barracks feet first,'' an opposition supporter said glumly.
   At San Miguelito, a poor section of town, four women banged pots
and tried to set up a barricade.
   ``Where are the men?'' one woman was asked.
   ``Well,'' she answered, ``that's the problem.''
   ``I am not satisfied,'' said second vice presidential opposition
candidate Guillermo Ford. ``I thought people would express their
disatisfaction in a harsher way.''
   Opposition presidential candidate Guillermo Endara, however,
termed the action a ``total success.''
   Endara and other opposition candidates were severely beaten by
pro-Noriega thugs after the May 7 vote.
   In an interview Wednesday with France's Antenne 2 network,
Noriega alleged that the opposition itself brought about the
beatings by provoking violence.
   ``The police gave their protection to the candidates. I have as
proof that those who were injured were members of the police
forces,'' he said, showing photographs of what apparently were
hospitalized policemen.
   Ford appealed for the OAS to take concrete steps to force
Noriega to recognize the opposition victory.
   ``We just hope that the OAS once and for all becomes what it was
designed to be: a protector of the Latin American democracies and
not just a place to have nice Scotch and champagne,'' he said.
</TEXT>
