<FIRST>u i PM-Ethiopia 3rdLd-Writethru   05-18 0651</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ethiopia, 3rd Ld-Writethru,a0539,0668</SECOND>
<HEAD>Army Defections Pose Serious Problem For Ethiopian President</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts 1 graf after penultimate pvs, ``Mengistu inherited ...''
to include background on war. Pickup last pvs, ``Eritrea is ...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ABEBE ANDUALEM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ADDIS ABABA, Ethiopia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Mengistu Haile Mariam
today faced the biggest challenge of his 15-year Marxist rule _ the
reported defection of nearly half his army in the third day of an
attempted coup.
   The trouble came from war-weary troops in the north, who have
been fighting rebels of the Eritrean People's Liberation Front.
   After receiving word of the coup attempt, Mengistu cut short a
state visit to East Germany and returned Wednesday night to Addis
Ababa, where loyal soldiers defeated mutinous troops in a battle in
the capital.
   The city was calm today, but troops still guarded most key
government buildings and the international airport remained closed.
   At least two rebellious generals and the defense minister have
been killed in the fighting, but the total number of casualties was
not known.
   Addis Ababa state radio today urged people to return to work.
   Radio broadcasts from Ethiopia's second-largest city, the
northern provincial capital of Asmara, declared the coup a success
and urged the rest of the military to join the revolt.
   Soldiers backing the coup also were supported by secessionist
rebels the troops have been fighting in the province. The
clandestine radio of the Eritrean People's Liberation Front
declared today a two-week cease-fire ``to facilitate the successful
outcome'' of the military revolt that began Tuesday.
   Voice of the Eritrean Masses, the rebel radio, said Ethiopia's
2nd Army _ a force of 150,000 men _ has full control of Asmara,
capital of the northernmost province of Eritrea where the rebels
hold three-fourths of the countryside.
   It said the rebels are discussing with army officers in Asmara
``the best ways to intensify the struggle against ... the common
enemy.''
   The rebellious soldiers commandeered a former government radio
station in the city and broadcast in the name of the ``Armed Forces
of Eritrea.''
   They said they ``called on the (rebels) to join hands'' in
ousting Mengistu, but it was not clear whether the rebels and
soldiers had formed an alliance. Such an association would mean the
government had lost control of the province, Ethiopia's only access
to the Red Sea.
   The revolt began Tuesday, just hours after Mengistu and his wife
left for East Berlin. It was put down in the capital in 24 hours.
   Addis Ababa state radio today announced the death of the defense
minister, Maj. Gen. Haile Giorgis Habte Mariam, saying ``one of the
plotters shot him repeatedly'' Tuesday when he refused to join the
coup attempt.
   Two rebellious officers also were killed Tuesday: Maj. Gen.
Merid Negusie, the chief of staff, and the air force commander,
Maj. Gen. Amha Desta.
   There were unconfirmed reports that a third coup leader, Maj.
Gen. Kumalapchew Dejene, the deputy commander of the armed forces
in Eritrea, was hunted down and killed by loyalist soldiers on
Wednesday.
   State radio said another coup plotter was arrested _ Industry
Minister Fanta Belai who used to command the air force.
   Mengistu inherited the 28-year-old northern civil war when he
and a clique of army officers deposed Emperor Haile Selassie in a
Marxist revolution Sept. 12, 1974. Since then, his biggest ally,
the Soviet Union, has helped build the Ethiopian army into Africa's
biggest and best equipped, though many troops are unwilling
conscripts. They have been fighting 30,000 Eritrean rebels and
20,000 insurgents who want more autonomy in neighboring Tigre
Province.
   Persistent reports of military unrest in Ethiopia cite
war-weariness among field commanders unhappy with the level of
government support they are receiving in waging the war, which is
the oldest in Africa.
   Eritrea is a former Italian colony that was federated with
Ethiopia in 1957 under a U.S.-sponsored U.N. resolution. Selassie
annexed the territory in 1962.
</TEXT>
