<FILEID>AP-NR-05-18-89 1048EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-FalconRescue     05-18 0353</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Falcon Rescue,0362</SECOND>
<HEAD>Biologist Rappels Down Office Building In Bid To Save Falcon Egg</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A state biologist rappelled down the
side of a 23-story office building and endured repeated attacks by
two rare peregrine falcons to retrieve an egg from the birds' nest.
   The egg turned out to be infertile.
   Thomas French, head of the state's endandered species program,
dangled from two ropes Wednesday while a small crowd gathered on
the street hundreds of feet below and the adult birds attacked.
   He reached the 21st floor ledge of Monarch Place where the
endangered predators are raising two other chicks and sent the egg
up to the roof in a can. But after he rushed the egg to his Conway
home in hopes of incubating it, Thomas P. Ricardi, a master
falconer, said it had no embryo inside.
   ``My heart kind of sank,'' Ricardi said.
   State officials said it's not uncommon to find an infertile egg
in young birds' first nest, but they decided to try the rescue
after the egg did not hatch on schedule. The first egg opened
Saturday and the second chick hatched Monday.
   If the egg had been fertile, the chick would have been returned
to the nest.
   The adult birds are the first peregrine falcons to nest in
western Massachusetts in more than 40 years.
   The state raised and released young falcons in Boston and
Amherst in an attempt to restore a breeding population, but the
Springfield falcons found their own way to the downtown office
building last year. The birds easily adapt to tall buildings in
place of cliffs.
   A leg band shows the female was released in Toronto as part of
the Canadian government's falcon restoration efforts, French said.
The male also is banded but officials haven't yet determined his
origin.
   State biologists had to help a pair of Boston falcons incubate
their first eggs two years ago but they were able to use a
long-handled net to retrieve the eggs from a ledge. The net
couldn't be used at Monarch Place, because the high-rise office
building's windows don't open, officials said.
</TEXT>
