<FIRST>r w PM-US-Israel 1stLd-Writethru a0443 05-18 0534</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0443,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Israeli Official Seeking US Support for Policy</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 2 grafs new with meetings taking place; picks up at 3rd
graf, The United</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli Foreign Minister Moshe Arens today
sought support from U.S. officials for a controversial Israeli plan
to hold elections among Palestinians in the Israeli-occupied
territories.
   Arens met with national security adviser Brent Scowcroft and
Defense Secretary Dick Cheney. He also was scheduled to explain
details of the plan to Secretary of State James A. Baker III later
in the day. On Friday, he meets with Vice President Dan Quayle and
members of Congress.
   The United States has expressed qualified support for the plan.
   ``We think that the Shamir plan has some potential,'' Baker said
in an interview Wednesday on Worldnet, the television network of
the U.S. Information Agency. ``We think the idea of elections
cannot be seen as an end in and of themselves, (but) that it would
be helpful in moving toward peace,'' he added.
   Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir is seeking strong
endorsement for the plan, adopted by his cabinet on Sunday, both to
satisfy hardline critics at home and to enlist support for it among
moderate Arab leaders.
   Shamir will travel to England and Spain to campaign for the
proposal, which the Palestine Liberation Organization has rejected
because it excludes participation by its representatives and would
be held under Israeli occupation.
   The blueprint calls for elections that would pick Palestinians
who would initially negotiate with Israel over self-rule in the
predominantly Arab West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   The five-year autonomy period would be followed by negotiations
to determine who should control the lands which Israel captured
from Jordan and Egypt in the 1967 war.
   Shamir won reluctant Israeli parliamentary approval for the plan
Wednesday, but right-wing activists in his own Likud Party and
other parties claimed it would pave the way for creation of a
Palestinian state.
   Arens, speaking in a television interview, said some critics
believe Israel should withstand international pressure to advance
peace proposals until it has quelled the violent Palestinian
uprising in the territories.
   In response to escalating attacks on Israelis and growing public
pressure, the Israeli government this week cracked down on
Palestinians from the Gaza Strip, preventing them from traveling to
work in Israel and confining them to their homes. More than 480
Palestinians have died in the uprising which began 17 months ago.
   If the violence is to stop, Arens said, the United States must
help secure support for the Israeli election plan among Arab
leaders. ``The United States has a very crucial role to play at
this stage,'' Arens said in the televised interview.
   Arens also said that ``the most important thing as far as we're
concerned is that nothing be done in order to strengthen the image
of the terrorists, of the PLO, because they will try to sabotage
the initiative.''
   Israel objects strongly to the contacts launched last year
between Washington and the PLO, contending they only serve to
derail prospects for peace. Arens is expected to point to the PLO's
rejection of the Israeli plan as proof the organization does not
want peace.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
