<HEAD>Hussein Rejects Shamir Plan</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Israel</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMAL HALABY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMMAN, Jordan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   King Hussein today rejected an Israeli plan
for elections in the Israeli-occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip,
saying it was an attempt to buy time.
   The Israeli blueprint avoids ``facing increasing world pressures
to solve the (Palestinian) problem in a just and durable way,''
Hussein said.
   Earlier this week, the Palestine Liberation Organization
leadership also rejected the plan, which excludes participation by
PLO members. In a statement issued in Tunisia earlier this week,
the PLO leaders said they would not support elections under Israeli
occupation.
   Speaking at Marka air base near Amman, Hussein said: ``This (the
PLO decision) is a Palestinian move and I believe it is my duty and
the duty of all our Arab brethren to support it.''
   Israel's parliament, the Knesset, on Wednesday endorsed Prime
Minister Yitzhak Shamir's plan, which calls for the election of
Palestinian representatives to negotiate limited self-rule of the
West Bank and Gaza Strip. Under the plan, Palestinians would gain
autonomy for five years, then negotiate control of the territories
that Israel captured from Jordan and Egypt in 1967.
   In his remarks today, Hussein reiterated that he does not speak
on behalf of the Palestinian people. Jordan ruled the West Bank
between 1950 and 1967, then maintained an active role, speaking for
the Palestinians in international forums. But last year Hussein
handed over that responsibility to the PLO.
   ``The Israeli plan concerns the Palestinian people, and they
have their leadership, the PLO, under chairman Yasser Arafat,''
Hussein said.
   The Palestine National Council, the PLO's parliament-in-exile,
last year proclaimed an independent Palestinian state in the area
that roughly covers the occupied territories.
   Arafat later recognized Israel's right to exist and renounced
terrorism in a peace initiative. That action led the United States
to reverse a 13-year-old policy by opening talks with the PLO.
</TEXT>
