<FILEID>AP-NR-05-18-89 1108EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Soviet-Baltics     05-18 0463</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Baltics,0479</SECOND>
<HEAD>Baltic Parliaments Take Up Laws on Economic Autonomy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The parliaments of the Baltic republics of
Lithuania and Estonia today began considering legislation that
would give them greater economic independence from the federal
government.
   Lithuania's Supreme Soviet declared the republic ``sovereign''
and considered a draft law that would allow Lithuania to print its
own currency, an official in Lithuania's Foreign Ministry said.
   In Estonia, the proposal being debated included provisions for
limited private property.
   Both republics' plans would give them control over virtually all
industry in their territory and declare them the sole masters of
their natural resources.
   The proposed laws conflict with recommendations from a Moscow
commission on how much freedom the Soviet republics should have.
   The commission's proposed law would leave control over energy
and at least half of heavy industry, as well as all defense
production, in the hands of Moscow bureaucrats. It also would
prohibit republics from printing their own money.
   The Lithuanian parliament passed a law granting it general
sovereignty by a large margin, said Geidrius Cekuolis, first
secretary of the Lithuanian Foreign Ministry. The law specifies
that national Soviet laws are valid in Lithuania only if approved
by the Lithuanian parliament, effectively claiming the republic can
veto Kremlin decisions it does not like.
   The Estonian Supreme Soviet passed a similar law in November.
Moscow authorities pronounced the law invalid, but the Estonian
parliament stood by its decision and considers the sovereignty law
in force.
   The Estonian draft law on the economy does not provide for
separate currency, but Supreme Soviet members debated that question
today and it may end up in the law, the Estonian Foreign Ministry
spokesman, Gondo Olevsoo, said in a telephone interview from
Tallinn, Estonia's capital.
   The draft law's section on private property says that,``Within
limits set by the law, small-scale private property is allowed.''
   In a similar vein, the Lithuanian law provides for ``the
economically necessary introduction of plots of land for perpetual
use with the right of inheritance.''
   Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev has proposed leasing of up
to 50 years or more, but the Communist Party leadership has
explicitly rejected private ownership, which is antithetical to
communist ideology.
   Both republics say the new laws on economic independence should
come into force in 1990.
   Estonia claims full control over its land, water, air space,
forests and other natural resources in the law. All industry,
except defense-related factories, are to be put under control of
local authorities, according to the law.
   The Lithuanian proposal's provision on currency states that the
republic ``can introduce its own money system'' with independent
banks, and that it can ``if necessary print its own state
obligations, stocks and other valuable papers.''
   Latvia, the third Baltic republic, is considering similar
measures on economic independence.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
