<FIRST>r w PM-US-Germany 1stLd-Writethru a0418 05-18 0683</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Germany, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0418,680</SECOND>
<HEAD>West Germans Hold Talks With US Officials</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 10 grafs to include Baker meeting, new information
on German position; picks up 4th graf pvs,``We continue ....</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALEXANDER G. HIGGINS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III met
today with West German Defense Minister Gerhard Stoltenberg, who
presented some new suggestions for settling a heated dispute
between the two NATO allies over short-range nuclear missiles in
Western Europe.
   The talks are aimed at bridging the gap between the two nations
in order to sidestep confrontation at President Bush's first North
Atlantic Treaty Organization meeting, set for later this month.
   State Department officials had no immediate comment on the
outcome of the half-hour meeting, but a diplomatic source familiar
with Stoltenberg's proposals confirmed the West Germans are
prepared to be more flexible on the question of the timing of
U.S.-Soviet negotiations involving the weapons.
   The United States has opposed the idea of starting such
negotiations, fearing they would lead to pressures to remove all
short-range nuclear weapons in Europe.
   Stoltenberg's mission was to suggest a possible link between a
reduction of Soviet conventional forces in Europe with the start of
negotiations on cutting back the numbers of the short-range nuclear
weapons. The negotiations might not begin until there is
significant progress in cutting back the conventional arms in
Europe, where the Warsaw Pact has a huge advantage.
   One proposal would be to form a high-level NATO study group,
which would examine how much ``significant progress'' would be
necessary before any U.S.-Soviet talks could convene, the source
said.
   As Stoltenberg held talks with Baker and Secretary of Defense
Dick Cheney, a group of West German parliament members expressed
confidence that a solution to the dilema would be found.
   ``There's a new flexibility on both sides. The chances we will
reach an agreement are not 100 percent, but given the political
will, there's a good chance we will reach an agreement'' before the
NATO summit, said Volcker Ruehe, the deputy majority leader in
parliament, in a meeting with reporters.
   Ruehe and a three other members of parliament said they were
pleased with the reception they had gotten from officials at the
Department of State, the National Security Council, and on Capitol
Hill, in their talks on the dispute.
   West German Chancellor Helmut Kohl paved the way for
Stoltenberg's visit with a telephone call Tuesday to President
Bush, White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said Wednesday. He
gave no details of the call, which was initiated by Kohl.
   ``We continue to hope that we can reach some kind of an
agreement before the NATO summit (May 29), but if not, we'll
discuss it there or later,'' Fitzwater said.
   He was referring to the May 29 meeting of the 16-nation North
Atlantic Treaty Organization.
   Fitzwater said the dispute may also figure in talks that Bush
will have this weekend with French President Francois Mitterrand at
Bush's home in Maine.
   ``But the meeting is not designed to produce and specific
agreements or results in that sense,'' Fitzwater said.
   The U.S. government opposes the German call for early talks with
the Soviet Union on reducing short-range nuclear weapons in Europe.
Bonn objects to Washington's demands for an early NATO commitment
to upgrading NATO's Lance missiles when those weapons become
obsolete in 1995.
   ``We look forward to the Stoltenberg talks and think they'll be
very productive,'' Fitzwater said.
   Asked if there had been progress toward a solution, Fitzwater
said, ``Progress in the sense that we're talking and we understand
each other's positions better, but I couldn't give much more
projection than that.''
   Fitzwater said the United States is sticking to its position
that talks should first produce a reduction in Soviet Bloc forces
in Europe to match NATO levels. Only then would the United States
be willing to consider discussing short-range missiles.
   In a satellite interview with European correspondents Wednesday,
Secretary of State James A. Baker III said, ``Nuclear weapons are
part of a defensive strategy. We ought to move very, very slowly
before we abandon that strategy.''
</TEXT>
