<FIRST>r p PM-Kassebaum-Campaign     05-18 0364</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Kassebaum-Campaign,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kansas Senator to Seek Re-Election</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY MASSEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Nancy Kassebaum, R-Kan., saying she had
struggled with the decision ``for some time,'' announced today she
will seek re-election to a third term. Her decision dampened hopes
of Democrats to win their first Senate seat from Kansas in 50 years.
   Kassebaum said she will run in the 1990 elections because she
does not want to hurt the state by retiring and leaving it without
her seniority.
   Noting that she had pledged to serve only 12 years when she
first ran for the Senate, Kassebaum said she had ``struggled with
it for some time.'' But she said she decided to seek another term
because there is no limit on the number of years a senator can
serve.
   ``Unless everyone's doing it, you lose seniority ... that is
valuable to one's state,'' Kassebaum said.
   She pledged when she ran for the Senate for the first time in
1978 and again in 1984 that she would retire after 12 years in the
Senate, but she opened the door to a possible third term a short
time after winning re-election in 1984.
   Republicans have been urging Kassebaum to run again, fearing her
retirement would give Democrats their best chance at seizing a
Senate seat in Kansas since 1974, when Republican Sen. Bob Dole
narrowly won a second term. The last Democrat to hold a Senate seat
from Kansas was George McGill, who served from 1930-39.
   Political observers in Kansas consider Kassebaum an odds-on
favorite to win another term. Recent polling by her campaign
organization found that most Kansans would continue to support her
for re-election in 1990 in spite of the two-term pledge.
   Her popularity in Kansas has scared away serious Democratic
opposition in the past, and she won re-election in 1984 with 76
percent of the votes.
   Kassebaum is the daughter of the late Alf Landon, a Kansas
governor and 1936 Republican presidential nominee. She arrived at
the Senate a political novice, with her previous elective
experience limited to a local school board seat.
   She and Democrat Barbara Mikulski of Maryland are the only women
in the 100-member Senate.
</TEXT>
