<HEAD>Baby Found in Convenience Store Trash Can</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BIRMINGHAM, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A convenience store customer who heard a
muffled cry found a newborn girl at the bottom of a restroom trash
can with toilet paper stuffed in her mouth and ears.
   Ray Turner, 30, said he knew the sound he heard Wednesday wasn't
coming from a cat, as his brother suspected. ``I knew that was a
baby crying,'' he said.
   The infant was taken to Children's Hospital in Birmingham, where
she was in good condition today, said spokeswoman Tina Horton.
   Warrior Police said a woman went into the suburban Birmingham
convenience store Wednesday afternoon and asked to use the
restroom, where she apparently gave birth to the baby in 20 minutes
and left. Turner and his brother came by about 10 minutes later.
   ``Ray and his brother are regulars,'' cashier Kathy Coffey said.
``They're so regular they don't pay any attention to our `Not a
public restroom' sign. Thank goodness for that, though, because an
employee might not have gone in there until 8 p.m.''
   Mrs. Coffey said she let the woman, whom she did not know, use
the bathroom. ``She came in kind of bent over, asking please could
she go to the bathroom. I heard nothing at all (from the restroom)
the whole time.''
   Police Chief Mike Thrash said police were investigating.
