<FIRST>r i PM-SouthAfrica-Editor     05-18 0334</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-South Africa-Editor,0342</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Subpoena Editor After He Criticizes Murder Investigation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The editor of South Africa's
leading financial newspaper said today police have ordered him to
give testimony about an article he wrote criticizing their failure
to solve a 1986 murder case.
   Police Commissioner Hennie de Witt said police want to pursue
claims by Business Day editor Ken Owen that his reporters found
witnesses able to identify black miners who executed four fellow
workers during a mass protest at a gold mine.
   In a statement published by his newspaper, Owen said he would
comply with the subpoena, but contended the ``improper'' action was
a response to his accusations that Law and Order Minister Adriaan
Vlok handled the case ineffectively.
   The accusations were published Monday in the article in which
Owen scathingly questioned why police had been unable to solve
executions reportedly witnessed by 2,000 black mine workers. The
victims, also black, were accused of breaking a boycott organized
by militant union members.
   ``Vlok and his police have failed the most elementary test of a
government _whether or not it can uphold the common law,'' Owen
wrote. ``If he doesn't have the guts to fire them (his senior
officers) one by one until they do something, he should resign from
his highly paid position and go into the obscurity he deserves.''
   De Witt said in a statement Wednesday that police had been
unable to track down witnesses who could identify the killers and
were willing to testify in court. He said four suspects were
arrested but released for lack of evidence.
   Owen's article was ``unfair and slanderous,'' the commissioner
said.
   De Witt said police asked if he would supply information
voluntarily and were told he would do so only if subpoenaed.
   Business Day said in an editorial, ``The staff of the newspaper
do not wish to act as fact-gatherers or investigators for the
police ... it would close off future sources of information.''
</TEXT>
