<FIRST>u w PM-Shuttle-CloseCall 1stLd-Writethru a0419 05-18 0624</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Shuttle-Close Call, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0419,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shuttle Commander Pledges to Cooperate in Near-Collision Investigation</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts Walker's first name and rank in 2nd graf</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The commander of the Atlantis space shuttle
says he will cooperate ``to the best of my ability'' with three
federal investigations into accusations that he nearly ran his
space agency jet into a Pan Am airliner.
   Navy Capt. David M. Walker, who commanded the five-member
shuttle crew on a four-day voyage that ended May 8, said ``all the
facts have yet to be established'' on the incident. The pilot of a
Pan Am Airbus 310 carrying 166 passengers and a crew of 10 from
Washington to Paris initially reported the close call.
   The Federal Aviation Administration, the National Transportation
Safety Board and the National Aeronautics and Space Administration
all opened investigations into the incident after the Pan Am pilot
filed a report of a ``near midair collision.''
   The pilot said the NASA T-38 jet came within 500 feet of the
airliner.
   ``I will be assisting to the best of my ability with both NASA
and civil aviation authorities in their respective
investigations,'' Walker said. ``To discuss the issue further at
this point would be inappropriate.''
   Walker had flown to Washington for White House ceremonies on
Tuesday honoring the Atlantis crew.
   A NASA statement said Walker filed a ``hazardous air traffic
report'' with personnel at Andrews Air Force Base upon landing.
Spokesman Jack Riley said he did not know the nature of the report
or its contents.
   FAA air traffic controllers filed a ``pilot deviation report''
accusing Walker of violating flight procedures by not flying at his
assigned altitude and saying the planes were within 100 feet
vertically, said FAA spokesman Jack Leyden.
   The Pan Am jet was flying at 7,000 feet and Walker was assigned
to travel at 8,000 feet but descended to 7,000, the FAA spokesman
said. The controllers issued an advisory that two planes were in
the same area, and Walker took his jet to 8,000 feet, Leyden said.
   ``It was a very quick, like instantaneous sighting,'' said Pan
Am spokesman Alan Loflin. He said both planes were flying under
instrument conditions but the Pan Am pilot saw the T-38 because
they were between cloud layers when they crossed paths.
   Leyden said both FAA and safety board investigators on Wednesday
began looking into the incident, but details of their work were not
available.
   A near collision generally is reported when two planes come
within 500 feet of each other and either pilot feels they are in
danger of colliding.
   The FAA considers an incident ``critical'' when planes came
within 100 feet of each other at their closest point and
``potentially dangerous'' when they come within 500 feet.
   Leyden said possible enforcement action against a civilian pilot
who deviates from procedures could range from an administrative
letter to action affecting his license. But he said that since
Walker is a Navy pilot, any conclusion would likely be referred to
the military for further action.
   The safety board, which assigned three investigators to the
case, will determine the cause of the incident and recommend steps
to be taken to prevent it from happening again, but the board has
no power to impose penalties.
   NASA spokesman Riley said the Johnson Space Center was informed
of the near collision on Wednesday. Flight crew operations and
safety personnel will conduct a ``detailed investigation'' of the
incident, hesaid.
   No NASA T-38 has crashed since the 1960s, when four astronauts
were killed in three accidents. Riley said he was not aware of any
previous near-collision reports involving the 24 NASA T-38s which
the astronauts use to maintain required flying hours and to travel
between assignments.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
