<HEAD>University Teachers Suspend Strike After Meeting President</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KAMPALA, Uganda (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Striking teachers at Makerere University
went back to work Thursday after meeting with President Yoweri
Museveni on their demand for higher wages.
   Fredrick Juuko, chairman of Makerere University Academic Staff
Association, said Museveni had promised to seek solutions to the
teachers' problems.
   The teachers said they decided to suspend the strike, which
began May 2, but not call it off ``because it is the only weapon we
have.'' They resumed teaching in the afternoon.
   The teachers are demanding a salary increase from about $35 a
month for professors to about $576 a month.
   Museveni met representatives of the teachers Wednesday, a few
hours after they defied a government ultimatum to return to work at
the state-run university or face dismissal.
   Museveni, who is the university's chancellor, agreed to preside
at a new round of wage negotiations beginning Saturday, Juuko said.
   On Wednesday, hundreds of students supported their teachers'
defiance of the government's ultimatum to resume work.
