<FIRST>r a PM-ExxonMeeting-Demonstrations     05-18 0324</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Exxon Meeting-Demonstrations,0331</SECOND>
<HEAD>Demonstrators at Exxon Meeting Demand Complete Cleanup</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Exxon Meeting</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY20</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HENRY STERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARSIPPANY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Demonstrators at Exxon Corp.'s annual
shareholders meeting today accused the company of lying about the
Alaskan oil spill and said they hoped the disaster would end oil
exploration in that region.
   Barry Commoner, a long-time ecologist and former presidential
candidate, told about 250 demonstrators lining the entranceway to
the Aspen Manor Hotel that the spill in Alaska's Prince William
Sound shows the United States' overreliance on fossil fuels.
   ``We are here to pass judgment on a crime against nature and the
American people,'' Commoner told the crowd as some 80 police
officers stood by. ``That is the only adequate description for what
Exxon has done in Alaska.''
   Consumer activist Ralph Nader and leaders of national and state
environmental groups also planned to address the crowd, which
assembled peacefully outside the hotel and displayed signs saying
``Overthrow Exxon'' and ``Clean up your entire mess'' as
stockholders arrived for the meeting.
   Isabel Byrd, of Trenton, was dressed in an overstuffed tuxedo,
wore a pig's nose and walked on stilts. She said her outfit
represented the company's corporate mentality.
   Steve Kosnac, of Somerville, who said he had helped lay the
Alaskan pipeline in the 1970s, accused Exxon of deliberately
spilling the oil that poured from the hull of the grounded tanker
Exxon Valdez. Spoiling the coastline of Prince William Sound would
render it useless for anything but oil exploration, he said.
   Weldon Monsport, of Boonton, said, ``Exxon has lied from the
start and the government has dragged their feet and knuckles.'' He
carried a sign that said ``Exxon PR Is More Viscous Goo On The
Truth.''
   Township Mayor Frank Priore, a spectator at the demonstration,
said his sympathies lay with the protesters and that he would ask
Exxon to pay the police overtimes costs, which he estimated as high
as $18,000.
</TEXT>
