<FILEID>AP-NR-05-18-89 1245EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-BRF-MilitaryMoves     05-18 0196</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF-Military Moves,170</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Nominates New Commander for Presidio</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush has nominated Army Lt. Gen.
William H. Harrison to become the next commander of the 6th U.S.
Army at the Presidio of San Francisco.
   Assuming Senate confirmation, Harrison will replace Lt. Gen.
James E. Moore Jr., whom the Pentagon announced Thursday would
retire on July 1 after more than 35 years of active duty service.
   And in a related move, the Pentagon said President Bush had
nominated Maj. Gen. Calvin A.H. Waller for promotion to the rank of
lieutenant general and to replace Harrison in his current
assignment.
   Harrison, 55, is a native of Pembroke, Ky., who is currently
serving as the commanding general of the Army's I Corps and Fort
Lewis, Wash. Assuming Senate confirmation, Waller will pin on his
third star and replace Harrison in that job.
   Waller, 51, is a native of Baton Rouge, La., who is currently
serving as the commanding general of the 8th Infantry Division of
U.S. Army Europe and the 7th Army.
   Moore, 57, is a native of Fort Thomas, Ky., who is retiring
after having headed the 6th U.S. Army since June 1987.
</TEXT>
