<FIRST>r w AM-Toxin-Reactions     05-18 0615</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Toxin-Reactions,590</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bacteria Found to Cause Immune Overreaction</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release at 6 p.m. EDT</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Confronted with a relatively common toxin,
certain cells designed to protect the body can overreach and may
even make things worse, a Colorado researcher reported Thursday.
   Poisons produced by a bacteria blamed for many cases of food
poisoning and toxic shock syndrome can cause a massive reaction by
the body's T-cells, causing them to flood the body with potent
chemicals, explained Dr. Philippa Marrack of the Howard Hughes
Medical Institute in Denver.
   She is part of a team of researchers who reported their findings
in the journal Science, published by the American Association for
the Advancement of Science.
   Normally T-cells help protect the body by reproducing and
issuing chemicals to attack invading organisms.
   Under ordinary circumstances, such as the flu, a complex series
of five receptors is activated to set off the T-cells, meaning that
only about one cell in 10,000 to 100,000 may react to the invader,
Dr. Marrack explained in a telephone interview.
   The coupling mechanism is much simpler with staphylococcus
aurens, a bacteria that is associated with toxic shock syndrome,
many cases of food poisoning and some other human and animal
diseases, she reported.
   In this case, only one of the five receptors has to be
stimulated to cause the T-cells to reapond, Dr. Marrack said.
   ``The toxins might activate as many as one-third of the body's
one trillion T-cells almost simultaneously,'' she explained.
   This massive triggering of T-cells causes them to multiply
rapidly and discharge potent chemicals. In such quantities these
chemicals can make the invidiual ill or even cause death, she
reported.
   ``These chemicals, and not the toxin, probably produce the
symptoms of food poisoning and toxic shock syndrome,'' she said in
a statement released by the institute, which is located at the
National Jewish Center for Immunology and Respiratory Medicine.
   Dr. Marrack speculated that while the immune system is designed
to attack invaders, causing such an overreation may actually
protect the staphylococcus aurens bacteria. By overstimulating the
system they may prevent it from being able to concentrate on the
one invader, she said.
   Just how this process works and why the reaction varies from one
person to another are not understood, she added.
   Most victims of staphylococcus aurens food poisoning recover
with no long-term effects, she said. But cases have been reported
in which victims later developed an immune system-related form of
arthritis.
   The new findings may explain this.
   ``Suppose a small number of T-cells in your body have a tendency
to attack your own joints, but they've never had enough energy or
numbers to do so,'' she said. ``If a bacterial toxin stimulates
these cells, causing them to multiply rapidly, you could wind up
with a large number of `bad guys' that could cause arthritis, lupus
or some other autoimmune disease.''
   On the other hand, in the long run the response may also be able
to be used against such cells, according to Dr. Marrack. If a group
of T-cells attacking the body could be identified, a toxin might be
tailored to stimulate them to multiply and then drugs used which
kill only multiplying cells.
   Such a treatment, however, is not currently feasible and may not
be for years, she said.
   Other researchers taking part in the study included John
Kappler, also of the Howard Hughes Institute; Brian Kotzin, Lynne
Herron, Erwin Gelfand and Yongwon Choi of the National Jewish
Center; Robert D. Bigler of Hanneman University, Philadelphia;
Arthur Boylston, University of Leeds, England; Stefan Carrel,
Ludwig Institute for Cancer Research, Lausanne, Switzerland; and
David Ponsett of Cornell University Medical College, New York.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
