<FIRST>u a PM-KlanTrial     05-18 0319</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Klan Trial,0328</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Jury Convicts More Klansman of Murder</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GARRY MITCHELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOBILE, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An all-white jury today convicted a former
Ku Klux Klansman of murder for providing the rope and pistol used
in the killing of a black teen-ager whose body was hung in a tree.
   Benjamin Franklin Cox, 27, whispered ``I love you'' to his
weeping wife before county deputies led him away in handcuffs.
   Circuit Judge Michael Zoghby revoked Cox's $28,000 bond and set
a June 23 sentencing hearing. Cox could be sentenced to 10 years to
life in the March 21, 1981, strangulation and hanging of
19-year-old Michael Donald.
   Prosecutors said Donald was killed by Klansmen angry about a
1981 trial in which a black man was found innocent of killing a
white policeman.
   The verdict was delivered to a hushed courtroom filled with
relatives and friends of both the victim and the defendant. The
jury deliberated about four hours over two days.
   Cox's conviction was the third successful prosecution in the
last six years of trials stemming from the Klan murder. Defense
attorneys put on witnesses on the stand, while the state called at
least a dozen witnesses.
   In closing arguments, defense attorney Neil Hanley said the
witnesses against Cox had been ``coached and badgered'' into giving
false testimony.
   ``There is more than reasonable doubt ... there is a shocking
doubt in this case,'' Hanley said.
   Hanley described the prosecution's case as ``zero plus zero
equals zero,'' drawing the equation on a board. ``That's his
circumstantial evidence.''
   District Attorney Chris Galanos urged jurors to consider the
``big picture'' in which he claimed Cox participated in the
``organized and orchestrated'' Klan murder. Galanos called the
slaying ``senseless, mindless violence ... not just racism _ hate.''
   ``These people were Klansmen,'' Galanos said. ``Ordinary,
civilized people would never sit around and talk about taking the
life of another human being.''
</TEXT>
