<FIRST>u w PM-WrightProbe 2ndLd-Writethru a0602 05-18 0952</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wright Probe, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0602,900</SECOND>
<HEAD>House GOP Smiling at Wright Troubles</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Adds one graf with IRS declining comment on probe report</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House Republicans, after years of fighting the
ruling Democrats with noisy protests and parliamentary warfare, are
sitting back and smiling as they watch the storm encircling House
Speaker Jim Wright.
   The Texas Democrat is facing charges before the House ethics
committee and is the topic of nearly daily reports in the national
news media.
   The ethics panel decided today to hold a hearing next Tuesday on
Wright's motions to dismiss the main charges against him, and the
arguments by lawyers for the two sides will be open to television
coverage.
   Wright's spokeman, Mark Johnson, said the speaker welcomed the
development, and would renew his call for the committee to expedite
its procedures.
   In addition to the speaker's troubles, press reports have forced
Rep. Tony Coelho, D-Calif., Wright's chief vote-counter, to revise
and defend his own financial disclosure statements.
   But most House Republicans aren't putting out press releases,
making speeches about it, or even attacking the speaker in
conversations with reporters.
   Rep. Newt Gingrich, R-Ga., the No. 2 House Republican who
launched the probe against Wright, continues to comment when asked,
but he's avoiding television interviews on the topic. Asked what he
was thinking about a story involving Coelho's financial dealings,
he answered: ``I don't.''
   Rep. Jerry Lewis of California, chairman of the House Republican
Conference, says he has urged his colleagues to remain quiet in
deference to the ethics process, which eventually could require all
members to pass judgment on the speaker.
   Lewis and Rep. Robert Michel of Illinois, the Republican leader,
made clear they're happy to have the news media take on the speaker
without them.
   ``Far be it from this member to put any kind of cloud over a
free press,'' Michel said at a session with reporters following
President Bush's visit with House Republicans on Wednesday.
   ``Far be it,'' seconded Lewis, with a broad smile.
   A rank-and-file GOP member, speaking on condition his name not
be used, said the Republicans are in the catbird seat. ``For once,
good politics is also good policy,'' he said.
   While not directly attacking the Democrats on ethics, the
Republicans are needling the Democrats for the slow pace of
legislation and blaming it on ``disarray'' in Wright's leadership
team.
   Michel said ``it takes a strong hand'' to push through
contentious legislation, such as the supplemental spending bill
which House Democrats failed for a second time Wednesday to push
forward to a final vote.
   For Wright, ``I think that power... has been eroded by what
we've been witness to in the last several months,'' Michel said.
   Rep. Thomas Foley of Washington, the majority leader and the
next ranking Democrat after Wright, defended the speaker Wednesday
as ``fully involved'' and said there was no ``gridlock'' in the
House, as the Republicans claimed.
   But it is clear Wright's problems are much on the minds of
Democrats. A group of more than a dozen moderate Democrats who have
been supportive of Wright held a grim hour-long meeting in the
Capitol on Wednesday to discuss the speaker's plight.
   The group was scheduled to meet again today, and one lawmaker
said the subject of the meetings was ``too hot'' to discuss
publicly. A House member familiar with the discussions said one
topic is whether a protracted defense of the speaker will prove too
politically damaging to the party.
   One of the participants, Rep. David Obey, D-Wis., said he argued
that Wright should have an opportunity to make his legal case on
the ethics charges without delay.
   But, Obey added, Wright ``will also have to _ at some other
time, I would hope _ make a judgment about the political
situation.''
   Obey said the discussion revolved around ``whether or not Jim
can get a review on the issues without the political question ...
getting in the way.''
   The ethics committee, meanwhile, continued to investigate a gas
drilling venture last year that yielded a quick $170,000 profit for
Wright at a time when he needed $100,000 to pay off a bank loan for
another deal that went sour.
   The panel also was meeting today to decide how to handle
Wright's motion to dismiss the two most serious sets of charges
against him: that he sought to evade limits on outside income
through bulk sales of his book, and that he accepted improper gifts
from business partner George Mallick, deemed by the panel to have
had a direct interest in legislation.
   The motions to dismiss charges are important because they
represent a chance to win a badly needed victory and to avoid a
full-blown hearing on the matters that could be the most
embarrassing to the speaker.
   ``The motions are quite significant,'' Wright said, repeating
his argument that the ethics committee is seeking to hold him to
some new and higher standard than provided for in House rules.
``Members need an assurance that the rules mean what they say and
won't be changed to fit the specific situation. It's important not
just to me but to the whole Congress.''
   The Los Angeles Times reported today that the criminal division
of the Internal Revenue Services is conducting a preliminary
investigation into the speaker's business dealings with Mallick.
   The Times, quoting unidentified federal sources, said agents
from the IRS' Dallas bureau were looking at a broad range of
transactions involving Mallightco, the company formed by the two
men and their wives.
   At IRS headquarters in Washington, spokesman Wilson Fadely
declined comment on the report. ``The IRS is prohibited by law from
disclosing whether or not we are investigating any taxpayer,'' he
said.
</TEXT>
