<FIRST>u w PM-S&amp;Ls     05-18 0439</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-S&amp;Ls,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Panel Votes to Require Greater Bailout Contribution by S&amp;Ls</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A House panel voted today to make savings and
loan banks add $600 million over the next three years to their
share of an industry bailout, and potentially billions of dollars
more over the next three decades.
   The Ways and Means Committee, however, rejected raising taxes
through a 1.5 percent surtax for five years to pay for the
government's immediate $50 billion share of the costs in assuring
depositors in insolvent S&amp;Ls against losses.
   On a voice vote, the committee said S&amp;Ls have to contribute $600
million more to the bailout's cost in 1991 and 1992 and potentially
billions of dollars more over the next three decades by indexing
increases in a required $300 million annual contribution to the
rate of inflation.
   The committee later approved the overall bill on a 26-10 vote.
   The defeated surtax would have been the first since such a
revenue-increasing measure was adopted by the government since the
late President Lyndon Johnson used one to finance the Vietnam war.
   Its purpose was to save an estimated $200 billion in interest
costs that taxpayers will have to absorb over the next 30 years by
financing the government's share of the bailout through increased
borrowing.
   ``We've got garbage and none of us wants to carry it out,'' said
Rep. Sam Gibbons, D-Fla., who proposed the surtax. ``So what we're
saying is that our children and grandchildren are going to carry it
out. That's just morally and ethically wrong.''
   Gibbons' proposed surtax effectively would have added $150 in
taxes a year for every $10,000 in federal income taxes paid by an
individual, family or company.
   It was defeated on a 10-13 vote after Rep. Frank J. Guarini,
D-N.J., said it would only ``derail everything that's been done''
in view of President Bush's campaign pledge of ``no new taxes.''
   ``I think the train already has left the station,'' Guarini
said, referring to a no-new-tax agreement on the budget approved
Wednesday by the House and up for a vote in the Senate today. ``I'm
not looking for a train wreck at this point.''
   However, the committee reaffirmed its vote last week to make the
bailout part of the federal deficit, defeating Bush's proposal to
finance it through private bond sales in order to make it appear
that the deficit is being reduced.
   The Congressional Budget Office and others have estimated Bush's
plan would cost taxpayers an additional $4.5 billion in interest
costs over the next 30 years than if the money was borrowed
directly from the Treasury.
</TEXT>
