<HEAD>1 Big Lotto Win, But Bad TV Numbers Cause Disappointments</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A $21.3 million jackpot is awaiting one
lottery ticket holder, and disappointment is in store for countless
others who saw the wrong numbers on TV.
   California's Lotto 6-49 drawing Wednesday night was broadcast
live from Sacramento to the stations that usually carry it. Rather
than break into a Dodgers baseball game, KTTV in Los Angeles
superimposed the numbers.
   Lotto officials said the station told them a technical mixup
caused numbers from the April 12 drawing to appear by mistake. KTTV
interrupted its game broadcast a short time later to give the
correct numbers and explain the error.
   ``We've had calls from people who said they had the winning
number but they tore up their tickets,'' said lottery spokeswoman
Joanne McNabb.
   Those people can file a claim with the lottery security office,
she said.
   Many other callers complained that they mistakenly thought they
had won the jackpot or one of the lesser prizes, which range down
to $5.
   Lottery officials Thursday said only one jackpot-winning ticket
was sold, but they had not yet verified the name of a winner.
   For the record, the numbers were 10, 22, 26, 31, 33, 46, and the
bonus number, 37.
