<HEAD>Bright &amp; Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Funeral directors deal with grief every
day, so when death takes a holiday _ or morticians hold a
convention _ they do their best to lighten up.
   While many of the meetings cover topics such as ``OSHA
Regulations _ Formaldehyde Content in the Preparation Room,''
there's always time to share a light story.
   ``We've even had a request to put racing stripes on a casket,''
said M.E. Garrett of the Clarksburg Casket Co. ``That may not be
consistent with my sense of taste or yours, but it was important to
the survivors.''
   The casket was for a young man killed in an auto racing
accident. The stripes on the coffin matched those on his car.
   Ray Surface of the Clark Grave Vault Co. said he likes to bring
a gimmick to conventions to break up the crowd. He places a book
titled ``Sex Report'' on a table in front of his booth.
   Passersby are stunned by exploding caps that go off when the
book is opened.
   ``We have a good time at our conventions,'' Surface said.
``Funeral directors don't get out much, so when they do ...''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SWEETWATER, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It's time for the annual Critter
Barbecue contest and, as usual, they're having a hard time finding
judges.
   Pork and chicken are at hand for this weekend's cookout, but
there's also a critter category for hunters and their squirrels,
deer, rabbits and ``other.''
   ``Last year we cooked 27 groundhogs,'' said competitor Larry
Anderson. ``We should have won first place, but some of the judges
refused to taste it.''
   The event's organizers are having trouble finding judges willing
to taste everything, said Alice Worrell, an organizer.
   Critters, for purposes of the contest, are defined as anything
that can't be bought in a local grocery store, including alligator,
buffalo and possum.
   Anderson said this year his team, the Mule Skinners, will cook
bear, venison and antelope, but its main entry is a secret.
   ``It's a four-legged creature, and it's prepared by Amish
friends. It'll probably take about five minutes to cook. It can't
lose,'' he said.
