<FIRST>u w AM-Inflation Bjt   05-18 0953</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Inflation, Bjt,910</SECOND>
<HEAD>Steepest Gasoline Price Hike on Record Sends Inflation Rate Skyward</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The largest one-month jump in gasoline prices
since the government began keeping track in the 1930s sent the
overall inflation rate for consumers soaring 0.7 percent in April,
the sharpest advance in more than two years, the government said
Thursday.
   The Labor Department said gasoline prices skyrocketed 11.4
percent in April, following substantial gains of 2.1 percent in
March and 1.7 percent in February.
   Financial markets, noting the heavy influence of the energy
price gains, which are not expected to repeat in the coming months,
shrugged off the bad news. The Dow Jones industrial stock average
slipped 5 points in the first half hour of trading but then quickly
recovered.
   The overall April increase, if it continued for 12 months, would
amount to an annual inflation rate of 8.1 percent. It was the
sharpest climb since an identical 0.7 percent gain in January 1987.
   For the first four months of 1989, inflation was running at an
annual rate of 6.6 percent, half again the 4.4 percent rate posted
for both 1988 and 1987.
   The Bush administration, which is hoping inflation will moderate
and allow the Federal Reserve Board to push down interest rates,
read the report favorably.
   ``We think it's kind of like a bulge moving through the economy.
Other than energy prices, inflation looks like it's in pretty good
shape,'' White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said.
   Energy accounted for about 60 percent of the April advance. The
previous monthly record for gasoline was 7.4 percent, hit in
January 1987 and March 1974.
   The department noted, however, that although gasoline prices
have zoomed upward 16.7 percent this year, they were still 17.7
percent below their peak in March 1981 during the OPEC oil crisis.
   The 5.1 percent advance for all energy costs also set a record
and followed a 1.1 percent rise in March. Home heating oil prices
rose 2.2 percent; natural gas and electricity prices were up 0.6
percent.
   Economist S. Jay Levy of Levy Economic Forecasts in Chappaqua,
N.Y., said that crude oil prices, which have jumped about 30
percent since the start of the year, have already eased somewhat.
But, that won't necessarily translate immediately into relief for
motorists at the gasoline pump, he said.
   ``Gasoline could very well increase further because of a
shortage of refining capacity and because of an increase in
seasonal demand during the summer,'' he said.
   On Tuesday, the federal Energy Information Administration
projected that gasoline prices, for all grades, would rise by the
summer to an average of $1.09 per gallon from $1.05 currently. The
average price last summer was 99 cents a gallon.
   Food and beverage costs in April rose a moderate 0.5 percent.
Prices for fats and oils, meat and poultry, dairy products, baked
goods and fruits and vegetables all rose. Prices of sugar and
sweets fell a slight 0.1 percent.
   Levy said food prices were no longer being influenced by last
year's drought, but he said it was too soon to tell if this year's
growing conditions will be favorable enough to bring food prices
down.
   The rate of inflation excluding the volatile food and energy
areas, a calculation analysts say is often a better measure of
underlying inflationary pressures than the broader index, rose only
0.2 percent in April. The annualized rate for this ``core''
inflation from February through April was 4.2 percent, down from a
4.9 percent in the preceding six months.
   Economist Lawrence A. Hunter of the U.S. Chamber of Commerce
said the report ``should be clear and convincing evidence to the
Fed that the time has come to ease interest rates.''
   But economist Michael Moran of Daiwa Securities America Inc.
said that, while the Fed may read the report positively, it will
not interpret it as a signal to ease credit restraints.
   ``They need to keep a firm grip on policy or the secondary
effects of energy prices could become important,'' he said. ``Many
items consume energy in their production process. And the overall
(consumer) index (including energy) is the basis for many
cost-of-living increases,'' including those in Social Security
benefits.
   The April figures left the overall Consumer Price Index at 123.1
percent of its 1982-84 base, meaning that a hypothetical selection
of goods costing $100 during the base period would have cost
$123.10 in April, 80 cents more than in March.
   In a separate report, the Labor Department said Americans'
average weekly earnings, after adjusting for inflation, rose 1.2
percent in April after falling 0.3 percent a month earlier.
   Average weekly earnings in April, before adjusting for
inflation, were $334.08, up 4.3 percent from a year earlier. Taking
the 5.3 percent inflation rate for urban workers into account over
the 12-month period, real weekly earnings were down 0.9 percent.
   The Labor Department offered these other details on price
changes in April:
   _Apparel prices rose a modest 0.3 percent after jumping 1.4
percent a month earlier. Early spring sales of women's clothing
somewhat offset the normal price increases at the start of a season.
   _Medical care costs were up 0.5 percent, the same as in March.
   _Entertainment prices climbed 0.6 percent, double the March rate
of 0.3 percent.
   _Transportation costs, reflecting gasoline hikes, rose 2.1
percent, the sharpest in nearly seven years. New car prices rose a
slight 0.1 percent, reflecting manufacturers' incentives to bolster
lagging sales; used car prices fell 0.3 percent.
   _The cost of services climbed a modest 0.2 percent in April even
though the labor market remains tight. The moderate increase came
despite a 0.9 percent hike for the cost of telephone services,
reflecting a nationwide increase in line access charges.
</TEXT>
