<HEAD>Hedda Nussbaum Leaves Hospital and Moves to Apartment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hedda Nussbaum, the battered woman who testified
against Joel Steinberg in the death of their illegally adopted
6-year-old daughter, has been released from a psychiatric hospital
and moved to an apartment.
   One of Nussbaum's lawyers, Betty Levinson, was quoted in
Thursday's Daily News as saying Nussbaum was discharged from Four
Winds Psychiatric Hospital in Katonah several weeks ago.
   Nussbaum is in outpatient therapy and also attends weekly
meetings of a support group for battered women, Levinson said.
   Steinberg, Nussbaum's former live-in lover, was convicted
earlier this year of manslaughter and sentenced to up to 25 years
in prison in Lisa's death.
   The child was found beaten unconscious in the couple's Greenwich
Village apartment and died three days later.
   Charges against Nussbaum were dropped after prosecutors
concluded that she had been so severely beaten by Steinberg that
she was unable to aid the child.
   Nussbaum, a former children's book editor, is on disability
insurance until she finds a job, Levinson said. She has also filed
a $3 million suit against Steinberg and sold the TV rights to her
story, reportedly for $100,000.
