<HEAD>Execution Scheduled Tonight</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: DELETES 5th graf, `Fleming's attorneys ...', which refers to
other inmate in case.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge today refused to stay the execution
of a murderer who is scheduled to die tonight in Georgia's electric
chair.
   Henry Willis III, 36, was sentenced to death for his part in the
Feb. 11, 1976, killing of Ray City Police Chief Ed Giddens.
   Superior Court Judge Hal Craig today denied Willis' request for
a stay of execution. His attorney, Millard Farmer, said he was
preparing an appeal to the Georgia Supreme Court.
   The state board of Pardons and Paroles also scheduled a clemency
hearing on Willis' case in Atlanta.
   Giddens was 29 when he was abducted and killed after he stopped
a car matching the description of one wanted in a robbery. He had
resigned and was one day away from moving to Florida to manage a
citrus farm.
   Giddens was taken to a Lanier County swamp in southern Georgia
where he was shot when he ran from his abductors. He was shot again
at close range in the face and thrown into the swamp, according to
trial testimony.
   A friend of Giddens, Robert Swanson, now Alapaha chief of
police, was in the swamp when Giddens' body was found.
   ``It was coldblooded murder,'' Swanson said Wednesday. ``A man's
last night on the force, he has two little boys, he begged for his
life, and they killed him. ... Henry Willis will get what is coming
to him.''
   Willis was one of three people tried in connection with Giddens'
death. Son Fleming is on death row and Larry Fleming, Son's nephew,
was sentenced to life in prison.
   The U.S. Supreme Court in February refused to hear Willis'
appeal on grounds that automatic challenges to exclude blacks from
the jury that heard his case violated his right to a trial by his
peers.
   The court in 1986 barred prosecutors from using such jury
strikes to exclude jurors on the basis of race, but the ruling was
not made retroactive.
   Willis was raised by his paternal grandmother, Ruthie Willis,
who said she does not have the money to bury him.
   ``If he done that, I think he should die because the Bible says
`He that kill, shall be killed,''' she said. ``It's hurtin' me all
over.''
</TEXT>
