<DOCNO> AP890518-0124 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-18-89 1428EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-ReaganonRushmore     05-18 0422</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Reagan on Rushmore,440</SECOND>
<HEAD>For Ronald Reagan, They Want a Profile in Granite</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE FEINSILBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some admirers, convinced Ronald Reagan's place
in history will be monumental, think the place for a monument to
him is amid the greats on Mount Rushmore.
   But Tom Griffith, executive secretary of the Mount Rushmore
Society in Rapid City, S.D., suggests they have rocks in their
heads.
   ``Why fool with a masterpiece?'' asks Griffith. ``Would you
paint another figure next to the Mona Lisa?''
   The idea of adding Reagan to Mount Rushmore was advanced in 1984
by Frank Fahrenkopf Jr., then Republican national chairman. But its
current champion is R. Emmett Tyrrell Jr., editor of the American
Spectator, a monthly conservative review.
   He says Reagan earned a place on the mountaintop, beside
Washington, Jefferson, Lincoln and Theodore Roosevelt, because ``he
brought peace and prosperity to a country riven by fear.''
   He sounds half serious _ and half not-so-serious _ but he says
he did raise the idea with Reagan over dinner last July.
   Reagan ``smiled,'' he said.
   Ever since word got out, Tyrrell said, he has been dogged by
``the maniacs in favor and the maniacs against.''
   Out of ecological consideration, he said, he'd be willing to
cast a concrete Reagan nose and chin and an ear or two and
helicopter them in, keeping blasting on the mountain to a minimum.
Washington's head has a serious crack, and no one wants to make
that worse.
   Also promoting the idea is Young Americans for Freedom, which
sent out an add-Reagan-to-Rushmore ballot in 23,000 fund-raising
letters. The results will be counted in June, said Tom Lizardo, YAF
executive director, and if the response is an enthusiastic
go-for-it, YAF may petition the Interior Department.
   ``It won't happen,'' says Griffith, whose organization raised
the original $1 million required for 360 workmen to dynamite and
drill the visages of the four presidents into a granite cliff in
the Black Hills of South Dakota between 1927 and 1941.
   The faces are the largest carved figures anywhere. Washington's
is as high as a five-story building, bigger than any sphinx in
Egypt.
   ``The simple fact is there is no more suitable rock to carve
anyone at Mount Rushmore,'' Griffith said.
   Tyrrell argues that surely Reagan could be tucked in on
Washington's right side, or between Roosevelt and Lincoln.
   As for the cost, he'd have the people of South Dakota handle
that.
   ``It's going to be their tourist trap,'' he said, ``and they
ought to pay for it.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
