<FILEID>AP-NR-05-18-89 1458EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-China-Press     05-18 0456</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Press,0481</SECOND>
<HEAD>Press Gives Unexpected Coverage to Demonstrations</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRIL JONES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China's state-controlled media gave unprecedented
coverage Thursday to students and workers demonstrating for
democratic reform.
   The reporting was astonishing in its frankness, speed and clear
sympathy with protesters for the heavily censored press.
   ``One Million From All Walks of Life Demonstrate in Support of
Hunger-Striking Students,'' read the banner headline on the
People's Daily, the official organ of the Communist Party.
   Protests since mid-April have gone largely unreported, and many
Chinese relied on Western media coverage for accurate accounts.
   ``Large-scale Demonstrations in More Than 20 Cities
Nationwide,'' read the headline in the Guangming Daily. It was one
of seven front-page stories on the protests.
   ``The condition of the students and the future of the country
touched the heart of every Chinese who has a conscience,'' the
newspaper said.
   Chinese were hungry for news of the democracy movement.
   ``There is no free press, and that breeds corruption,'' said Xue
Yong, a novelist from Hebei province at Tiananmen on Thursday.
``It's only in the last couple of days that we've seen fairly
objective reporting. That's the great sorrow of China's media.''
   ``We depend a great deal on the foreign press. We don't trust
the Chinese media,'' said a worker at a chemical factory.
   It would have been hard for newspapers to ignore the story.
   More than 1 million people swarmed into the streets of the
capital Wednesday to call for democracy. It was largest show of
public defiance in 40 years of communist rule.
   Of six articles on the front page of the People's Daily, five
were about the demonstrations. Only a small bottom corner was
devoted to the historic visit to China by Soviet President Mikhail
S. Gorbachev for the first Sino-Soviet summit in 30 years.
   The student protests began with the April 15 death of Hu
Yaobang, an ousted Communist Party chief who pushed for democratic
reforms. But the first sympathetic coverage came only on April 23,
after journalists at the daily Science and Technology News
threatened to quit.
   And it wasn't until this week that many newspapers followed suit.
   When more than 3,000 students began a hunger strike on Saturday,
a press emboldened by the Science and Technology News' article
began Western-like coverage. Newspapers carried accurate and fairly
complete accounts of events and details of the students demands,
including a free press.
   Electronic media, though slower, have also picked up on the
trend.
   Beijing TV interrupted programming four times Thursday with news
updates on the demonstrations. China Central Television's evening
news showed leaders visiting hunger strikers in a hospital.
   Newscasters read letters from viewers calling for authorities to
agree to meet with the fasters.
</TEXT>
