<FIRST>u i AM-Lebanon 1stLd-Writethru a0601 05-18 0641</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0601,0654</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fighting Reported in South Lebanon</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 7th graf ``Shortages of ...'' to ADD closing
of East German Embassy.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An argument over subsidized flour ended
in shelling that killed one civilian and wounded five Thursday in a
Palestinian refugee camp on the outskirts of Sidon in south
Lebanon, police reported.
   Police in the ancient port 25 miles south of Beirut said two
155mm shells were fired from positions manned by the South Lebanon
Army militia in nearby Jezzine and landed at the edge of the Ein
el-Hilweh camp.
   The Sunni Nasserite militia that controls Sidon said earlier it
had gone on alert because the militia threatened to shell the city
if its border enclave did not receive a share of
government-subsidized flour being unloaded at the port.
   Israel sponsors the South Lebanon Army, a predominantly
Christian militia that helps patrol a ``security zone'' north of
the border. Israel established the zone, ranging in depth from six
to 10 miles, when most of its soldiers withdrew in June 1985 after
a three-year occupation.
   A statement from the Nasserite militia said the zone's share of
flour was ``ready and waiting for someone to come and receive it.
It is the share of the Lebanese people in the enclave, which the
Lebanese government has bought. We never tried to deny the Lebanese
people its food.''
   About 225,000 people live in the zone, including 25,000 who have
fled south since March 8, when an artillery war began in Beirut
between a Syrian-Druse alliance and Christian army units led by
Gen. Michele Aoun.
   Shortages of flour, fuel and other supplies have developed since
the Beirut port was closed by the shelling.
   East Germany said it was closing its embassy in Beirut
temporarily and withdrawing the staff because the building had
suffered heavy shelling damage. A dispatch from Berlin by the
official East German news agency ADN did not say how many people
were involved.
   In Beirut, leaders of the Lebanon's 900,000 Sunni Moslem said a
senior aide to Sheik Hassan Khaled, the slain grand mufti, would
carry out his duties until a new spiritual leader was elected. They
did not set a date for the election.
   Sheik Mohammed Rashid Kabbani, the 46-year-old aide, has been in
charge of Khaled's office. The mufti and 21 other people were
killed by a car bomb Tuesday in Moslem west Beirut.
   Arab League envoy Lakhdar Ibrahimi met with Lebanese leaders on
how to consolidate a cease-fire in the artillery battle.
   ``All sides have assured me that the cease-fire will continue,''
he said. The truce was called a week ago.
   Syrian gunners and the Druse militiamen of Walid Jumblatt have
continued shelling the Christian coastline north of Beirut to
prevent Aoun from receiving weapons and ammunition by sea.
   A police spokesman said 20 rockets and howitzer shells fired
from west Beirut, where Syrian troops are stationed, hit the
Christian coastal area Thursday. No casualties were reported.
   He said there was no response from Aoun's gunners in the
310-square-mile Christian enclave north and east of Beirut.
   By police count, 359 people have been killed and 1,393 wounded
since the shooting started two days after Aoun's forces blockaded
illegal ports operated by Moslem militias.
   Syria has 40,000 soldiers in Lebanon under an Arab League
peacekeeping mandate issued in 1976, a year after the Lebanese
civil war began, and has become the nation's main power broker.
   Violations of the truce have prevented deployment of 321
military observers from six Arab nations under terms of the
cease-fire agreement.
   After conferring in Christian east Beirut with Nasrallah Sfeir,
the Maronite Catholic patriarch, Ibrahimi said he hoped next week's
Arab summit in Morocco would ``consolidate the truce by adopting
the appropriate resolutions.'' He did not elaborate.
</TEXT>
