<FIRST>r i AM-Summit-Elevator     05-18 0190</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Summit-Elevator,0196</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Leaders, Raisa Get Stuck on Elevator</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Summit, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SHANGHAI, China (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One-fourth of the Soviet Union's ruling
Politburo, including Mikhail S. Gorbachev, got stuck in an elevator
Thursday while they were on their way to an elevator factory.
   Gorbachev, his wife, Raisa, and two of his closest advisers,
Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze and Alexander Yakovlev,
left a fifth-floor briefing on the operations of the Minhang
Economic and Technological Development Zone and were escorted to a
waiting elevator.
   A moment later, the lift's door opened on the same floor, and
Shevardnadze stepped out. It closed and reopened, and Yakovlev got
out. Then the Gorbachevs and their bodyguards.
   ``Too heavy,'' suggested a reporter.
   ``No,'' replied Gorbachev. ``It's your Western technology.''
   The Soviet president and his entourage then went to visit the
Shanghai Mitsubishi Elevator Co. Ltd., a joint venture between
Chinese and Japanese manufacturing firms.
   Gorbachev, who left a short time later for Moscow ending a
four-day trip to China, is seeking to encourage Soviet enterprises
to modernize by taking in foreign partners in joint ventures
similar to those that have enjoyed success in China.
</TEXT>
