<FILEID>AP-NR-05-18-89 1608EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-US-Cyprus     05-18 0222</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Cyprus,230</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Department Praises Implementation of Agreement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department praised Greek and Turkish
forces on Thursday for implementing a disengagement agreement in
Cyprus this week.
   Greek and Turkish Cypriot forces abandoned 24 military positions
along a line dividing Nicosia, capital of the east Mediterranean
island.
   The disengagement agreement, brokered by the U.N. peacekeeping
force based on the island since 1964, was aimed at reducing tension
along the buffer zone that runs through the old, walled section of
the city.
   ``This represents an important practical step towards
alleviating tensions and averting incidents. It is a measure which
we strongly supported,'' said State Department spokesman Richard
Boucher.
   ``We congratulate the parties concerned and the United Nations
which worked with them to bring about this success. This
deconfrontation agreement is the product of leadership and of
vision,'' he said.
   Boucher added that the United States hopes implementation of the
initial phase of the agreement will enable progress on resolving
the fundamental dispute over control of the island.
   Cyprus has been divided since July 1974, when the Turkish Army
invaded after a short-lived coup by militant supporters of union
with Greece.
   The Turks seized the northern one-third of the island. The
minority Turkish Cypriots, who make up 18 percent of the 650,000
population, declared a breakaway republic there in 1983.
</TEXT>
