<FILEID>AP-NR-05-18-89 1638EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Judges     05-18 0480</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Judges,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Panel Pushing Ahead With Judge Candidate Despite Cranston</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A San Francisco attorney will remain under
Senate consideration as a federal judge despite a thumbs down from
home-state Sen. Alan Cranston, the chairman of the Senate Judiciary
Committee said Thursday.
   Sen. Joseph Biden, D-Del., said Cranston has submitted a
negative ``blue slip'' on the nomination of Vaughn Walker, which
under the customs that once prevailed within the Senate would have
been sufficient to put an immediate end to the lawyer's candidacy
for the bench.
   But Biden said, ``I have no desire to hold up'' Walker.
   Still, Biden said the opposition from Cranston ``will affect
Walker negatively.'' And the nomination was held back Thursday as
the committee sent all other current judicial nominees to the full
Senate with favorable recommendations.
   Cranston, D-Calif., has sought to sidetrack Walker's nomination
to the U.S. District Court, saying that last year before the
committee Walker went too far in defending a private club that has
been alleged to discriminate against women and that he was too slow
to resign from membership.
   California's other senator, Republican Pete Wilson, has urged
confirmation of Walker.
   According to Biden, the custom of allowing a single member of
the Judiciary Committee to kill a judicial nomination ended when
Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., became chairman.
   Biden said that under his own chairmanship one negative ``blue
slip'' from a home-state senator could veto a candidate only if the
administration had failed to consult with senators before making
the nomination.
   He said such consultation would have to be serious. ``If it's
perfunctory, there's going to be a problem,'' Biden said.
   The nominations sent to the full Senate were those of Pamela Ann
Rhymer of Los Angeles and Ferdinand F. Fernandez as judges of the
9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, Robert C. Bonner of Pasadena,
Calif., as a judge of the U.S. District Court for the Central
District of California and Melinda F. Harmon of Houston as a judge
of the District Court for the Southern District of Texas.
   Biden said it was unclear when Walker would get a new hearing.
He said questions had been raised by the committee staff and he had
not reviewed them to determine if they were worth pursuing at the
cost of further delay.
   Walker was a member of San Francisco's Olympic Club until Feb.
1, when he resigned, saying he had enjoyed being a member but
``unfortunately, the club's present membership practices are
wrongly based on a policy of exclusion.''
   He said the club ``has certainly recently demonstrated that
race, ethnicity, religion and other arbitrary factors do not play a
role in club membership.''
   ``Nonetheless,'' he added, ``I, as a member of the club, have
been disappointed that the club has not taken longer strides toward
making full membership status available to women.''
</TEXT>
