<FIRST>r w AM-US-China     05-18 0205</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-China,200</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Department Issues Alert About Travel to China</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department issued an alert Thursday
about travel to China, advising Americans going there to use ``good
sense'' and avoid the massive demonstrations.
   ``The Department of State advises Americans traveling to China
to use caution and avoid areas where demonstrations are
occurring,'' State Department spokesman Richard Boucher said.
   He said there was no indication of any anti-foreign feeling
among the demonstrators. ``Nonetheless,'' he added, ``caution, good
sense, and discretion are called for to ensure that Americans are
not caught up in a demonstration.''
   Boucher stressed that the alert does not advise against travel
to China, only that ``caution should be exercised.''
   Meanwhile, the Senate Foreign Relations Committee approved a
resolution urging China to ``take all necessary steps to establish
a just and democratic society, with a free and open political
system that will protect the essential human rights of all people
living within the country.''
   The resolution, sponsored by Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., said
Secretary of State James A. Baker III should tell Chinese leaders
that ``official violence directed at those who would peacefully
demonstrate for democracy, liberty and justice will seriously
damage relations with the United States.''
