<FIRST>r a AM-TiptonLawsuit     05-18 0338</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tipton Lawsuit,0348</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawsuit Filed Over Female Jazz Musician Who Lived as a Man</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SPOKANE, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman whose baby son was adopted in 1963
by Billy Tipton has sued the late jazz musician's estate because
Tipton turned out to be a woman posing as a man.
   Patricia Clark, in the suit filed Wednesday in Superior Court,
alleged Tipton defrauded her by promising to be a good father to
the boy, Jon Clark.
   Tipton's death in January from a bleeding ulcer revealed that
the leader of a jazz trio was a woman.
   Tipton, believed to be 75 years old at death, had apparently
assumed a man's identity early in life in hope of succeeding in the
male-dominated field of jazz.
   Ms. Clark said she felt angry and betrayed when she learned
Tipton's secret. She said her fragile relationship with her son,
who has known she was his mother since 1986, has been shattered.
She is seeking unspecified damages.
   Jon Clark, however, said that he's never been close to Ms. Clark
and that she might be another of many people trying to profit from
Tipton's story.
   ``I owe my dad and I don't owe anyone else,'' Jon Clark said.
``I really want people to know what kind of person he was. It's too
bad we all have to fight and argue after someone like him dies.''
   Kitty Oakes, who lived as Tipton's wife after 1960 until they
separated about 10 years ago, said there is no basis for the
lawsuit.
   ``Nobody committed fraud,'' said Ms. Oakes, executor of the
estate. ``I never met her before the adoption and nobody lied to
her. She's just out to make a buck.''
   L. Neil Axtell, Ms. Clark's attorney, said the estate is worth
about $150,000 but could increase because of movie, TV and tabloid
offers the family has received since Tipton's death.
   Tipton, a pianist and saxophone player, traveled throughout the
West with the Billy Tipton Trio in the 1950s before settling in
Spokane and becoming a musicians' agent.
</TEXT>
