<FILEID>AP-NR-05-18-89 1957EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Bomb-Candy     05-18 0502</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bomb-Candy,0517</SECOND>
<HEAD>Airport Bomb Alert Over Suspect Packages of Candy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BEN DOBBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government said Thursday it has tipped all
airlines using British airports to be on the lookout for containers
of a Middle Eastern candy that could conceal bombs.
   The Transport Department said it issued an air security alert
after a package of candy was found to contain Semtex, a plastic
explosive.
   It did not identify the candy and gave no further details of the
find. British newspapers published a Transport Department security
memo identifying the candy as ``halawa'' and saying it is similar
in color and texture to Semtex.
   The Czechoslovak-made explosive is odorless, hard to detect and
can be molded into any shape.
   Arabic radio pronounced the name of the candy ``halwa.'' It is
manufactured by companies throughout the Middle East and is
packaged in tins and plastic tubes.
   Newspapers quoted unidentified security officials as saying they
feared Semtex in a candy package could be taken on board, perhaps
by a child, and left with a delayed timer for a later flight.
   Three months ago, the government recommended airline checks on
transistor radios, portable computers, cassette recorders and other
electrical and electronic equipment after investigators announced
that Pan Am Flight 103 had been destroyed by plastic explosive
built into a radio-cassette player.
   The New York-bound jumbo jet blew up over Lockerbie, Scotland,
on Dec. 21, killing 259 people on board and 11 people on the ground.
   At London's Heathrow Airport, police with submachine guns
patrolled terminals and lounges Thursday. Private security staff
employed by U.S. airlines asked passengers detailed questions about
their baggage.
   ``We have been ordered to be on our toes all the time,'' said
one security officer, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   ``All staff have to be more vigilant than ever and must not let
their concentration slip for a moment,'' he said. ``We just don't
know where the next threat is coming from and therefore have to
check anything out of the ordinary.''
   The security memo, published in full by the Daily Express, said
the explosive could be molded to the shape of the circular candy
containers, which are eight inches in diameter, six inches deep and
``and large enough to contain all the components of an IED
(improvised explosive device).''
   ``Arming is achieved by pulling a pin accessible through a small
hole in the casing,'' the newspaper quoted the memo as saying.
``Such an item should feel heavier than expected.''
   ``Airlines should be alert to the possibility of such a device
being left on board aircraft at transit stops,'' it quoted the memo
as saying.
   The Transport Department is testing a computer which its
developer, Science Applications International Corp. of California,
claims can detect any explosive. Semtex is transparent to
conventional X-ray detection.
   The device is undergoing trials at Harwell Nuclear Research
Center in western England and will be introduced in British
airports if the trials show the machine is safe and effective, said
a ministry spokesman.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
