<FILEID>AP-NR-05-18-89 1957EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-KlanTrial     05-18 0359</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Klan Trial,0375</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Klansman Convicted in Death of Black Man Found in Tree</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GARRY MITCHELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOBILE, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An all-white jury convicted a former Ku Klux
Klansman of murder Thursday for supplying the rope and pistol used
to abduct and kill a black teen-ager who was strangled and his body
strung up in a tree.
   The conviction of Benjamin Franklin Cox, 27, was the third
successful prosecution in six years in the 1981 slaying of
19-year-old Michael Donald.
   A federal jury in 1987 ordered the United Klans of America, then
the nation's biggest Klan organization, to pay $7 million to
Donald's mother.
   Cox whispered, ``I love you'' to his weeping wife, Gail, before
he was led away in handcuffs. ``There just must be some mistake,''
said Mrs. Cox.
   A lone black woman in the hallway shouted, ``Hooray for
justice!''
   Cox, a truck driver, could receive 10 years to life in prison.
Circuit Judge Michael Zoghby revoked Cox's $28,000 bail and set
sentencing for June 23.
   The jury deliberated about four hours over two days.
   Donald, a part-time technical college student, was abducted at
gunpoint and at random from a dark city street. He was beaten,
strangled, his throat cut and his body left in a tree, where it was
found the next morning.
   Prosecutors said Donald was killed by Klansmen angry about a
mistrial of a black man charged with killing a white police officer.
   Donald's sister, Cynthia Mitchell, said the conviction ``won't
bring my brother back.''
   Still awaiting trial on a murder charge is Bennie Jack Hays, 72,
a former Klan leader and Cox's father-in-law.
   Cox's brother-in-law, Henry Francis Hays, was convicted of
murder in 1983 and sentenced to death.
   Another ex-Klansman, James ``Tiger'' Knowles, who admitted
helping Henry Hays kill Donald, Knowles pleaded guilty in 1983 to
violating Donald's civil rights. He received a life sentence and
agreed to testify against KKK members.
   The slaying also resulted in a $7 million verdict in favor of
the teen-ager's mother, Beulah Mae Donald. She was given ownership
of the Klan headquarters building in Tuscaloosa, which she sold
before she died last year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890518-0141 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-18-89 1958EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-RuralDevelopment     05-18 0367</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Rural Development,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Panel Chairman Pledges Quick Action on Development Measures</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PHILIP BRASHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate Agriculture Committee chairman
pledged on Thursday that there would be quick action on rural
development measures that could provide $100 million a year in
loans to stimulate businesses.
   ``This legislation will in many ways determine whether we have a
rural America worth saving as we move into the next century,'' said
Sen. Patrick Leahy, D-Vt.
   In addition to providing federal seed money for local revolving
loan funds, the proposed Rural Partnerships Act of 1989 would
earmark $200 million this year to improve education, health
services, communications and utilities in rural areas to encourage
business development.
   Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell, D-Maine, has promised to
move the legislation to the Senate floor in late June to ensure its
passage this year, Leahy said at a news conference where he was
joined by six of the bill's 23 co-sponsors.
   ``There have been some hard times in the heartland. This bill
sends forth a message of hope,'' said Sen. Kent Conrad, D-N.D.,
architect of the legislation's lending program.
   The $100 million in seed money would be aimed at encouraging
banks to increase investments in new or expanding businesses in
rural areas.
   The federal funds would be matched by money from the private
sector and put into revolving funds for loans, loan guarantees and
investments in businesses with fewer than 100 employees.
   The revolving funds would be operated by states, local
governments or economic development groups, assuring local control
of the lending program, sponsors said.
   Other provisions would provide money to:
   _Upgrade telephone lines so rural businesses would have access
to such services as digital switching and fiber optics necessary
for some computer operations.
   _Improve health care and education with telecommunications links
to rural hospitals and schools.
   _Assist communities to comply with federal water standards.
   The $300 million package is a ``modest step forward'' that
recognizes federal budget constraints, Leahy said. He had said he
wanted to put $500 million into the program.
   ``We're dealing with the realities of the budget and $300
million ... is a lot better than nothing, and that's the
alternative,'' he said.
</TEXT>
