<FILEID>AP-NR-05-18-89 2033EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Argentina     05-18 0495</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Argentina,0514</SECOND>
<HEAD>Current, Future Governments Work Together on Economic Issues</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BAI1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED McCULLOUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Peronist Party, which swept
recent presidential elections, will work with the outgoing
government to bring the faltering economy under control,
President-elect Carlos Menem said Thursday.
   ``We are not assuming any compromises,'' Menem said after
meeting with President Raul Alfonsin for the first time since his
Sunday victory. ``We are simply trying, together with the national
government, to alleviate this situation.''
   The battered economy was the principal issue in the presidential
campaign and the chief issue that defeated government candidate,
Eduardo Angeloz.
   In a first joint step, economists representing both governments
will travel to the United States for negotiations on Argentina's
$59 billion foreign debt with creditor banks, Menem said.
   No details were disclosed, but they were expected to discuss
arrearages, estimated at about $3.5 billion, and new loans, which
have been blocked for nearly a year.
   The meeting between Menem, of the Peronist Party, and Alfonsin,
of the Radical Civic Union, was part of an attempt by both parties
to stabilize Argentina's troubled economy until Menem's six-year
term begins on Dec. 10.
   Peronist Party economic proposals call for a ``social pact''
among workers, businessmen and the government, and a vague
``productive revolution'' to generate employment, double
agricultural harvests and exploit natural resources.
   All will require significant sacrifice from Argentines and Menem
can't risk losing public support by being seen to support failed
Radical Civic Union policies.
   But the economic problems are so pressing, the Peronists can't
sit on the sidelines, either. The national budget deficit is vast,
inflation might top 50 percent this month, and the currency, the
austral, continues its spectacular devaluation.
   The government has not paid interest on its foreign debt since
late last year and principal payments were deferred several years
ago. This year, interest bills amount to $6 billion, about twice
the expected trade surplus and foreign exchange reserves in the
Central Bank are very low, Menem said.
   ``We're not betting on this government's failure,'' Peronist
national deputy and potential economy minister Edward Bauza said
Wednesday after the party endorsed utility price increases needed
to shore up the budget.
   In addition, Menem hopes to quell uncertainty about his
worker-oriented policies. Rumors about them helped to spur the
dramatic devaluation of the currency in the last months.
   ``Our government is not going to embargo deposits, nor
confiscate foreign exchange, nor open security boxes, or anything
like that,'' said Eduardo Menem, a national senator, brother and
key advisor to the president-elect.
   Economic problems are generating political pressures.
   The 4 million-member General Labor Confederation, which backed
Menem in the election, is demanding that the monthly minimum wage
be raised by 125 percent, to the equivalent of about $64 by June 1.
   Some commuter trains were disrupted Wednesday by wildcat
strikes, and bus owners in the capital threaten to strike next week
if they are not allowed to raise fares.
</TEXT>
