<FIRST>r w AM-DroughtRelief     05-18 0220</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drought Relief,200</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wheat-State Senators Introduce Relief Extension</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senators from wheat-growing states introduced
relief legislation Thursday for farmers whose winter crops have
been devastated by this year's drought.
   ``Our bill is simple and straightforward,'' said Sen. Bob Dole,
R-Kan. ``We believe it is time to extend the 1988 relief act to
crops planted in 1988 but harvested in 1989.'' He said it would
cover mostly winter wheat.
   Provisions would be administered along the lines of last year
concerning payment rates, benefits and requirements on federal crop
insurance participation in future years, Dole said.
   The legislation also calls for $25 million to transport
livestock to areas where feed and water exist and $25 million for
livestock producers who have had to spend money on emergency water
projects.
   Money saved under the deficiency payment program would be used
to cover the cost of the legislation.
   Sen. David Boren, D-Okla., said about $500 million in federal
deficiency payments was saved because of higher market prices on
wheat. The money would have gone to farmers if wheat prices had
been below the federally set target price.
   Joining Dole and Boren in sponsoring were Sens. Nancy Landon
Kassebaum, R-Kan.; Don Nickles, R-Okla.; Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas;
Phil Gramm, R-Texas; Max Baucus, D-Mont.; Conrad Burns, R-Mont.;
Timothy Wirth, D-Colo.; and David Pryor, D-Ark.
