<FIRST>r a AM-AlcoholLawsuit     05-18 0414</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Alcohol Lawsuit,0426</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jurors Feel Little Sympathy For Woman Who Sued Jim Beam</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Candance is cq.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATIA BLACKBURN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jurors who cleared a liquor company of negligence
for failing to warn a pregnant woman about the dangers of drinking
say they felt little sympathy for her.
   Members of the federal jury Wednesday said Candance Thorp should
have known drinking while pregnant could harm her unborn child.
   Mrs. Thorp and her husband, Harold, sought about $4 million from
Jim Beam Brands Co. for lifetime care for their 4-year-old son,
Michael, born with deformities, retardation and other problems
categorized as symptoms of fetal alcohol syndrome.
   ``I was surprised they were actually suing Jim Beam,'' said
juror Staci Gilbreth. ``I know that (Jim Beam whiskey) was what she
drank the most, but my gosh. We wondered if it was just that Jim
Beam had the most money.''
   ``They could have sued everyone,'' said Geraldine Jackson,
another juror, referring to testimony Mrs. Thorp was seen drinking
beer in bars several times during her pregnancy.
   Mrs. Thorp, 39, testified she was an alcoholic who drank as much
as half a fifth of Jim Beam a day during her pregnancy, but said
she would have stopped drinking if warning labels meant for
pregnant women were on the bottles.
   ``We're obviously disappointed with the verdict, but the jury
system operates,'' said the Thorps' lawyer, Barry Epstein.
   No decision was made on an appeal, he said.
   During the trial, Epstein said the alcohol company had an
obligation to warn the public of the risks of drinking while
pregnant.
   Witnesses said Mrs. Thorp was warned repeatedly by relatives and
friends about the dangers and that she and other alcoholics would
not have heeded a warning on a label.
   Jurors said they decided the danger of to unborn babies was
common knowledge and said that was a factor in their decision to
deny damages.
   Attorneys said the case was the first against a liquor company
for birth defects linked to alcohol. Two similar cases are pending
in Washington state courts.
   About 1 percent of the infants born in the United States each
year, or 35,000 babies, are born with fetal alcohol syndrome.
Symptoms include slow growth, central nervous system impairment,
hyperactivity, retardation and facial deformities.
   A federal law goes into effect in November requiring that all
bottles of liquor, wine and beer to carry a label warning that
drinking while pregnant may be hazardous to fetuses.
</TEXT>
