<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Corruption     05-18 0278</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Corruption,0287</SECOND>
<HEAD>Second Official Denies Corruption</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investigators who linked him to a corruption probe
are lying, a former member of the Communist Party's ruling
Politburo said in a statement released Thursday.
   The statement by Mikhail S. Solomentsev, who was retired from
the Politburo in September, was read at a regular briefing by
Foreign Ministry spokesman Vadim Perfiliev.
   ``I believe it is my party and civic duty to state that the
assertions by the investigators of the U.S.S.R. Procurator
General's Office are a brazen provocation, a vile and downright
base lie,'' the statement said.
   ``Never and under no circumstances had I given a pretext for
such accusations.''
   Before his retirement, Solomentsev was in charge of the Party
Control Commission, which disciplines party members who violate
rules.
   His statement followed by two days a denial by Politburo member
Yegor K. Ligachev, who has been considered a conservative
counterweight to President Mikhail S. Gorbachev and a potential
rival.
   Perfiliev also read Ligachev's statement, which previously had
been distributed by Novosti news agency.
   Solomentsev and Ligachev were reacting to statements made by
criminal investigators Telman Gdlyan and Nikolai Ivanov, who are
famous throughout the Soviet Union for their probe into corruption
in Uzbekistan.
   Both Ligachev and Solomentsev said they demanded an
investigation of the charges, and that the results be published.
   Gdlyan was elected to the new Congress of People's Deputies
parliament in March with about 87 percent of the vote in a Moscow
region.
   On Sunday, two days after mentioning Ligachev and Solomentsev in
connection with the continuing investigation, Ivanov won 61 percent
of the vote in a race among more than two dozen candidates in
Leningrad.
</TEXT>
