<FILEID>AP-NR-05-18-89 2103EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-MissileDispute     05-18 0422</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Missile Dispute,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dickinson Seeks Early Showdown on MX-Midgetman Dispute</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID PACE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The ranking Republican on the House Armed
Services Committee called Thursday for an early congressional
showdown over President Bush's plan to proceed with development of
two kinds of land-based nuclear missiles.
   Rep. Bill Dickinson, R-Ala., asked Defense Secretary Dick Cheney
to seek congressional approval if he intends to use money
designated for deployment of the rail-mobile MX missile to keep the
Midgetman missile program alive for the remainder of fiscal 1989.
   Dickinson said in a statement that such a request would give
Midgetman opponents ``a mechanism to kill it in the weeks ahead
unless a longer-term deal to ratify the president's package is
struck.''
   In last year's defense budget bill, Congress provided $250
million for the Midgetman and $600 million for the raid-based MX
program, but directed that no more than $250 million of the MX
money could be spent before Feb. 15.
   The remaining $350 million was supposed to have been reallocated
after the new president decided whether to pursue one program, the
other, or both.
   Cheney initially recommended that the Midgetman be scrapped. But
Bush, bowing to pressure from congressional Democrats who support
the small, single-warhead missile, opted to proceed with both
programs, but to deploy the 50 MX missiles in rail cars first.
   In his new Pentagon budget request for fiscal 1990, Bush calls
for $1.2 million for deployment of the MX and $100 million to
continue research and development of the Midgetman.
   Dickinson, who backed Cheney's recommendation for cancellation
of the Midgetman, said he supports Bush's compromise package but
does not want to see the missile debate drag on for months while
Democrats maneuver to increase funding for the Midgetman.
   ``My tolerance for any attempt to plus-up the Midgetman and thus
undermine the president's politically and fiscally acceptable
compromise is zero,'' Dickinson said. ``If these attempts continue,
I will work as hard as I can to kill the program outright.''
   Some Democrats who have supported the Midgetman indicated after
Bush announced his compromise decision last month that they might
join Republican opponents in efforts to kill the missile rather
than support funding two programs in a period of intense fiscal
constaints.
   Cheney has told Congress it will cost about $350 million to keep
the Midgetman program alive for the remainder of fiscal 1989, $100
million more than was authorized last year. Dickinson said any
reallocation of MX money to make up the difference must be approved
by Congress.
</TEXT>
