<FILEID>AP-NR-05-18-89 2014EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Ruder     05-18 0764</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ruder,760</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ruder Quits as Securities and Exchange Commissioner</HEAD>
<BYLINE>DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   David S. Ruder announced his resignation
Thursday as chairman of the Securities and Exchange Commission
after guiding the agency through two tumultuous years that included
the 1987 stock market crash and a historic investigation of
corruption on Wall Street.
   Ruder, in a letter to President Bush, said he planned to return
to the faculty of Northwestern University School of Law at the end
of August. He left there in August 1987 to head the SEC, which
regulates the nation's financial markets and oversees disclosure
requirements for U.S. publicly traded corporations.
   The date of his resignation depends on when his successor is
appointed. He gave no reason for leaving, but Bush had been widely
expected to name someone else to the post even though senior
Democrats in Congress were urging that Ruder stay on. His term
expires in June 1991.
   On the list of possible successors are attorney Thomas A. Russo,
a former division director at the Commodity Futures Trading
Commission, Edward H. Fleischman, who already holds a seat on the
five-member SEC, and Kraft Inc. Chairman John M. Richman of Chicago.
   White House spokesman B.J. Cooper said the administration was
reviewing the appointment and declined further comment.
   In his letter to Bush, dated Thursday, Ruder said it was crucial
that the commission have ``vigorous and strong leadership.''
   When Ruder, 60, took over the SEC, he had a reputation as a
respected legal expert and, as former dean of the Northwestern Law
School, as a skilled administrator.
   That skill was tested a little more than two months later on
Oct. 19, 1987, when the stock market crashed, registering a record
508-point decline on the Dow Jones average of industrial stocks.
   Ruder, who had little experience operating in the national media
spotlight, was sharply criticized by congressional committee
chairmen for talking with reporters on the day of the crash about
possibility of a trading halt. Some analysts said his remarks
squashed a recovery attempt by the market and deepened the plunge
while Ruder maintained he was misquoted.
   However, in the debate over market reform that followed, Ruder
soon won friends among Democrats on Capitol Hill for hewing a
somewhat independent line from the free-market Reagan
administration.
   The White House and Treasury Departments resisted any attempt to
combine the regulation of stock and futures markets, which are
regulated with a lighter hand by the CFTC. Ruder, alone among top
administration officials, argued that stock and futures markets are
closely linked and that his agency should coordinate regulation of
both.
   Also, in the wake of an outcry from small investors who lost
money in the crash, he pushed the securities industry to improve
its system of arbitrating disputes with customers and to take other
steps to restore public confidence.
   In the end, the Reagan administration view prevailed on market
reform proposals, but Rep. John Dingell, D-Mich., chairman of the
House Energy and Commerce Committee, praised Ruder for
``understanding the importance of maintaining public confidence.''
   ``He was a fine chairman and I hope someone of his integrity,
ability and orientation will succeed him,'' said Dingell, who had
urged Bush to reappoint Ruder.
   ``I thought he brought an unusually scholarly and calm
perspective to one of the more turbulent times in the market's
history. He probably will be respected more for what he didn't do,
rather than for what he did do. Namely, he didn't overreact,'' said
Roberick M. Hills, chairman of the SEC under the administation of
President Ford.
   William Proxmire, former chairman of the Senate Banking
Committee, had opposed Ruder's nomination but now says that was a
mistake.
   ``Frankly, I think he worked out well,'' Proxmire said. ``Ruder
believes strongly in regulation. He believes that securities
issuers should be vigorously required to provide information to
investors and if they don't they should be penalized, fined or
jailed.'' less regulation rather than more.''
   Ruder, had he stayed, faced presiding over a commission that
likely would have been increasingly out of sync with his views.
Ronald Reagan, a month before leaving the presidency, replaced
Aulana Peters, a Ruder ally, with Mary Schapiro, a former futures
industry lobbyist. The term of Charles C. Cox, another frequent
Ruder ally, has expired and his nomination by Reagan was never
acted on.
   Ruder also broke from the administration in seeking large
increases in his agency's budget, which had remained static while
stock and bond trading mushroomed.
   Gary G. Lynch, the 38-year-old attorney who heads the SEC's
enforcement division, announced his own resignation, effective
mid-July, last week.
</TEXT>
