<FIRST>r p AM-Kassebaum     05-18 0248</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Kassebaum,220</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kassebaum Seeking Third Term Despite Two-Term Pledge</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Nancy Landon Kassebaum, R-Kan., who
promised in her first and second campaigns that she would serve
only two terms, announced Thursday she changed her mind and would
seek a third term in 1990.
   Her decision dashed hopes of Democrats that she would retire and
thus give them a much-improved chance of ending a 50-year drought
in which no Democrat has represented Kansas in the Senate.
   When she first ran in 1978, she pledged to serve only 12 years _
two six-year terms _ if she won a Senate seat. She was elected that
year. When seeking re-election in 1984, she repeated that vow and
retained the seat.
   She said she changed her mind and decided she could best serve
Kansas by using her seniority, but added that it troubled her to
break the pledge. ``It did bother me because I believe a number of
Kansans valued the fact that when I say something that's what I
mean,'' Kassebaum said.
   However, she argued that it would hurt Kansas if she limited her
tenure when others in Congress are not subject to similiar
restrictions. There is no limit on the number of terms a person can
serve in the Senate or the House.
   ``If you're the only one ... you simply give up some of the
credentials and the seniority that you have built here that you
hope can be useful to your state,'' Kassebaum said.
</TEXT>
