<DOCNO> AP890518-0160 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-18-89 1729EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Kampelman-Soviets     05-18 0593</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Kampelman-Soviets,6000</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Askes Arms Clarification from Soviets</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-US-Germany Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<UNK>Associated Press Writer</UNK>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard Shevardnadze's
vow to keep medium-range nuclear weapons in Europe if the U.S.
modernizes its short-range arms is an ``appalling'' threat
unsupported by the negotiating record, a former chief U.S. arms
control negotiator said Thursday.
   ``I believe that Shevardnadze's statement was pretty
appalling,'' Max Kampelman, chief strategic arms control negotiator
in the Reagan administration, told the Senate Foreign Relations
Committee.
   ``I cannot believe they want to leave the message that they want
to open up questions about their willingness to live up to their
arms control commitments,'' Kampelman said.
   Shevardnadze, speaking in Bonn, West Germany last Saturday, said
that if the United States did not drop plans to more than triple
the range of its aging Lance Missiles in Western Europe, the Soviet
Union would respond, either by developing a new short-range weapon
or by retaining SS-23 missiles which have a range of 310 miles.
   The 1987 Intermediate Nuclear Forces or INF treaty bans all
missiles with a range of between 300 and 3,500 miles, including the
SS-23.
   Kampelman noted that some have speculated that there might have
been an implicit understanding at one level or another of the U.S.
and Soviet negotiating teams that if the Soviets agreed to
dismantle the SS-23 the United States would not give modernized
short-range missiles a range close to 300 miles.
   Kampelman said that when he heard of Shevardnadze's statement,
``I was certain that if there had been that kind of understanding,
I would have known.''
   He said he checked with other negotiators who were part of the
hard bargaining that produced the INF treaty.
   Kampelman said they ``agreed with me that there was absolutely
no reason for the Soviets to believe there was anything that could
be so interpreted.''
   He said that possibility did present itself at one time but the
Soviets did not agree to it.
   ``The Soviets were told, `OK, but then we don;'t want you to
complain if our modernization comes close'' to 300 miles.
   Kampelman said the ststement was ``not typical of the
Shevardnadze I have been dealing with for quite some time.''
   ``I have never before seen a threat and I was surprised,''
Kampelman said.
   ``I have to believe this was part of the `old thinking' of the
Soviet Union toward Western Europe, which is to frighten them.''
   Paul Nitze, who was President Reagan's chief arms control
adviser, said he cannot imagine that Shevardnadze would have made
his vow ``without some explanation.''
   ``There must be something, some place, that I haven't been able
to find,'' Nitze said.
   But Kampelman there mere be an outside chance Soviet negotiators
were told informally that ``something is possible.''
   ``That he has evidence (that a commitment was actually made) I
would just doubt very much,'' Kampelman said.
   All 19 members of the Foreign Relations Committee signed on
Wednesday a letter to President Bush, asking him to seek a
clarification from the Soviet president about his foreign
minister's statement.
   Sen. Nancy L. Kassebaum, R-Kan., who helped organize the letter
writing effort, called the foreign minister's statement ``very
irresponsible'' because it could cause a lot of damage (to the
future of arms control) and throw a lot of and in everybody's
eyes.''
   Sen. Joseph R. Biden, R-Del., siad he believed Shevardnadze's
declaration was ``done out of whole cloth.''
   ``It flies in the face of what they have been doing and had that
kind of impact after all their cooing and wooing,'' he said.
</TEXT>
