<FIRST>u w AM-US-Germany 1stLd-Writethru a0710 05-18 0634</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Germany, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0710,590</SECOND>
<HEAD>West German Defense Minister Confers on NATO Missile Dispute</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts 1 graf new material after 6th graf pvs, The West</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III held a
hurried-up meeting Thursday with West German Defense Minister
Gerhard Stoltenberg, who carried new proposals designed to avoid an
allied clash over short-range nuclear weapons at the upcoming NATO
summit.
   A diplomatic source familiar with Stoltenberg's proposals
confirmed that the West Germans are prepared to be more flexible on
the question of U.S.-Soviet negotiations over the weapons.
   The United States has opposed such talks, proposed last week by
Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev, fearing that they could open
the way to stripping Western Europe of its short-range nuclear
weapons and leaving it vulnerable to the superior conventional
forces of the Warsaw Pact.
   West Germany wants such talks to begin and has proposed that
NATO delay modernizing its arsenal of short-range Lance missiles,
most of which are based in West Germany.
   The Bonn government's opposition to the weapons stems from the
fact they are designed for battlefield use, meaning that in time of
war they would most probably strike East and West Germany.
   The West Germans are now expressing the hope that an agreement
with the United States might be worked out within the next few
days, even though sharp differences remain eight days before
President Bush leaves for a critical NATO meeting in Paris.
   At the end of Thursday's talks, West German sources said
Stoltenberg had described his meeting with Baker as ``very useful''
and had said he was hopeful an agreement with the United States
could be reached by early next week. The source spoke on the
condition of anonymity.
   Although Baker and Stoltenberg had been scheduled to meet only
on Friday, an early Thursday session was arranged so that
Stoltenberg could confer with Baker at the beginning of the defense
minister's two-day visit, which is aimed at settling the bitter
dispute between Bonn and Washington.
   Stoltenberg also met for three hours with his counterpart,
Defense Secretary Dick Cheney.
   State Department spokesman Richard Boucher declined to comment
on the substance of Stoltenberg's talks with Baker, except to say
that the two touched on the short-range missile issue and on other
topics. Boucher said they planned to continue their talks with ``a
longer discussion'' on Friday.
   Stoltenberg's mission was to suggest a possible link between a
reduction of Soviet bloc conventional forces in Europe and the
start of negotiations between East and West on cutting back the
number of short-range nuclear weapons in Europe.
   Such negotiations might not begin until there is significant
progress in reducing European arsenals of conventional arms, where
the Warsaw Pact has a huge advantage.
   One proposal would be to form a high-level NATO study group to
examine how much ``significant progress'' would be necessary before
any U.S.-Soviet talks could convene, the diplomatic source said.
   Allowing such a study would give the NATO summit partners more
of a chance to resolve their differences.
   Baker has insisted the United States will stick to its position
that talks should first produce a reduction in Soviet bloc forces
in Europe to match NATO levels. Only then would the United States
be willing to consider discussing short-range missiles.
   Stoltenberg's visit came amid predictions from a group of West
German parliament members visiting Washington that an agreement
between Bonn and Washington will be ironed out prior to the NATO
summit.
   ``There's a new flexibility on both sides. The chances we will
reach an agreement are not 100 percent, but given the political
will, there's a good chance we will reach an agreement'' before the
NATO summit, said Volcker Ruehe, the deputy majority leader in
parliament, in a meeting with reporters.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
