<FIRST>r i AM-GermanRefineryFire     05-18 0158</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-German Refinery Fire,0160</SECOND>
<HEAD>Explosion at Hamburg Refinery Kills 1, Injures 2</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto FRA10</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HAMBURG, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An explosion and fire at the German
Shell oil refinery in the port of Hamburg sent flames shooting 100
yards into the air Thursday and killed at least one worker,
authorities reported.
   Two others were injured by the explosion in a network of pipes
leading from the central pumping and mixing station, Shell manager
Siegmar Vetter said. He said the cause was being investigated.
   Firefighters said more than 100 tons of fuel spilled after the
explosion and fed the fire, which was brought under control after
four hours.
   The pumping station is in a tank farm, and intense heat created
the danger of further explosions, firefighters said.
   More than 200 firefighters went to the scene at the Elbe River
port. Thick black smoke from the fire swept over the city, but
authorities said no toxic substances were released.
