<FIRST>r i AM-Mexico-UnionBattle     05-18 0291</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mexico-Union Battle,0299</SECOND>
<HEAD>78 Injured in Mexican Oil Worker's Union Dispute</HEAD>
<DATELINE>POZA RICA, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police and soldiers broke up a battle
by two groups for control of a local section of the Petroleum
Workers Union in this oil producing center, and 78 people were
injured, officials said Thursday.
   One worker was in critical condition with a fractured skull, and
five more were hospitalized with broken bones, said Jose Luis
Bermudez, a spokesman for the state petroleum monopoly Pemex.
   Bermudez said Wednesday's brawl occurred at the union's Section
30, and he called it strictly a union dispute. He said the incident
did not affect Pemex operations in the large oilfield in Veracruz
state, on the Gulf of Mexico.
   Carlos Carvajal Lopez, state judicial police regional commander,
told the government newspaper El Nacional he had to call on a
nearby army post to help local police restore order.
   The dispute began March 7 when a dissident group led by Roberto
Reyes Betancourt claimed they won elections for control of Section
30, seized the building and barricaded themselves inside.
   Carvajal and Bermudez said that Wednesday morning an estimated
200 workers loyal to Ruben Amador Castro, who is backed by the
union's national executive council, tried to storm the building.
   The attackers were armed with rocks, picks and shovels and a
pitched battle followed, the officials said.
   No arrests were reported.
   Disputes in sections and locals have been frequent in the giant
union since Joaquin Hernandez Galicia, nicknamed La Quina, and a
group of 49 old-time leaders were arrested by federal agents in
January on charges of corruption and illegal possession of weapons.
   Five of the leaders were released for lack of evidence, and the
others are awaiting trial in Mexico City.
</TEXT>
