<FIRST>r i AM-China-Slogans     05-18 0430</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Slogans,0450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Protesters Create Slogans, Chants Against Deng</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRIL JONES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The biggest cheers for slogans being chanted at
massive pro-democracy demonstrations in Beijing go to those calling
for senior leader Deng Xiaoping to step down.
   But all the sloganeers are striving for clever verses and catchy
rhythms to make their point.
   Protesters parade endlessly by the Great Hall of the People,
hard by the huge Tiananmen Square rallying site.
   One group stops to chant, ``Where has all the money gone? Gone
to feed them,'' gesturing toward the cavernous hall where Deng and
other leaders conduct much of their business.
   Widely popular when he began implementing rural economic reforms
a decade ago, the 84-year-old Deng _ 85 to the Chinese, who count
children as one year old when born _ is now the target of
disaffected students, workers and intellectuals.
   They hold him responsible for rampant government corruption and
stymied political reform.
   ``Xiaoping, get down from the stage,'' runs the most common
anti-Deng slogan seen during the protests so far.
   ``Xiaoping, your time has come,'' read a banner held aloft at
Tiananmen Square by workers from the No. 2 Beijing Shoe Factory.
   One chant pokes fun at Deng's well-known fondness for bridge.
   ``Xiaoping, Xiaoping, at 85 you're old.
   ``You're OK at cards, but your mind's no good.''
   Another takes a line from a song about Mao Tse-tung and adds one
about Deng:
   ``Chairman Mao is like the sun, wherever he shines it is bright.
   ``Deng Xiaoping is like the moon, whose phases come and go.''
   Bystanders cheered a truck bearing a cardboard sign that read,
``First go after the son,'' referring to Deng's son Pufang. A major
trading firm associated with the younger Deng's association for the
handicapped was reorganized because of corruption.
   ``The children of the people are starving,'' others sang out.
``What's Xiaoping's son doing?''
   Two Qinghua University students carried a banner demonstrating
the winds of change. In 1984, the banner said, ``Xiaoping, how are
you?'' But now a character had been added so it read: ``Xiaoping,
you are so cruel'' _ for not visiting students fasting on the
square since Saturday.
   Several signs recalled the memory of Chou En-lai, a beloved
statesman who died in 1972.
   ``Chou was a great premier for all the people,'' said Wang
Guangju of the Chinese Association of Industrial Associations as he
waved a portrait of Chou.
   ``We used to love Deng Xiaoping, but now there is corruption and
official extravagance in every part of the country, and we have no
democracy.''
</TEXT>
