<SECOND>AM-Helms-Kissinger,170</SECOND>
<HEAD>Helms' Legislation Targets Kissinger</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., took a legislative
shot on Thursday at former Secretary of State Henry A. Kissinger,
now the head of a firm that provides counseling to foreign
governments and U.S. and overseas corporations.
   He persuaded the Senate Foreign Relations Committee to adopt
legislation requiring all members of the president's Foreign
Intelligence Advisory Board to disclose all income from foreign
governments or companies.
   Kissinger is a member of the advisory board.
   Helms, who opposed many of Kissinger's policies during his State
Department tenure, acknowleged that Kissinger was in fact the
principle target of the amendment, which was attached to the
pending State Department authorization bill.
   ``He's not king; he doesn't have to serve on this board,'' Helms
said of Kissinger. ``The government functioned before him and the
government will function after him.''
   ``Henry Kissinger has been up to his armpits in deals with
foreign countries,'' the North Carolina senator said.
   Much work remains on the bill to which the Helms amendement was
attached and it was unclear whether the provision would in fact
become law.
