<FILEID>AP-NR-05-18-89 2120EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-UN-USHumanRights     05-18 0458</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UN-US Human Rights,0472</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Envoy Condemns Practices in South Africa, Occupied Territories,
Panama</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States on Thursday condemned
apartheid in South Africa as ``innately inhuman,'' deplored
violence by both sides in Israel's occupied territories and cited
human rights abuses in Afghanistan, Panama and Romania.
   In the annual U.S. speech on human rights to a key U.N.
committee, Ambassador Thomas R. Pickering also alleged human rights
violations in Burma, Cuba and Iran.
   Pickering made no mention of the Soviet Union and China, where
the United States previously has expressed deep concern over human
rights practices including China's harsh handling of unrest in
Tibet.
   The former ambassador to Israel called for restraint ``by all
parties'' in the Israeli-occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   ``We regret and deplore the violence in the occuied territories
from all sides,'' he told the Second Committee of the U.N. Economic
and Social Council. Pickering said the United States opposes some
Israeli practices, including the use of excessive force to maintain
order, administrative detentions, deportations and the destruction
and sealing of homes of suspects without due process.
   The U.S. envoy began his speech with a denunciation of
Pretoria's segregationist policies, known as apartheid. He said the
South African government ``sponsors and enforces arrangements for
systematic discrimination, asserting that the color of one's skin
makes some human beings superior to others. This premise is
innately inhuman.''
   Pickering said the United States wants to see a new
constitutional order based on equality, a democratic electoral
system based on universal franchise and effective constitutional
guarantees of basic human rights.
   In Afghanistan, he said, there remains overwhelming evidence of
massive violations of human rights carried out by the Kabul
government. These include political killings, disappearances,
torture, summary executions, arbitrary arrests and imprisonment
under unacceptable conditions, he said.
   Pickering also noted that in Panama,``recent, highly regrettable
events'' illustrated ``the overwhelming importance of national
institutions which ensure universal and equal suffrage.''
   He cited need for independent supervision of elections, fair
voter registration, reliable balloting prcedures and means to
prevent electoral fraud and resolve disputes.
   Panama's de facto ruler Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega declared
last week's elections in Panama null and void after his supporters
beat opposition candidates. Observers reported widespread evidence
of fraud on the part of Noriega'ssupporters.
   Despite a cease-fire in the Persian Gulf war, Pickering said,
the human rights situation in Iran has not improved. He cited
hundreds of political executions that began late last year.
   Pickering criticized Romania for declaring in Vienna in January
that it would not be bound by certain provisions of the Conference
on Security and Cooperation in Europe.
   Bucharest has rejected human rights inquiries from the United
States and other Western nations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
