<FIRST>r w AM-FCCSpending     05-18 0542</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-FCC Spending,590</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Panel Promises $400,000 to FCC to preven Furloughs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Senate appropriations subcommittee freed up
enough new money Thursday to prevent the Federal Communications
Commission from having to close its doors for two days this year.
   But the panel made no promises to fund a 10 percent increase for
the commission in 1990.
   The appropriations subcommittee on the departments of Commerce,
Justice and State, the Judiciary and related agencies said the FCC
could have about $400,000 the government received from Florida as
compensation for moving an FCC monitoring station in Fort
Lauderdale to make way for a new highway.
   FCC Chairman Dennis Patrick, in a second day of congressional
testimony on the agency's 1990 appropriation request, told the
panel the commission needs $495,000 or it will have to furlough all
its employees for two days.
   Congress gave the FCC $99.6 million in this fiscal year that
ends Sept. 30, the same amount the commission received in 1988. The
agency went over budget this year, Patrick said, because of
federally mandated increases in salaries and benefits.
   Patrick had told a House appropriations subcommittee on March 7
that the shortfall would be $890,000, or 3{ furlough days. But
Thursday he said more employees than expected had taken advantage
of early retirement programs, leave without pay or shortened their
work schedules.
   FCC spokeswoman Maureen Peratino said the agency could avoid the
furloughs if it received $400,000.
   ``Through attrition and other cutbacks, it looks like we're
going to come out fine by the end of the year,'' she said following
the hearing.
   Patrick estimated the agency would have 1,620 full-time
permanent employees by Oct. 1, the beginning of fiscal 1990. That
would be 20 percent below staffing levels in the early 1980s, he
said.
   Therefore, Patrick said, the agency's backlog in processing
license applications has grown.
   He said the FCC needs the full $109.8 million requested by the
White House, a 10 percent increase, to pay for 1,889 full-time
employees, new computer and monitoring equipment, increased
salaries and benefits and travel expenses to keep up with explosive
growth in the telecommunications industry.
   ``We simply have not had the funds necessary to maintain our
speed of service in processing applications,'' Patrick said.
   A subcommittee aide, Warren Kane, said the panel was sympathetic
to Patrick's budget request.
   ``We don't find a whole lot to dispute them on that,'' Kane said
in an interview following the hearing. ``The problem is, how far
can we go on the current budget resolution?''
   The House on Wednesday passed a $1.17 trillion federal budget
resolution that reflects a $28 billion deficit-reduction deal the
Bush administration and congressional leaders reached last month.
The Senate worked on the measure Thursday.
   Subcommittee Chairman Ernest F. Hollings, D-S.C., told Patrick
that job attrition could be expected at the FCC since the agency
has eased or abandoned some regulatory oversight.
   Peratino of the FCC said that even though subcommittee members
made no promises regarding 1990 funds, ``I think we'll do better
than we did this year.''
   Patrick also made a pitch for a proposal to auction off new
licenses to the highest bidder, a system he said would reap $3.38
billion for the U.S. Treasury.
</TEXT>
