<FIRST>r i AM-AntarcticTrek     05-18 0297</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Antarctic Trek,0305</SECOND>
<HEAD>Polar Ship Completes Repairs, Again Leaves Port For Antarctic Expedition</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LE HAVRE, France (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A ship that is to carry a team of
explorers to Antarctica set sail for New York on Thursday on the
first part of its voyage, organizers said.
   The ceremonial departure of the high-tech polar ship UAP took
place on Sunday, but after some tests at sea the crew returned
quietly to port when some minor parts and repairs were needed,
skipper Jean Collet said.
   The silver ship left this Normandy port about 8 p.m. under clear
skies, the organizers said.
   After the New York stop, the UAP will head for King George
Island, from where the adventurers will launch the first
unmechanized trek across the vast frozen continent.
   The operation is being organized by Will Steger of Ely, Minn.,
who in 1986 led the first unsupported dogsled trek to the North
Pole since Adm. Robert Peary, and Frenchman Jean-Louis Etienne, the
first man to ski alone to the North Pole.
   The team is to leave King George Island on Aug. 1 and spend
seven months crossing about 4,000 miles of ice and snow with their
dogs, arriving at the Soviet Mirnyy base in March.
   Organizers are hoping to draw attention to threats against the
Antarctic environment and the need for increased international
cooperation to protect it.
   The polar ship, built for $3.17 million, is 117 feet long and 32
feet wide. It was christened in a ceremony Saturday.
   Other members of the team include Victor Boyarsky of the Soviet
Arctic and Antarctic Research Institute, glaciologist Qin Dahe of
China, Geoff Somers of Britain and Keizo Funatsu of Japan.
   Most of the explorers will join the ship later in the
expedition, rather than participating in the Atlantic crossing.
</TEXT>
