<DOCNO> AP890518-0178 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-18-89 2124EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Crack     05-18 0520</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Crack,0540</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crack Specter Hangs Over Europe, Says Cabinet Minister</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Europe faces a crack epidemic that could be as bad
as any plague of the Middle Ages, Home Secretary Douglas Hurd told
a 19-nation conference on narcotics Thursday.
   ``This is a plague we are visiting on ourselves,'' said the
minister, whose department is responsible for police, prisons and
immigration.
   ``Crack is the specter I see hanging over Europe. If crack ever
becomes deeply rooted in Europe the outlook will indeed be bleak.''
   Hurd addressed the opening session of a two-day meeting of
Western European governments in the Council of Europe.
   Ministers met to discuss increased cooperation in fighting
narcotics and were told by Hurd they must ``work together
urgently'' to make sure the experience of drug abuse in the United
States is not repeated in Europe.
   Crack is a cheap, smokable form of cocaine that gives an
instant, intense high as the drug goes straight to the brain.
   But the effect wears off after a few minutes, and a lingering,
deep depression follows.
   Hurd noted that crack was unheard of in the United States before
1985 but is now a major drug there.
   He said 75 percent of the people who used crack three times
became addicted to it.
   ``Because the use of crack is accompanied by feelings of
omnipotence and paranoia, the behavior which results has devastated
family life in the United States. Figures of child abuse have
soared and so have attacks on the police,'' the secretary said.
   Hurd pleaded for international cooperation to ensure traffickers
or their profits have no hiding place.
   ``The North American market having been saturated, the cocaine
barons of Latin America are now driving their product into
Europe,'' he said.
   ``The traffickers are in it for the money. If they stand a good
chance of losing the money, wherever it is stashed, the incentive
disappears.''
   Hurd said Britain was giving $810,000 to the United Nations for
anti-narcotics operations and an additional $3.2 million for
equipment and training of law enforcement agencies in countries
along the cocaine supply route from Latin America to Europe.
   Hurd said figures supplied by the Paris-based international
police organization, Interpol, showed that cocaine seized in Europe
increased from 341 pounds in 1978 to nearly 5{ tons last year.
   He said two laboratories were dismantled in Italy and about 590
pounds of coca base and cocaine hydrochloride seized there.
   ``This event indicates without doubt that large-scale conversion
of coca base into cocaine is under way in Europe. There is
evidence, too, of cooperation between criminal organizations in
Colombia and Italy,'' Hurd said.
   He invited other countries to follow Britain's example in
signing bilateral agreements to confiscate money from trafficking.
There are such agreements with the United States, Canada, Bahamas,
Australia and Switzerland, and negotiations or approaching signings
with Spain, Sweden, Italy, France and the Netherlands.
   Barry Sheerman, the home affairs spokesman of Britain's
opposition Labor Party, criticized Hurd for ignoring police pleas
to provide cash to reward drug-ring informers.
   ``The only way to beat these gangs is to get high levels of
inside information,'' Sheerman said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
