<DOCNO> AP890518-0179 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-18-89 2128EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Lebanon-Kidnap     05-18 0382</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon-Kidnap,0395</SECOND>
<HEAD>PLO Expels West German Relief Workers From Refugee Camp</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By AHMED MANTASH</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SIDON, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The PLO expelled four West German relief
workers from their base in a refugee camp Thursday because it said
they concealed the identity of those who kidnapped members of their
group this month.
   The Palestine Liberation Organization also said the workers from
the ASME-Humanitas group at the Mieh Mieh camp had ignored security
regulations. It did not elaborate.
   ``We gave them 60 minutes to pack and leave,'' said Abu Ali
Wajih, in charge of security for all the Palestinian refugee camps
in Lebanon. ``We don't want to have anything to do with them
anymore.''
   The four West Germans were taken in a PLO car to Sidon, where
they were met by members of the Nasserite Militia and taken to
another base the group keeps in Aaqbiyeh, controlled by the Shiite
Amal militia. It was not immediately known how long they would stay
in Lebanon.
   The West German captives, Heinrich Struebig, 48, an
administrator, and Thomas Kemptner, 28, a male nurse, were
kidnapped along with nurse Petra Schnitzler on Tuesday.
   Ms. Schnitzler was freed a few hours later when a local militia
stopped the kidnappers' car, thinking it was a gang of thieves.
   Both Struebig and Ms. Schnitzler had been kidnapped along with
Markus Quint, also a West German, May 4. She and Struebig were
released the next day to transmit demands by the kidnappers seeking
a lenient sentence for convicted terrorist Mohammed Ali Hamadi, a
Lebanese Shiite Moslem.
   On Wednesday, a Frankfurt court sentenced Hamadi to life in
prison for air piracy and murder in connection with the 1985 TWA
hijacking during which a U.S. Navy diver was killed.
   ASME-Humanitas has seven workers serving mainly the Palestinian
camps.
   Quint was freed on Sunday. Nabih Berri, whose Shiite Moslem
militia controls most of southern Lebanon beyond Sidon, took credit
for the release and pledged to provide greater protection.
   Ms. Schnitzler said Thursday that ASME-Humanitas headquarters
had not asked the relief workers to leave.
   But West German Foreign Ministry spokesman Juergen Chrobog said
the West German government had asked the group 15 times in writing
to pull out.
   Besides the two West Germans, at least 16 foreigners are missing
and believed held hostage in Lebanon.
</TEXT>
