<FIRST>u i AM-Israel-Rabin 1stLd-Writethru a0627 05-18 0891</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Rabin, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0627,0914</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rabin: No Room For Gestures Towards Palestinians</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 4 grafs after 10th pvs, `The PLO...,' to UPDATE with
Shamir, Arens comment. Pick up 11th pvs, `Rabin met...' DELETES 16th graf
to remove redundancy.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICOLAS B. TATRO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEL AVIV, Israel (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin on
Thursday ruled out goodwill gestures to improve conditions in the
occupied territories and encourage Palestinians to accept Israel's
peace plan.
   Speaking on the eve of a 10-day visit to the United States,
Rabin said Israel was not now ready to release prisoners, reopen
universities and public schools or take other measures to improve
the climate amid the 17-month uprising by Palestinians in the
occupied lands.
   ``The present situation leaves no room for gestures,'' Rabin
said in an interview with The Associated Press.
   Rabin pecifically ruled out releasing large numbers of the 6,300
Palestinian security prisoners or reopening 11 Palestinian
universities and colleges in the West Bank with a total enrollment
of 17,000. They have been closed since February 1988.
   He said two attempts were made to restart classes at 1,194 grade
schools and high schools in the West Bank. But he said violent
clashes immediately began between students and soldiers.
   ``Once the schools were closed there was a sharp reduction in
the number of youngsters who were injured or worse,'' he said.
   Rabin suggested Israel might be willing to show flexibility on
the participation of 140,000 East Jerusalem Arabs, international
supervision and other unresolved questions about elections if
Palestinians first indicated agreement in principle to Israel's
proposal.
   ``If there will be acceptance in principle of (the plan) by
Palestinians in the territories we can go on and tackle other
problems which are related to the matter of elections,'' he said.
   Israel's plan calls for elections to chose Palestinian
representatives to negotiate a self-rule scheme for the 1.5 million
residents of the West Bank and Gaza Strip. Negotiations on a
permanent solution would start only after three years.
   The PLO Executive Committee rejected the Israeli plan, adopted
by the Cabinet on Sunday, as a ``farce.'' Most prominent
Palestinians in the occupied territories were also critical, saying
the plan failed to deal with Palestinian aspirations for an
independent state.
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir, in an interview on Israel
television, made clear he sees the plan as a way to prevent the
establishment of a Palestinian state.
   Asked if he believed the plan would lead to such a state, Shamir
replied: ``If I thought so I would not have proposed the plan. I
feel that the plan is our best weapon for fighting this.''
   Shamir told his right-wing Likud bloc Wednesday that Israel
would ``not give an inch'' of land to the Arabs as part of a
permament solution.
   Foreign Minister Moshe Arens said Thursday after meeting
Secretary of State James Baker in Washington that the Bush
administration supported the Israeli election plan. But U.S.
officials said many questions remained, such as who would be
allowed to participate.
   Rabin met with two groups of Palestinians from the occupied
lands this week to explain the government's peace proposals. He
conceded their views reflected the negative comments made publicly
by other Palestinians. But he said there was more of a sense of
urgency about finding a solution among local Palestinians.
   ``They would like to see the light at the end of the tunnel
while the (PLO) people who reside in the villas of Tunisia can wait
10 to 15 years. The urgency here is greater than outside. At the
same time no doubt they would not dare to go it alone,'' he said.
   He said Israel would be willing to wait three to six months for
a definitive Palestinian answer before giving up on the initiative.
In the meantime, he said Israel counted on the United States to
help persuade international and Arab opinion of the plan's worth.
   Palestinians would not be barred from running in the elections
because they wanted an independent Palestinian state or supported
the PLO, Rabin said, adding the only criteria would be the advocacy
of violence.
   ``Anyone who calls for violence against Israel cannot be a
candidate for elections,'' he said.
   But Rabin said Israel's two major parties, Likud and Labor, were
irrevocably split on whether Israel should trade land for peace.
   ``There is no government position on what should be on the
boundaries or the form of the permanent peace,'' he said.
   He argued that because of the division the only course open was
a two-step process that postponed talks on a permanent solution.
   ``We hope the new realities we offer for a transition period (of
self-rule) will create a new atmosphere and more confidence that
can bring one of the two (Israeli) sides to change its position,''
said Rabin.
   In talks on a permament settlement, Palestinian and Jordanian
negotiators could propose any solution they desire, including
demands for Palestinian statehood.
   Rabin called on Palestinians to adopt a realistic position,
saying past peace efforts failed because of maximalist demands.
   ``In the past, and unfortunately in certain circles even today,
(the Arabs) try a policy of everything or nothing. And they have
remained in the past 40 years with nothing.
   ``They should start to become reasonable and learn that complex
issues cannot be solved by miracles and `open sesame' solutions,''
he said.
</TEXT>
