<HEAD>Jury Refuses to Indict Father for Disconnecting Life-Support</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to give father's occupation, INSERTS 4 grafs after
6th graf, `Linares pleaded ...' to UPDATE with comment from judge and prosecutor,
explain meaning of conditional discharge; picks up 7th graf, `Linares'
son ...;'' SUBS 10th graf, ```I did ...' to CORRECT quote to `loved' sted
`love' and to whom quote was made; INSERTS two grafs after to give background;
picks up 11th graf `The grand ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENDA C. COLEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Cook County grand jury refused to indict a man
who disconnected his brain-damaged, comatose son from life support
and held hospital workers at gunpoint until the boy died,
authorities said Thursday.
   Rudy Linares, 23, a house painter from Cicero, was charged by
the state's attorney's office with murder in the April 26 death of
his 15-month-old son, Samuel.
   But after the grand jury action, the state's attorney's office
announced Thursday it would not prosecute the charge.
   ``I'm glad it's more or less behind me now,'' Linares said. ``I
want to thank everybody that sent me cards, letters, their prayers,
moral support.''
   He said he and his wife ``just want to go home and spend some
time together.''
   Linares pleaded guilty to a misdemeanor charge of unlawful use
of a weapon and was sentenced by Circuit Judge Robert Bastone to
one year conditional discharge, meaning he will serve no time in
jail, said Dan McCullough, spokesman for State's Attorney Cecil
Partee.
   ``As far as punishment is concerned,'' Bastone said Thursday,
``I think you have suffered enough.''
   ``The case of Rudy Linares has been a unique, frustrating and
troubling one,'' Partee said. ``His actions in removing his son
from a respirator, while armed with a loaded revolver, were
simultaneously inappropriate under the law, yet understandable from
the standpoint of a parent.''
   A conditional discharge means Linares can go free provided he is
given a psychological evaluation and that he get counseling if
authorities recommend it.
   After the hearing, Partee reiterated his plan to form a task
force of medical, legal and religious representatives to analyze
the issues presented by the case and seek appropriate legislation.
   Linares' son had been in an irreversible coma since August, when
he accidentally swallowed a balloon.
   ``Sammy Linares died ... nine months ago, and ...whatever
occurred between then and three weeks ago could not change that,''
said Kevin Smith, trial supervisor for the public defender's office
and one of Linares' three attorneys.
   Authorities said Linares pulled his son from a life-support
system at Rush-Presbyterian-St. Luke's Medical Center and, holding
a .357-caliber gun, cradled the boy in his arms until the baby died.
   ``I did it because I loved my son,'' Linares told reporters
after arrest.
   The hospital last year refused to comply with a request from the
Linares family for a withdrawal of life support from their son.
Hospital lawyer Max Brown said the youngster wasn't brain dead and
such a move could have left doctors open to criminal charges.
   Authorities say Linares also had unhooked his son's life-support
system during a December visit, but that staff members immediately
re-attached the boy's ventilator and did not notify police.
   The grand jury began its investigation three weeks ago.
   Medical Examiner Robert J. Stein testified before the grand jury
Wednesday and said afterward that he still had not determined if
the baby's death was accidental or a homicide.
   Stein has said the baby died from lack of oxygen to the brain
because of the balloon and the termination of life-support.
</TEXT>
