<HEAD>Panel Asks Probe of Imports of Illegal Drug Paraphernalia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate Finance Committee has asked for an
investigation into illegal imports of drug paraphernalia from
nations on the rim of the Pacific, Sen. Daniel P. Moynihan, D-N.Y.,
said Thursday.
   He said the committee sent a letter to Anne Brunsdale,
chairwoman of the U.S. International Trade Commission, asking for
an investigation of the scope of illicit drug paraphernalia imports
and the effectiveness of the Mail Order Drug Control Act in
restricting such products.
   ``The proliferation of crack cocaine has spawned a new epidemic
in illegal paraphernalia imports,'' Moynihan said. ``Crack vials,
plastic bags and pipes are providing illegal profits often greater
than the drugs themselves.''
   He called for acting against the source countries, which include
Taiwan, Singapore, Hong Kong, Thailand, Japan and South Korea.
   Between April 15, 1988, and March 7, 1989, the Customs Service
seized at least $8 million worth of vials, pipes, spoons, straws,
filters, bags and other drug paraphernalia, the committee told
Brunsdale.
