<HEAD>Reputed Leader of Medellin Cartel Sentenced in Absentia</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   POINTE-A-PITRE, Guadeloupe (AP) _ Pablo Escobar Gaviria, said to
lead the notorious Medellin Cartel, was sentenced in absentia to 20
years in prison Thursday for conspiring to smuggle half a ton of
cocaine into this French Caribbean island.
   The Correctional Court of Pointe-a-Pitre also sentenced four
Colombians captured with the drug shipment in 1987 to prison terms
of 10 and 14 years.
   On Wednesday, the four identified Escobar during the trial as
the organizer of the shipment, which French police said was
destined for Europe.
   ``This is very significant because it's the first international
sentencing of Pablo Escobar by a court,'' said Jacques Floro, a
prosecutor.
   Juan Perez Piedraca, Howard Armando Castro Munoz, Jesus Garcia
Asparilla and David Ortiz Hernida were captured after their small
plane carrying the cocaine landed on Marie Galante, a small island
adjacent to Guadeloupe.
   ``It's the biggest drug bust in France and one of the biggest in
Europe,'' Floro said.
   Gustavo Gaviria and Gustavo Gonzalez of the drug cartel also
were identified as co-conspirators and sentenced in absentia to 20
years.
   Perez and Ortiz were given 14 years each and Garcia and Castro
10 years. Floro said French police valued the cocaine at $75
million and said it was 80 percent pure.
