<FIRST>u w AM-Scotus-Willis     05-18 0227</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Scotus-Willis,220</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Scotus Denies Stay of Willis Execution</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court on Thursday denied a stay of
execution for Henry Willis III, convicted of murdering a small-town
Georgia police chief who was shot to death one day before he was to
quit law enforcement.
   The application for the stay was filed at 6:40 p.m. and the
denial issued at 7:11 p.m., said court spokeswoman Kathy Arberg.
   Justices William J. Brennan and Thurgood Marshall dissented,
Arberg said.
   At 6:30 p.m., 30 minutes before Willis' scheduled 7 p.m.
execution, a three-judge panel of the 11th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals in Atlanta had granted a four-hour stay for Willis to give
his attorneys time to file an appeal with the Supreme Court.
   Before the ruling, Willis' attorney, Millard Farmer, was turned
down in three different courtrooms. Within hours Thursday, a
Georgia Superior Court judge and the state Supreme Court denied a
stay. Later, the state Board of Pardons and Paroles refused
clemency.
   Willis' attorney, Millard Farmer, then filed an appeal with U.S.
District Judge Wilbur Owens in Macon, but Owens denied it, agreeing
with the parole board that Willis ``failed to make a substantial
showing that he has been denied a federal right'' in his trial.
   Willis, 36, was scheduled to die for the 1976 slaying of Police
Chief Ed Giddens of Ray City.
</TEXT>
