<FIRST>u w AM-Boat-Mexico     05-18 0464</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Boat-Mexico,460</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mexican Navy Fires On, Boards U.S. Fishing Vessel</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Mexican naval vessel fired on and boarded a
U.S. fishing boat Thursday morning in the Gulf of Mexico after
accusing it of fishing in Mexican waters, the Coast Guard said.
   None of the boat's three crew members was injured but several
bullets struck the fishing boat H.W. Junior when the Mexican patrol
used gunfire to stop the vessel, said Coast Guard spokesman Capt.
Randy Peterson.
   After Mexican authorities boarded the boat, the Mexican vessel
left the area and the Coast Guard ships escorted the H.W. Junior
into Port Isabel, Texas, according to a Coast Guard statement.
   ``The indication is that Mexican authorities were correct in
their action,'' said Capt. Randy Peterson, a Coast Guard public
affairs officer in Washington. He said international law allows
police action against vessels outside territorial waters if
authorities are in ``hot pursuit.''
   The Coast Guard release said the H.W. Junior was 15 miles
east-northeast of Port Isabel when Mexican authorities shot at and
boarded the vessel.
   Meanwhile, Mexican authorities announced in Mexico City that
they intercepted an American fishing vessel called the Juanita and
arrested its three-member crew, described as two persons of
Nicaraguan origin and one of Cuban origin. Authorities said the
three were turned over to ``competent authorities'' in the port of
Tampico where it said the vessel was taken.
   The Mexican report did not say when that incident occurred, and
it was not immediately clear whether it referred to a separate
incident. A Coast Guard duty officer in New Orleans, Steve Guy,
said he knew of no report involving a vessel called Juanita.
   Coast Guard public affairs officer Lt. Pat Philbin in New
Orleans said a Coast Guard jet and two ships were sent and
witnessed the boarding after the fishing boat called for assistance.
   ``The incident was apparently sparked over Mexican claims that
the shrimper was in Mexican territorial waters,'' said a Coast
Guard statement.
   Philbin said no action was taken against the boat by U.S.
authorities, aside from a warning issued in port because it did not
have a device to exclude turtles from its fishing nets.
   He said the names of the boat's crew members were not
immediately available. The H.W. Junior's home port is Brownsville,
Texas.
   Philbin said U.S. authorities could not verify whether the boat
was fishing in Mexican waters because they did not observe it prior
to the boarding.
   Mexican authorities said the boat was caught fishing about six
miles off the Mexico shore, five miles south of the border between
Mexican and U.S. waters, Philbin said.
   State Department spokeswoman Nancy Beck, asked if the Mexican
government had been contacted about the incident, said she had no
other details.
</TEXT>
