<FILEID>AP-NR-05-18-89 2142EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-AnnenbergCollection     05-18 0414</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Annenberg Collection,0425</SECOND>
<HEAD>Exhibit Boasts One Of Nation's Top Impressionist Collections</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE OWEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former publisher Walter Annenberg's
collection of impressionist art, including what one expert called a
``smack-in-the-kisser Renoir'' and ``the'' Monet, goes on display
publicly this weekend for the first time.
   The former ambassador's collection of 50 noted impressionist and
post-impressionist paintings includes works by Paul Cezanne, Claude
Monet, Vincent Van Gogh and Paul Gauguin. They will be shown in the
special exhibit beginning Sunday at the Philadelphia Museum of Art.
   ``You're dealing with three generations of very revolutionary
painters who were leaning on each other very hard and then reacted
very hard,'' said Joe Rishel, the museum's curator of pre-1900
European paintings.
   Annenberg and his wife, Leonore, accumulated the collection over
three decades. It is accompanied by two Cezanne sketchbooks
Annenberg gave to the museum in 1987, and offers a concentration of
leading impressionist and post-impressionist works ``that's hard to
come by anywhere in the world publicly,'' Rishel said.
   ``What the Annenbergs have achieved, truly remarkably, is it's
not just the good Monet; it is `the' Monet. It's not just the
(good) Renoir; it is the right there, smack-in-the-kisser Renoir,''
Rishel said.
   ``They've had the discipline to wait for the very best to come,
then to act.''
   Standing before Gauguin's 1890s ``The Siesta,'' a colorful oil
painting of four women in the shade on a porch with a sun-drenched
lawn beyond, Rishel said, ``If you want a Tahitian Gauguin, you
want this Gauguin. It has everything, that dazzling light of the
tropics.''
   Placement of the paintings emphasizes contrasting styles of the
artists, but shows similarities and examples of borrowed ideas.
   In one room hangs Cezanne's imposing ``Portrait of Uncle
Dominique as a Monk,'' an 1866 painting showing a stern
black-bearded figure in a white hooded robe against an olive gray
backdrop.
   At the opposite end of the wall is ``Seated Peasant,'' a Cezanne
work painted about 30 years later in softer dark hues, a serious
but less imposing figure with his arms folded in his lap.
   The paintings, on loan, had been in the Annenberg's Rancho
Mirage, Calif., home. The exhibition is set to run through Sept. 17.
   Annenberg founded Triangle Publications, which included TV
Guide, Good Food and Seventeen magazine and The Racing Form when it
was sold last year.
   Annenberg was appointed ambassador to England during the Nixon
administration and in 1981, Mrs. Annenberg was appointed chief of
protocol by then-President Reagan.
</TEXT>
