<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Armenia     05-18 0345</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Armenia,0354</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thousands Rally in Armenia to Demand Freedom for Jailed Activists</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of Armenians demonstrated for the
freedom of jailed activists and action by the legislature on their
demands to annex a region in neighboring Azerbaijan, a local
journalist said Thursday.
   About 40,000 people in Yerevan, the capital of Armenia, took
part in the two-hour protest Wednesday in front of the Matenadaran,
a world-famous library of ancient manuscripts, said Rem Ananikan,
deputy director of the official Armenpress news agency.
   The demonstration was illegal under military regulations imposed
to restore order in Yerevan, but no arrests were reported, Ananikan
said.
   Speaking in a telephone interview from Yerevan, Ananikan said
police initially tried to break up the protest but ultimately let
it go on.
   The protesters were calling for the release of 14 jailed members
of the Karabkah Committee, which last year launched a campaign for
Armenia to annex the Nagorno-Karabakh region, where three-quarters
of the 162,000 inhabitants are ethnic Armenians. Nagorno-Karabakh
is part of the republic of Azerbaijan.
   The Kremlin rejected the unification demand, putting
Nagorno-Karabakh under Moscow's direct control instead and jailing
the committee members.
   Ananikan said demonstrators also called for an emergency meeting
of Armenia's Supreme Soviet legislature to resolve the Karabakh
issue before a new national parliament, the Congress of People's
Deputies, convenes in Moscow on May 25.
   ``They want the leadership of our republic to get involved once
again in the Karabakh question,'' the Armenpress official said. He
said the protesters demanded the unification of Karabakh with
Armenia or its complete withdrawal from Azerbaijan.
   The Armenian drive to annex Nagorno-Karabakh, launched in
February 1988, led to ethnic strife between predominantly Christian
Armenians and mostly Moslem Azerbaijanis in which more than 90
people were killed last year.
   After four months of relative calm, unrest broke out again in
Nagorno-Karabakh early this month as Armenians accused Soviet
authorities of trying to increase the number of Azerbaijanis in the
district through a crash building program. A general strike
declared May 3 by Armenians in the district was continuing,
Ananikan said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
