<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     05-18 0595</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0612</SECOND>
<HEAD>Severe Weather Over The Central Gulf Coast And The Plains</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Severe thunderstorms battered Louisiana and southeastern Texas
on Thursday, producing tornadoes, damaging wind and very heavy rain
for a second day in a row, and thunderstorms also developed over
the Plains.
   From 5 to 14 inches of rain fell in 24 hours over southeastern
Texas and western Louisiana. Coushatta, La., reported 14.20 inches
in 24 hours.
   Flooding closed some 40 major roads in Louisiana, State Police
said.
   Two train engines and 15 rail cars derailed during the night
when they hit flooded tracks in northwestern Louisiana's Red River
Parish, authorities said Thursday.
   A tornado was reported near Rayne, La., in Acadia Parish shortly
before noon and another was spotted northeast of Lafayette, La.,
after noon, authorities. There were no immediate reports of
injuries.
   A tornado also was reported briefly on the ground near downtown
Houston, Texas.
   On Wednesday, a tornado killed a woman and four people drowned
in swollen creeks in Texas. Flooding forced hundreds of Dallas-Fort
Worth area residents to leave their homes. A levee failed along the
Trinity River in Dallas and rising tributaries forced more
evacuations Thursday.
   In Lake Charles, La., the roof of a building housing a Masonic
lodge and a furniture store collapsed early Thursday under the
weight of collected rain water, said Civil Defense director Jerry
Merchant. There were no injuries.
   Wind damage was reported elsewhere in Louisiana with power lines
down and trees blown onto at least two mobile homes, the National
Weather Service said.
   Heavier rain during the six hours up to 1 p.m. CDT included 5.11
inches at Houston's airport; 3.23 inches at Beaumont-Port Arthur,
Texas; and 2.50 inches at Lake Charles, La.
   Another area of severe thunderstorms developed across eastern
Kansas and eastern Oklahoma. Tornadoes were reported in Kansas near
Sylvia and Clay Center and in northeastern Oklahoma's Wagoner and
Rogers counties, the weather service said.
   Two houses and two mobile homes were damaged by the Oklahoma
twisters and one person was injured, authorities said.
   Gerald Gouard, Rogers County, Okla., commissioner, said
relatives who gathered at his house before a funeral saw one
tornado develop. The tornado came to the edge of his yard, but rose
up over the house and a shop before hitting another house.
   Hail as big as golf balls fell west of Valley Falls, Kan., and
hail an inch in diameter fell elsewhere in Kansas at Basehor,
Linwood and Kansas City.
   Overbrook, Kan., got half an inch of rain in 10 minutes.
   Elsewhere, rain was scattered over the northern Pacific Coast,
as well as from south-central Nebraska into northern Illinois. A
snow advisory was posted for the Cascades of Oregon.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 32
degrees at Butte, Mont., to 97 at Beeville, Texas. Thursday's low
for the 48 contiguous states was 23 degrees at Gunnison, Colo.
   For Friday, showers and thunderstorms were forecast from the
central and eastern Gulf Coast region across much of the
Mississippi Valley, and the Ohio Valley into the upper Great Lakes.
Showers and some thunderstorms were expected over the northern
Plains. Showers were forecast across the Pacific Northwest.
   Highs in the 50s and 60s were predicted from the northern and
central Pacific Coast to the upper Missouri Valley; in the 60s
across northeastern Minnesota and much of Wisconsin; in the 90s
across much of Texas, the southern Rockies, the desert Southwest
and the central and southern Florida Peninsula; and generally in
the 70s or 80s in the remainder of the nation.
</TEXT>
