<FIRST>u i AM-Venezuela 1stLd-Writethru   05-18 0475</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Venezuela, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0685,0491</SECOND>
<HEAD>Labor Toughs Enforce Strike Call; Most Businesses Stay Closed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with president pledging to keep
austerity plan; pickup 6th graf, ``Close it...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANTHONY CAPLAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shops and banks were closed Thursday
and labor activists roamed the streets to enforce a 12-hour general
strike, but President Carlos Andres Perez pledged to keep a
government austerity plan that prompted the protest.
   The strike was the first in 31 years of democracy in Venezuela.
The strike organizer, the Venezuela Confederation of Workers,
claimed it paralyzed the nation.
   But Perez, in a nationally televised news conference held five
minutes after the strike ended at 6 p.m., said the government would
continue with the austerity plan ``because it is the only way open
to us.''
   The president said he sympathized with the working classes, hit
by severe increases in bus fares, gasoline and other consumer
items, but he stressed that any reversal would mean a ``catastrophe
for Venezuela.''
   In downtown Caracas, strike supporters surrounded a McDonald's
restaurant, breaking windows and forcing the restaurant to close.
   ``Close it down! Down with the gringos!'' shouted about 200
members of the Venezuelan Worker's Federation, ``dissuasive
brigades'' dispatched to roam the streets and enforce the work
stoppage.
   ``Up with McDonald's! This is a free country!'' customers
shouted back.
   Fistfights broke out between union members and store managers.
Soldiers were sent in to cordon off the store.
   The labor force also forced the closing of several banks that
defied the strike call.
   The 3 million-member labor federation called the strike to
protest the austerity measures, which prompted riots in February
and left at least 276 people dead.
   The unrest broke out after Perez cut government subsidies for a
broad range of consumer items and public services as part of an
effort to ease payments on the nation's $33 billion foreign debt.
   Many people blamed labor unions, which are closely tied to the
governing Democratic Action Party, for not doing enough to defend
working-class people affected by the measures. In response, the
union called for the strike.
   The government declared the strike illegal but said it would
``avoid useless confrontations that in no way benefit the nation.''
   Squadrons of motorcycle police cruised the streets, which were
empty as most Venezuelans stayed home.
   Labor leaders said the strike closed the nation's small and
medium industries, shops, banks and public services, and paralyzed
transportation.
   All international flights were canceled from 6 a.m. to 6 p.m.,
travel agents said.
   Basic industries such as oil and aluminum operated normally
under a pact worked out between the government-run enterprises and
unions affiliated with the confederation.
   Venezuela depends on oil exports for 90 percent of its export
revenue.
   Planning Minister Miguel Rodriguez said the strike would cost
the country $300 million in lost productivity.
</TEXT>
