<FIRST>r e BC-Theater     05-18 0417</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Theater,0435</SECOND>
<HEAD>Comedy Duo Writes, Performs Off-Broadway in `Laughing Matters'</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: No PMs Planned.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Laughing Matters'' is the title of an
off-Broadway evening of sketches written and performed by the
comedy duo of Linda Wallem and Peter Tolan. While a viewer doesn't
fall apart in helpless bellylaughs, one really does laugh _ a lot.
   The title of the evening which opened Thursday at the Theater at
St. Peter's Church correctly indicates that it's focusing on
situations which are funny.
   In the first mini-play, a couple meet on a blind date in a
restaurant. The man, a nerd who pronounces pate as if it were the
crown of his head, mentally is moving the relationship on
fast-forward and is terribly concerned about AIDS. At a perfect
moment for get-acquainted small talk, he blurts, ``Can I have a
throat culture?''
   In the next vignette, Tolan is a fast-talking, money and
telephone-addicted agent visited by a 15-year-old recording star
who doesn't like being different from other girls. In a rather
sweet ending, she feels a lot better when Mr. High Pressure relaxes
long enough to tell her she only has a few more months of stardom.
   Other skits satirize overconcern with age and what morality in
government means in Washington D.C. Act 2 begins with Tolan playing
piano for three songs he wrote, sung by both of them. One,
sprinkled with Yiddish words, comments on how Catholics and
Protestants who move to New York become a little Jewish. It was
greeted with laughs of recognition.
   Both halves of the evening end with a couple in Champaign, Ill.
To say that their taste and sophistication is on the backwoodsy
level is probably placing that a notch too high. Yelling
conflicting commands at their children is their child-rearing style
and when once they yell the same thing, Miss Wallem says
wonderingly, ``That doesn't happen very often.''
   Martin Charnin, who wrote lyrics for and directed ``Annie,''
directed, keeping the evening moving crisply. Zev Guber, Sanford H.
Fisher and Beluga Entertainment Corp. produced.
   Miss Wallem was born in Madison, Wis., grew up in Rockford,
Ill., and attended the University of Minnesota in Minneapolis.
Tolan is from Scituate, Mass., and attended the University of
Massachusetts in Amherst.
   Their sketches have variety and humor and though people may yell
angrily, anger and satire never cut deep.
   Amplified ``backstage'' converstions between skits doesn't add
much for the audience but gives the pair time to change clothes.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
