<FIRST>r w AM-Manley-Literacy 1stLd-Writethru a0639 05-18 0571</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Manley-Literacy, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0639,540</SECOND>
<HEAD>Football Star Tells Tortures of Illiteracy</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: SUBS 2nd graf, Manley, a ... , to CORRECT that he did not graduate
from Oklahoma State University.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Football star Dexter Manley told a Senate
panel Thursday that he has finally overcome childhood rejection and
gained self-respect since seeking help three years agoto learn to
read and write.
   Manley, a defensive end for the Washington Redskins, graduated
from Houston schools and completed all but 45 hours of
undergraduate work at Oklahoma State University despite a severe
learning disability that effectively rendered him illiterate.
   He enrolled in night classes at Washington's Lab School three
years ago after seeing teammate Joe Theismann felled by a broken
leg during a game against the New York Giants.
   ``I can recall that vividly,'' Manley told Sen. Paul Simon,
D-Ill., chairman of the Senate education subcommittee. ``I had so
much fear and insecurity. I was saying, I hope to God this never
happens to me because what would I do.''
   Manley, 30, was judged to have a second-grade reading level when
he entered the Lab School. He was diagnosed as having an auditory
channel problem that makes it difficult for him to remember what he
hears, particularly rote material like the sounds that letters make.
   ``Somehow or another, you have to find the will ... to come
forward and ask for help. That's the most difficult thing for a
human being to do,'' Manley said of his decision at 27 to face his
problem. ``I had to humble myself. I had to walk into the Lab
School and not pretend. Today I can read and write. I have some
self-respect.''
   Manley brought with him a written statement, but with all eyes
on him in a hearing room packed with spectators and television
cameras, he began to stumble from the first sentence. Sweat rolled
down his cheeks and tears of frustration filled his eyes by the
time he had reached the second paragraph.
   There was a long pause. Then Wally ``Famous'' Amos, the cookie
magnate and a spokesperson for the Literacy Volunteers of America,
approached the witness table, put his arm around Manley and spoke
softly to him.
   ``Just tell your story, how it came about,'' Simon told Manley
after Amos had returned to his seat. ``Don't worry about that
prepared statement. This takes more courage than anything you've
done on the football field.''
   Manley, obviously relieved, scrapped the statement and told
Simon and Sen. Barbara Mikulski, D-Md., about receiving 19 grades
of ``F'' in second grade and being placed in a special education
class for four years.
   ``It was very difficult because I felt I was normal, but I was
told I was dumb and stupid. I had a lot of rejection in my life,''
Manley said. Athletics was the only thing ``that built some
self-esteem, some self-worth in Dexter Manley. Other than that I
had no identity.''
   Manley said special education consisted of ``more or less
playing with blocks'' with no instruction in phonics or other
skills needed to read.
   ``I was passed, of course, and that repeated itself all along,''
he said. He attributed his progress through the education system to
his willingness to show up for class, but added: ``It's amazing
that I've come this far. I've had a lot of tutoring, but I would
suspect that I was just passed through.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890518-0206 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-18-89 2126EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-Bush 1stLd-Writethru a0631 05-18 0648</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0631,640</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Challenges Business Community to Help Improve Schools</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Adds two grafs at end</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush acknowledged on Thursday
that his $441 million program to reward excellence in education is
not ``a be-all and an end-all,'' and he challenged America's
business community to help improve schools.
   ``The fact is that unless we act, our children will be
ill-equipped to read, to write or to understand new technologies,
to compete in the work place,'' Bush said.
   ``And the fact is that education partnerships can help us act
boldly and urgently, to keep America No. 1,'' he said.
   Bush made his remarks in a speech en route to a four-day stay at
his summer home in Kennebunkport, Maine. On Saturday, he will meet
visiting President Francois Mitterrand of France.
   The two leaders will travel to Boston University on Sunday to
receive honorary degrees, make remarks at the school's commencement
exercises and hold a joint news conference. A week later, they will
gather in Brussels with other Western leaders for a NATO summit.
   Bush made his education speech at an Eastman Kodak photographic
plant. He praised the company for putting up some of the money that
he said helped one school overcome a high dropout rate and a poor
academic showing to become one of the top-rated schools in the
state.
   Before his address, Bush toured the school, the Wilson Magnet
High School, which offers special courses in computer science,
robotics, photo-optics and Japanese language studies.
   ``Rochester and Kodak embody the notion that helping others
through cooperation ... is America at her best,'' Bush said.
   Bush's education program offers $441 million for merit schools,
magnet schools and other programs. It has been criticized by
congressional Democrats and educators as insufficient.
   ``No, our program isn't a be-all and an end-all,'' Bush said.
``We're living in times of complicated resource allocation.
   ``But it is a commitment, a commitment to help business and
academia make America much more productive, a commitment to
partnerships, a commitment which you share.''
   The bulk of the money in Bush's bill, $250 million, would go for
a ``presidential merit schools'' program of cash awards to public
and private schools that make substantial progress in raising
student educational achievement, creating a safe and drug-free
environment and reducing the dropout rate.
   It also calls for $100 million in new spending on magnet schools
_ such as Wilson _ offering special courses.
   Bush said that in visiting Rochester, ``I honor the countless
individuals and companies across America who are following your
example.
   ``And to those not yet involved, I challenge you to get
involved,'' he said. ``For America's public and private sectors,
they can exceed the sum of their parts.''
   Before leaving Washington, Bush met at the White House with
Nobel Prize laureate Archbishop Desmond Tutu and a South African
anti-apartheid delegation.
   The White House also hailed the Organization of American States
for adopting a resolution saying that Panamanian ruler Manuel
Antonio Noriega was responsible for ``abuses'' and the electoral
crisis in his country. The group also voted to send three foreign
minister to Panama to try to induce him to give up power.
   Saying the White House was pleased by the measure, press
secretary Marlin Fitzwater said, ``It does constitute a
condemnation of Noriega by name for his abuses of the electoral
process and calls for a transition of power. ... We're gratified
that all the OAS countries shared the United States' position.''
   In Kennebunkport, Bush took his speedboat out into the Atlantic
for a couple of hours. His motor got hung up on lobster track lines
and he had to hang overboard to untangle them while someone hung
onto his ankles.
   In the evening, the president went to a local restaurant to dine
on stuffed lobster with his wife Barbara and some aides.
</TEXT>
