<FIRST>r a AM-LATeachers 1stLd-Writethru a0696 05-18 0485</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-LA Teachers, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0696,0499</SECOND>
<HEAD>Negotiations Muddied By Conflicting Reports On Money For Settlement</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 8 grafs to UPDATE with attendance report; details
on news blackout; union seeking restraining order; picks up 4th graf, `The
district ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD DE ATLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The first formal talks in months between the
striking teachers union and the school district took place under a
news blackout Thursday, with the situation muddied by conflicting
reports on school finances.
   The strike by at least 22,000 teachers in the nation's
second-largest district was in its fourth day, with the 600 schools
in the 700-square-mile district reduced to day-care facilities as
absenteeism ran high.
   Student attendance has declined steadily throughout the week. Of
the 551,759 students enrolled this quarter, 283,620 were counted
Thursday, down from 329,371 on Monday, the first day of the strike.
   Other than announcing the resumption of talks, neither side
would release any information on the first formal meeting since an
impasse in March.
   ``There is a total blackout,'' said United Teachers-Los Angeles
spokesman Don Schrack, on Thursday.
   The union negotiating team refused to disclose any details of
the talks, including time and place, to ensure that no information
would be released, Schrack said.
   ``That was something that was wanted and desired by both
sides,'' said Diana Munatones, a spokeswoman for the Los Angeles
Unified School District.
   Union lawyers also sought a court order late Thursday to
prohibit the school district from halting monthly premium payments
to striking teachers, said Catherine Carey, a union spokeswoman.
   The district had on its side a fact-finder's report received
Wednesday agreeing it had no money to offer beyond a 21.5 percent
raise over three years.
   But confusion reigned after Gov. George Deukmejian announced the
same day that the state expects a $2.5 billion budget windfall over
the next two years.
   The state's Proposition 98 requires virtually all revenue above
an expenditure limit to be given to the schools. The
594,000-student Los Angeles district reportedly could receive $120
million to $228 million of that money.
   But School Board President Roberta Weintraub said the district
had no assurances it would get the money and could not sweeten its
wage offer.
   Deukmejian said he wants to enact budget reform and guide more
of the surplus toward transportation needs.
   United Teachers-Los Angeles President Wayne Johnson, encouraged
by the windfall report, immediately changed the union's demand from
21 percent over two years to 26 percent over three years.
   Weintraub called that ``an impossible figure. It is not
acceptable.''
   ``If they stand firm, the union's strike is going to continue,''
said Johnson.
   The UTLA represents 22,000 of the district's 32,000 teachers,
nurses, counselors and librarians. The strike is the district's
first since a 23-day walkout in 1970.
   Currently, teachers' pay ranges from a beginning $23,440 to
$43,319 to those with doctorates, 98 extra course units and 19
years' experience.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
