<FIRST>u i AM-Colombia-Prison     05-18 0296</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Colombia-Prison,0306</SECOND>
<HEAD>15 Killed in Colombian Prison Raid</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEDELLIN, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An attack force stormed Bellavista
prison Thursday in an apparent attempt to free jailed drug runners
and 15 people died before the attackers fled without accomplishing
their mission, police said.
   At least 12 inmates who tried to escape in the confusion and
three prison guards were killed during a two-hour battle, they
reported.
   Officers said about 20 men with bombs and automatic weapons
tried to shoot their way past guards in a wing of the penitentiary
that houses mainly drug traffickers and leftist guerrillas.
   Authorities reported that when police and soldiers arrived to
help the prison guards, most of the raiders fled.
   Bellavista lies six miles north of Medellin in northwest
Colombia, center of the powerful Medellin drug cartel.
   Among those housed in the targeted wing, known as Pavilion 5,
was Freddy Rodriguez, son of Gonzalo Rodriguez Gacha, said to be a
leader of the Medellin Cartel. Officials said his fate was not
known immediately.
   Freddy Rodriguez was jailed two weeks ago on charges of illegal
weapons possession.
   It was not immediately known whether he was linked to the
planned escape.
   Bellavista, considered a low-security prison, has been the site
of three escapes since December. Some guards were fired for alleged
complicity in the escapes.
   Secretary-General Diogenes Plata of the Ministry of Justice said
in Bogota, the capital, that state security forces earlier found a
plan for a big breakout at a unspecified jail and that prison
guards nationwide were put on alert last week.
   ``Despite their outdated weapons, the prison guards were able to
repel the attack until they obtained help from the army and the
police, but unfortunately three of the guards died at the hands of
the attackers,'' Plata said.
</TEXT>
