<FIRST>r i AM-Brazil-Rains     05-18 0294</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brazil-Rains,0303</SECOND>
<UNK>Rains, Mudslides Kill at Least 18 People in Brazil</UNK>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Torrential rains set off mudslides
that engulfed shantytowns in the northeastern city of Salvador on
Thursday, and at least 18 people were killed, fire department
officials said.
   Fireman Trindade de Santana said a slide in the outlying slum of
Calcada late Thursday afternoon swallowed five modest
concrete-block homes and killed a mother and her four daughters.
   ``A wall of mud rushed down the hill and buried them,'' de
Santana said by telephone from Salvador, a coastal city of 1.8
million people 1,055 miles northeast of Rio de Janeiro.
   ``It happened so fast, they probably didn't have time to move.''
   Rescue workers with search lamps dug their way with hoes and
spades through chest-deep mud Thursday night looking for additional
victims.
   ``We're almost sure there's at least another 10 buried under
there,'' de Santana said.
   He said it rained almost without letup since last week, and a
particularly heavy downpour late Wednesday night apparently
triggered the mudslide. He said more rain was forecast for Friday.
   Earlier Thursday, in the impoverished Lobato district of
Salvador, a hillside fell away and buried 10 clay and
concrete-block houses, fireman Julio Cesar dos Santos said by phone.
   ``We know of at least 12 people who were killed when the houses
collapsed, and one person in another slum area who was drowned,''
dos Santos said.
   TV film footage on Globo TV, Brazil's largest commercial
network, showed helmeted firemen with hoes helping slum residents
clear mud from destroyed houses in a search for more victims.
   In Santo Amaro, a city 50 miles northwest of Salvador, six
people drowned and about 30,000 remained homeless as a result of
flooding last week, dos Santos said.
</TEXT>
