<DOCNO> AP890518-0215 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-18-89 2249EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r e BC-Dance     05-18 0487</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Dance,0508</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ballet Theater Adds 2 New Dances</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: No PMs Planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Martha Clarke, known primarily as a creator of
dream-like theater evenings, among them ``Vienna: Lusthaus'' and
``The Garden of Earthly Delights,'' entered another garden a decade
ago and created a ballet.
   She, Robert Barnett, artistic co-director of Pilobolus Dance
Theater, and Felix Blaska, who has directed a dance company,
choreographed the 10-minute ``The Garden of Villandry'' and danced
its premiere in Paris in 1979.
   On Thursday night, American Ballet Theater performed it for the
first time in this city, at the Metropolitan Opera House. Martine
Van Hamel, Kevin McKenzie and Michael Owen were the trio _ or
triangle. Pianist Howard Barr, violinist Dennis Cleveland and
cellist Eric Bartlett were the on-stage players of a Schubert trio.
   Miss Van Hamel is embraced and eloquently partnered by first one
then the other of the men. No story is discernable as the three
stroll and dance in the famous _ here imagined _ gardens of a Loire
Valley chateau. The three don't seem to be a family. Their
affection seems excessive for friends taking the air. One thing is
clear; there's no jealousy. While one man is lifting the ballerina
in her long, bustled skirt, the other leans back nonchalantly,
hands in pockets.
   At one point, the two men swing Miss Van Hamel between them. It
doesn't look like the usual swinging of a ballerina but as though
she's sitting in a swing hanging from a tree. The audience,
realizing that, laughed.
   The effect is of a pleasant afternoon outing.
   On Tuesday, Amanda McKerrow and John Gardner danced company
dancer Clark Tippet's latest work, the 25-minute duet ``Some
Assembly Required.'' They also danced the ballet's premiere in
Washington in April. Music is William Bolcom's ``Second Sonata for
Violin and Piano,'' played by Lawrence Shapiro and Barr.
   This long pas de deux begins with Gardner, in T-shirt and jeans,
spending a lot of time on the floor, as the pony-tailed Miss
McKerrow spins and jumps over him. He carries her around, his knees
bent, with her feet on his thighs. Then he lifts her to his
shoulders and again slides to the floor.
   The choreography follows the music and in the second movement,
which Bolcom named ``Brutal-fast,'' the steps also are fast.
Gardner repeatedly flings her away, becoming almost menacing here,
as though a game has turned rough.
   When the music becomes gentle, they face each other on their
knees and he scoots forward, then stands to twirl her. A number of
the movement sequences, like facing each other on their knees, are
repeated. The final musical movement sounds almost like cakewalk
music. The couple do high jumps and dance in balletic ballroom
style to it.
   Neither dance is a favorite on one viewing but neither should
cause pain or make a ballet goer decide to leave early.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890518-0216 </DOCNO>
