<DOCNO> AP890518-0219 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-18-89 2305EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Nicaragua 1stLd-Writethru a0723 05-18 0635</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Nicaragua, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0723,0651</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviets Again Say They Stopped Arms Shipments to Nicaragua</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout with conflicting Soviet, Nicaraguan statements
on arms shipments, other remarks by Nicaraguan president. No pickup</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   t
   MOSCOW (AP) _ Soviet officials publicly asserted for the first
time on Thursday that Moscow has halted arms shipments to
Nicaragua, but President Daniel Ortega of Nicaragua himself said
otherwise.
   The Soviet claim met with skepticism from U.S. officials when it
was communicated earlier in private.
   And on Thursday Ortega denied in Nicaragua that the Soviets had
stopped supplying arms to his Central American nation, saying they
continue to fulfill their commitments to his leftist Sandinista
government.
   Soviet Foreign Ministry spokesman Vadim Perfiliev told a regular
news briefing, ``The United States is very well aware that the
Soviet Union is exercising a certain restraint, and in fact for a
certain time has not been shipping any armaments to Nicaragua.''
   Yan A. Burlyai, an official in the ministry's Latin American
department, echoed that claim, but neither man gave reporters an
exact date for any halt of arms shipments to Nicaragua.
   Asked by one reporter to spell out for how long a period the
Soviets had stopped the weapons deliveries, Burlyai replied only
that it was ``not one day, not two days, not one week; it's much
more.''
   Burlyai also said shipments of food, medicine and bandages to
the Sandinistas could not be properly considered military
assistance, leaving open the possibility that such deliveries by
the Soviets continue.
   U.S. officials on Monday disclosed that Soviet President Mikhail
S. Gorbachev had written President Bush that arms supplies to
Nicaragua would halt. But the White House said Tuesday no proof
emerged that Gorbachev had made good on his promise.
   When a reporter asked Ortega in Niquinohomo, Nicaragua, on
Thursday about the Gorbachev letter, Ortega smilingly replied, ``We
have normal relations ... with the Soviet Union in the fields of
economic aid, military aid. The Soviet Union has met all of its
agreements with Nicaragua.''
   He added, however, he is ``in favor of reaching an
understanding'' regarding foreign military aid to Central America
under the Esquipulas regional peace pact.
   Under the pact, signed Aug. 7, 1987 by Ortega and the presidents
of Honduras, Costa Rica, El Salvador and Guatemala, foreign aid
would end to irregular forces in the region. That is understood to
mean no Soviet aid to the leftist Salvadoran guerrillas and no U.S.
aid to the Nicaraguan rebels, known as Contras.
   Ortega was in Niquinohomo, a small town 20 miles south of the
capital of Managua, to speak on the 94th anniversary of the birth
of Gen. Augusto Cesar Sandino, the nationalist rebel leader from
whom the Sandinistas take their name.
   State Department spokesman Richard Boucher told reporters in
Washington on Wednesday that the Soviet Union may have halted arms
shipments to Nicaragua, but weapons were continuing to arrive from
Cuba and Moscow's East European allies. He said the level and
pattern of arms shipments through April was similar to that last
year.
   Boucher said the Soviet Union and its allies sent 27 shipments
of military goods to Nicaragua through April.
   ``We are not shipping any armaments,'' Burlyai said Thursday,
while indicating that Soviet shipments of other goods for the
Sandinista army may be continuing.
   In other remarks made by Ortega in Niquinohomo:
   _He charged that the right-wing party of Salvadoran
President-elect Alfredo Cristiani was responsible for several
murders, including that of Archbishop Arnulfo Romero of El Salvador
in 1980.
   _He condemned what he called U.S. intervention in Panama and
Wednesday's vote in the Organization of American States, saying:
``The Yankees impose the points of discussion on the Latin American
agenda.''
   The OAS voted to send a commission to Panama to investigate
charges of fraud in the May 7 elections, which the government later
annulled.
</TEXT>
