<FIRST>r a AM-TowerDown     05-18 0236</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tower Down,0242</SECOND>
<HEAD>Air Force Jet Hits Tower, Makes Emergency Landing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FRINK, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Air Force fighter jet practicing a
low-flying stunt with another jet Thursday clipped a broadcast
tower's support wire, toppling the tower and knocking one radio and
two television stations off the air.
   The damaged F-15 Eagle made an emergency landing at Tyndall Air
Force Base near Panama City after the accident in this Florida
Panhandle hamlet, said a spokeswoman at Tyndall, Marilyn Silcox.
   There were no reported injuries in the 2:30 p.m. incident,
officials said.
   ``The entire tower was knocked flat on the ground,'' said
Cynthia Gould, news anchorwoman for television station WMBB.
   The loss of the 1,549-foot-tall tower knocked WMBB, public
television station WFSG and commercial radio station WPAP off the
air, Ms. Gould said.
   The F-15 jet's left landing gear was damaged, forcing the pilot,
an instructor assigned to the 2nd Tactical Fighter Training
Squadron, to balance the plane on its nose wheel and right landing
gear during the landing, said Capt. Carolyn Hodge, a public affairs
officer.
   Both the jet and the second F-15 that it was attempting to
intercept had been cleared to fly as low as 500 feet, Ms. Hodge
said.
   It is the second accident involving a Tyndall-based F-15 jet
this month. Another jet crashed into the Gulf of Mexico on May 1,
killing a student pilot who had been practicing dogfighting tactics.
</TEXT>
