<FIRST>u i AM-Nicaragua-Elections 1stLd-Writethru a0706 05-18 0529</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nicaragua-Elections, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0706,0539</SECOND>
<HEAD>17 Parties May Participate in Elections</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with Ortega saying no more electoral
reforms. Pick up 3rd pvs, `Five groups...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DORALISA PILARTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four new parties obtained legal
status, raising to 17 the number of political groups that could
take part in next February's general balloting, officials said
Thursday.
   Opposition groups, however, are still disputing the fairness of
the electoral laws, and it is not yet known how many of them will
run candidates to challenge the ruling Sandinista National
Liberation Front.
   President Daniel Ortega said Thursday the political opposition
should not expect any more reforms.
   ``There will be no more concessions. I want this to be very
clear,'' Ortega said. ``The reforms that were going to take place
have taken place and that's the end of it.''
   Ortega made his comment during a speech Thursday evening in
Niquinohomo, a small community 25 miles south of Managua, where
Gen. Augusto Cesar Sandino was born. The speech was on the occasion
of the 94th anniversary of the birth of Sandino, from whom the
Sandinista National Liberation Front takes its name.
   Five groups asking for legal recognition as political parties
were rejected by the National Council of Political Parties. The
council approved the request of four other parties, said Orlando
Tardencilla, secretary to council president Hugo Mejia.
   One group, the Authentic Liberal Party, was denied legal status
because its slogan, ``Neither Somocism Nor Marxism,'' harmed
another party, the Marxist-Leninist Popular Action Movement,
Tardencilla said. Somocism refers to support for the regime of late
President Anastasio Somoza, whom the Sandinistas ousted in the
1978-79 revolution.
   The council rejected another group, the Conservative National
Union, because although its statutes formally speak against foreign
intervention, they accept it ``when a government fails to respect
the principles of Western democracy.''
   Other groups were turned down because they had the same names as
legally constituted parties or did not meet minimum requirements
under the law.
   Critics say the reforms in election and news media laws were
passed by the Sandinista-dominated National Assembly, or
legislature, without considering opposition demands. They say the
reforms are merely cosmetic and still give the Sandinistas an
unfair advantage.
   In a letter to the National Reconciliation Commission, chaired
by Cardinal Miguel Obando y Bravo, the opposition repeated its
complaints and accused the government of failing to live up to its
commitments of democratic reforms in a regional peace accord.
   Vice President Sergio Ramirez said his government ``cannot
accept that the National Reconciliation Commission become a
negotiating panel between the government and the opposition because
this is not its role.''
   Under a Central American peace accord signed in February,
President Daniel Ortega moved up elections by 10 months to Feb. 25,
1990, and promised legal reforms to ensure the balloting is free
and fair.
   Ortega and his colleagues from El Salvador, Honduras, Costa Rica
and Guatemala also agreed to draft a plan by May 15 to dismantle
the Nicaraguan rebel force now encamped in Honduras near the
Nicaraguan border. The deadline was later extended to a yet
unspecified date in July by mutual accord.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
