<TEXT>
   Some conservatives, certain of Ronald Reagan's
place in history, are talking up the idea of finding a place for
him alongside the granite faces of four great presidents at Mount
Rushmore.
   And they think they've gotten a wink from the man himself.
   At least Reagan smiled when an artist's sketch was presented
last summer showing him alongside the Rushmore visages, says R.
Emmett Tyrrell Jr., a promoter of the movement to add Reagan.
   ``He seemed pleased,'' said Tyrrell, editor-in-chief of American
Spectator magazine, a monthly conservative review.
