<FILEID>AP-NR-05-18-89 1024EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a PM-APonTV-MiamiVice Adv19   05-18 0817</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AP on TV-Miami Vice, Adv 19,0833</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv19</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Friday PMs, May 19, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>NBC Gives Faded `Miami Vice' Honorable Send-Off</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NBC is showing some class this weekend by giving
its now-lukewarm but once sizzling detective series ``Miami Vice''
an honorable sendoff in a special two-hour conclusion Sunday.
   The series that launched Don Johnson's career and a wave of
fashion trends is leaving the air after five seasons. Unlike ABC,
which allowed its once-ballyhooed ``Moonlighting'' to whimper away
in so-so final episode that ended up at the bottom of the Nielsens,
NBC is giving ``Vice'' the coveted Sunday movie slot.
   The producers and the network have refused to pre-screen or
discuss the episode in order to keep the ending a secret. But
executive producer Michael Mann has a penchant for the dramatic. He
ended ``Crime Story'' _ prematurely, it turned out _ by
incinerating his villains with no less than an atomic bomb.
   When ``Miami Vice'' premiered in 1984, it amazed jaded
television critics with its fresh writing, charmingly seedy
characters and art deco Miami landscapes. The show derived from a
now-fabled scribble of an idea by NBC Entertainment President
Brandon Tartikoff _ ``MTV cops.''
   Anthony Yerkovich, a producer-writer on ``Hill Street Blues,''
created the characters and wrote the two-hour pilot, which still
stands as one of the best cop shows ever.
   The look came from Michael Mann, then a relatively obscure film
director (``The Jericho Mile,'' ``Thief'') who knew how to put film
and rock music together in a way that made hair stand up on the
back of necks _ beginning with the opening montage set to pounding,
synthesized Caribbean rhythms created by Jan Hammer.
   Thomas Carter (``Hill Street'') directed the first episode, and
American TV entered a new era of style _ cool colors, hot sounds.
Straight-from-the-charts music such as Phil Collins' ``In the Air
Tonight'' wafted from television speakers in the middle of network
prime time.
   The show didn't catch on in the ratings until summer reruns,
when word of mouth got around. In later seasons, the kids' favorite
show met its ratings demise, ironically enough, at the hands of
CBS' aging, night-time soap ``Dallas.''
   In the beginning, ``Vice'' viewers were as intrigued by the
characters as the color scheme. Don Johnson was virtual unknown,
with a credit list of failed pilots and ignominious movie parts.
But he connected with Sonny Crockett, a down-at-the-heels former
football star who lived on a boat guarded by an alligator named
Elvis.
   Another unknown, Philip Michael Thomas, played Ricardo Tubbs, an
interloping black cop from the New York streets who came to Miami
looking for his brother's murderer. City slicker Tubbs and
good-ol'-boy Crockett were the classic odd couple and were,
naturally, forced to become partners. NBC will try the unlikely
buddies concept again in a new cop show, ``Hardball,'' that goes
into ``Vice's'' time period next season.
   ``Vice'' might have impressed the critics, but it was virtually
ignored by the Hollywood establishment. It won only a handful of
technical Emmy Awards, except for Edward James Olmos' 1985 win as
best supporting actor in a drama. Olmos joined the cast midway
through the first season as Martin Castillo, a mysterious, taciturn
successor to the cops' first boss (Gregory Sierra, who left the
series).
   If the industry establishment ignored ``Vice,'' the feeling was
mutual. Mann shunned the usual TV writers and hired playwrights and
authors to create his scripts. He bypassed the pool of Hollywood
regulars and cast New York stage actors in guest roles.
   The late playwright Miguel Pinero (``Short Eyes'') wrote for
``Vice,'' and played Tubbs' archrival Calderon. Bruce Willis, who
later became a star on ``Moonlighting,'' had only an Off Broadway
production of ``Fool for Love'' to his credit when he was cast as
an arms dealer-wife beater in an episode. Rock star Glenn Frey made
his acting debut in an episode based on his song ``Smuggler's
Blues.''
   The show took chances. In a remarkably sophisticated episode,
``Evan,'' Crockett and a one-time partner (William Russ) confronted
their long-hidden mutual guilt over the suicide of another partner
they had rejected because of his homosexuality.
   In the last three seasons, the show drifted away from character
development and flirted with self-parody. It still hit the mark
sometimes, but by then was taken for granted.
   ``Vice'' lives on _ on cable. USA Network bought the reruns.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Elsewhere in television:
   `SUNDAY NIGHT' GOES GENERIC _ NBC has renewed ``Sunday Night,''
with a new title: ``Michelob Presents Night Music,'' so stations
can carry it in other-than-Sunday, late-night time periods. The
critically praised hour-long music series from ``Saturday Night
Live'' producer Lorne Michaels features eclectic blends of jazz,
rock and blues overseen by hosts David Sanborn and Jools Holland.
It airs on NBC-owned stations and in syndication on other stations.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Fri PMs, May 19</NOTE>
</DOC>
