<FILEID>AP-NR-05-18-89 1248EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e PM-APonTV-NBCFall ADV22   05-18 0866</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AP on TV-NBC Fall, ADV 22,0885</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv22</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Monday PMs, May 22, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>NBC Relies on Old Standbys in Fall Movies</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: In 18th graf, bgn, Rod Parker ..., Ed. Weinberger, is cq</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NBC, the network of known quantities, has
enlisted such tried-and-true stars as Doris Day, Loretta Young,
Elizabeth Taylor and Anthony Quinn for a wave of star-driven,
1989-90 made-for-TV movies.
   The word ``reprise'' occurs frequently in NBC's list of upcoming
projects for the fall:
   Jack Klugman and Tony Randall will reprise their roles as ``The
Odd Couple,'' the popular series inspired by the movie.
   Randy Quaid will reprise his Emmy-nominated performance as
Lyndon B. Johnson in ``LBJ: The Presidential Years,'' a sequel to
``LBJ: The Early Years.'' Patti Lupone returns as Lady Bird Johnson.
   Also reprised is ``Eight Is Enough.'' The Bradford clan will
reunite for another reunion movie, this time ``An Eight Is Enough
Wedding.''
   Reprised, too, are fact-based dramas.
   Daniel J. Travanti (``Hill Street Blues'') stars as a prosecutor
in ``Howard Beach: Making the Case for Murder,'' based on the
real-life racially motivated Queens attack.
   NBC will make a miniseries about Drug Enforcement Agent Enrique
``Kiki'' Camarena, who was murdered by drug dealers. ``Desperados:
The `Kiki' Camarena Story'' will star Steven Bauer, Elizabeth Pena
and Craig T. Nelson.
   ``Murder In Mississippi'' will recount the final days of three
civil rights workers murdered in 1963. The TV movie is something of
a prequel to the Oscar-nominated film ``Mississippi Burning,''
which was a fictionalized account of the investigation into the
slayings.
   ``The Rock Hudson Story'' will be told in a TV movie. No casting
has been announced.
   ``Roxanne: The Prize Pulitzer'' was to have aired this season,
but was held over. It is based on Mrs. Pulitzer's autobiographical
account of her messy divorce from Herbert ``Pete'' Pulitzer.
   When not re-creating real-life stories, NBC's movies will be
based on classics. There is a two-part miniseries of ``Phantom of
the Opera'' in the offing. The miniseries is based on the Gaston
Leroux novel, not the hit Broadway musical. Anthony Quinn will star
in Ernest Hemingway's ``The Old Man and the Sea.'' Elizabeth Taylor
plays a faded movie queen and Mark Harmon the drifter she becomes
involved with in Tennessee Williams' ``Sweet Bird of Youth.''
Nicholas Roeg (``Track 29,'' ``The Man Who Fell to Earth'') directs
in his television debut.
   Loretta Young has been cast as ``Lady in a Corner,'' a respected
editor of an international magazine that an infamous publisher
wants to take over.
   Doris Day will star in the comedy ``Running Mates,'' as a woman
in a small, Southern California town who runs against an
interloping movie star for mayor in order to stop his plan to turn
the community into a tourist attraction _ shades of Clint Eastwood
who was elected mayor of Carmel, Calif.
   In a new-season preview for advertisers last week, NBC
Entertainment President Brandon Tartikoff showed clips of the five
new series that will join the network's prime-time schedule and
revealed some changes in returning shows.
   ``ALF'' will be getting into comic trouble caring for the
Tanners' new baby. The series will also get a new cast member, yet
unnamed, who will play Willie Tanner's brother.
   Lisa Bonet will return to the nest in ``The Cosby Show.'' The
spinoff she spun off to have a baby, ``A Different World,'' will
make a transition, too. Tartikoff says ``a mystery wedding'' will
begin the season.
   Rod Parker and Hal Cooper, producers on ``Empty Nest,'' are
going over to ``Dear John,'' in an apparent effort to relieve
tension on the set. Executive producer Ed. Weinberger will stay on.
   Tartikoff stressed that the network has ``the best bench since
Johnny,'' referring to shows waiting in the wings. The network only
needed four hours of new programming to fine-tune its No. 1
prime-time schedule. NBC will add two half-hour shows: ``Nutt
House,'' a slapstick Mel Brooks comedy with Harvey Korman and
Cloris Leachman running a New York hotel; and ``Sister Kate,''
starring Stephanie Beacham as a tough nun with a herd of orphans to
manage. The one-hour new shows are ``Baywatch,'' a lifeguard drama;
``Hardball,'' a mismatched-partners cop show; and ``Mancuso FBI,''
a spinoff of the political intrigue thriller ``Favorite Son.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Elsewhere in television:
   NEW NEW ORLEANS SHOW _ Fans of the Big Easy frustrated by CBS'
cancellation of ``Frank's Place'' have a new New Orleans-set show
waiting in the wings. Emmy winner Alfre Woodard and ``Sonny Spoon''
star Mario Van Peebles head the cast of the NBC pilot ``Orleans,''
from former ``L.A. Law'' co-executive producer Terry Louise Fisher.
Elizabeth Ashley and Roy Thinnes also star. ...
   BIG BIRD AND FRIENDS _ On June 22, the Smithsonian Institution's
National Museum of American History will open an exhibit honoring
the PBS children's series ``Sesame Street,'' commemorating its 20
years on the air. On the reasonable assumption that many of the
exhibit's visitors might be of the non-adult persuasion, the museum
will put photos on display at two different levels _ one at
standard grown-up eye level and the other a bit closer to the floor.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon PMs, May 22</NOTE>
</DOC>
