<FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     05-18 0691</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0720</SECOND>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Democratic-controlled Congress gave final
approval to legislation raising the minimum wage for the first time
in eight years, but President Bush said it was ``inevitable'' he
would kill the measure with the first veto of his administration.
   The vote Wednesday was 63-37 to approve the plan, which would
boost the minimum wage from $3.35 an hour to $4.55 by October 1991.
That vote left supporters shy of the 67 needed in the Senate to
override Bush's veto.
   Majority Democrats are short of a two-thirds override margin in
the House, which passed the bill earlier this month, but sponsors
have promised a veto override attempt nonetheless.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. trade deficit, benefiting from record
export sales, shrank dramatically to $8.86 billion in March, the
government said in a report that prompted some economists to
question their earlier assessment that the country's trade
improvement had stalled out.
   The Commerce Department said Wednesday the March deficit was
down 9.8 percent from February's imbalance of $9.82 billion, a
figure that was revised from an initial deficit of $10.5 billion.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Florida officials have accused the penny stock
brokerage Blinder, Robinson and Co. of a variety of securities law
violations and moved to kick the firm out of the state.
   Comptroller Gerald Lewis said Wednesday the state named 29
former and current employees in a civil action to revoke their
licenses, including company President Meyer Blinder and his son,
vice president Larry Blinder.
   Denver-based Blinder, which has offices in 37 states _ including
10 in Florida _ and the District of Columbia was ordered to
immediately stop violating Florida securities laws.
</TEXT>
