<FILEID>AP-NR-05-18-89 0246EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Maxwell-McGraw-Hill     05-18 0582</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Maxwell-McGraw-Hill,0608</SECOND>
<HEAD>McGraw-Hill Stock Slumps After Maxwell Agrees Not To Mount Takeover</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Speculators sold McGraw-Hill Inc. stock after
the company announced a standstill agreement barring British
publisher Robert Maxwell from attempting to take over the company
for 15 years.
   The pact with Maxwell Communications Corp. was part of a joint
educational publishing venture between Maxwell affiliate Macmillan
Inc. and McGraw-Hill announced Wednesday.
   McGraw-Hill fell $5.75 a share to $69 in composite New York
Stock Exchange trading Wednesday.
   ``The market is saying it is a less likely takeover candidate
because Mr. Maxwell has been an active buyer of media properties,''
said analyst Peter Appert of C.J. Lawrence, Morgan Grenfell Inc.
   But he added: ``Maxwell's one player in the universe. It seems
to me the stock is way overreacting.''
   Analysts said the selloff was led by speculators abandoning
McGraw-Hill because of the reduced likelihood that the company,
which has been considered a weak performer in recent years, would
be acquired.
   They speculated that Maxwell proposed the standstill to allay
fears he would go after new partner McGraw-Hill, considered a
takeover target for some time.
   Macmillan spokesman David Adler declined to say whether Maxwell
had made buyout overtures toward McGraw-Hill, the New York-based
publishing and information services company.
   Maxwell, one of the world's 10 biggest communications,
information and publishing groups, owns no stock in McGraw-Hill,
Adler said.
   ``Maxwell Communications offered to enter into the standstill
agreement and McGraw-Hill accepted,'' McGraw-Hill spokeswoman Betsy
Russo said. ``We have nothing more to say than that.''
   The joint venture in elementary, secondary and vocational
education publishing combines units of Macmillan and McGraw-Hill
that had $440 million in total sales last year.
   London-based Maxwell last year acquired New York-based Macmillan
for $2.5 billion after a bitter takeover battle.
   ``The combination of Macmillan's educational business with that
of McGraw-Hill is a dramatic illustration of the high quality of
the publishing businesses we acquired in Macmillan,'' Robert
Maxwell said in a statement.
   The publishing venture will create a new Chicago-based company,
Macmillan-McGraw-Hill School Publishing Co., equally owned by
McGraw-Hill and Macmillan.
   McGraw-Hill units that will enter the venture are its School
Division, Gregg Division, CTB-McGraw Hill and Educational
Resources. The units accounted for about 9 percent of McGraw-Hill's
total 1988 revenue, or about $165 million. Operating profits of the
divisions was $8.5 million.
   Macmillan units in the deal are its School Division, Glencoe
Division and Barnell Loft operations. McGraw-Hill will buy Maxwell
Communications' Science Research Associates and London House for
$190 million and place them in the new company.
   The Macmillan units last year had combined revenue of about $275
million, or about 20 percent of Macmillan's total revenue.
Operating profits totaled about $40 million.
   ``This restructuring of our elementary and high school units
into an independent entity fits nicely with our strategy to develop
core businesses with significant market share,'' McGraw-Hill
Chairman Joseph L. Dionne said.
   Analysts said the deal would catapult the new company to among
the top four elementary and high school publishers.
   ``McGraw-Hill has not been a power in the elementary and high
school side. ... They definitely take a step up in the ranks,''
Appert said. ``It's going to help McGraw-Hill's profit quite a
bit.''
   McGraw-Hill, which also owns Business Week magazine, four
television stations and the Standard &amp; Poor's credit rating
service, earned $185.5 million last year on revenue of $1.8
billion. Maxwell Communications reported $230.5 million in 1988
profit on sales of $1.9 billion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890518-0237 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-18-89 0202EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Avon-Amway Bjt   05-18 0561</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Avon-Amway, Bjt,0580</SECOND>
<HEAD>Avon Board Rejects Amway Takeover Bid</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Miffed at what it called an ``hysterical'' and
``irresponsible'' rejection of its $2.1 billion takeover bid, Amway
Corp. withdrew its offer to acquire rival Avon Products Inc.
   The move came late Wednesday, just hours after Avon's board
rejected Amway's $39-a-share offer saying that uniting the nation's
two biggest companies in person-to-person sales would cause a
culture clash with disastrous consequences.
   The board's rejection of Amway's bid had been expected, given
previous statements from Avon that the company was not for sale.
   Avon's stock had edged down 12{ cents a share to close at
$40.12{ in consolidated New York Stock Exchange trading. Amway,
which had sought a friendly deal and had indicated it would be
willing to increase its offer, withdrew after the market closed.
   In a letter to Amway, a privately held direct-selling concern
based in Ada, Mich., Avon Chairman James E. Preston said the board
reviewed the acquisition proposal thoroughly before voting
unanimously to turn it down.
   ``We are convinced that our shareholders' long-term interests
will best be served by Avon remaining independent,'' Preston said
in the letter released from the company's New York headquarters.
   Avon's shares are undervalued and don't reflect the company's
improved prospects, Preston said, noting ``we are confident that
the long-term value of the Avon common stock is significantly
higher than $39 per share.''
   Avon lost $404.5 million in 1988 on revenue of $3.06 billion.
The loss came as Avon continued the process of divesting its
operations in the health-care services field so it can focus its
efforts on enhancing its beauty and direct-selling businesses.
   Preston said Avon's management ``is turning the company around''
so ``from a shareholder perspective, now would be the worst time to
sell the company.''
   The lengthy letter sent on behalf of the Avon board contained a
litany of reasons why Avon objects to Amway's interest. One of the
key objections was that there would be dangerous friction in trying
to meld the two companies.
   ``Combining our cultures would be disastrous to our business,''
the letter said. ``It would create hostility within the sales force
and would destroy Avon's good name.''
   In response, Amway characterized Avon's rejection letter as
``hysterical, irresponsible and irrelevant'' as well as ``vicious
and irrational.'' It described Avon's charges as ``baseless,
reckless and defamatory.''
   Amway said it doesn't intend to pursue a bid as long as Avon's
board ``maintains its current hostile position that the company is
not for sale under any circumstances.''
   Analysts and investors believed Amway's offer was too low, and
some valued Avon as high as $45 a share. Amway may have
intentionally made a ``low-ball'' offer in the likelihood that no
other competitive bids would surface, they said.
   Avon said it conducted a survey this week in which almost half
of its top-selling sales representatives responded that they would
quit rather than be associated with Amway. Nearly 40 percent of the
representatives in the United States said they would probably
leave, also.
   Avon has about 425,000 sales representatives in the United
States and another 1 million agents marketing Avon products in more
than 80 foreign countries.
   Avon had planned to mail letters to shareholders today providing
details of its plans. Avon spokesman John Cox said shareholders
would be told the basis for the board's decision, not information
about anti-takeover tactics.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
