<FIRST>r f PM-IUDSuit     05-18 0357</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-IUD Suit,0370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Searle Wins IUD Suit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal jury has rejected a woman's claims that
G.D. Searle &amp; Co.'s Cu-7 birth control device caused her
infertility, marking the company's 15th victory of 19 cases that
have been decided in court.
   The jury in U.S. District Judge Rya Zobel's court concluded
Wednesday that the Cu-7 device was not responsible for any alleged
injury of the plaintiff, Cindy Nickerson. The jury also found in
favor of the other defendant, Ortho Pharmaceuticals, manufacturer
of the Lippes Loop intrauterine contraceptive.
   ``We are pleased that the Massachusetts jury was persuaded by
the weight of science, the long history of safety and
effectiveness, of the Cu-7 and the continuing endorsement of the
product by the medical community,'' said William I. Greener Jr.,
Searle spokesman.
   So far, 19 such cases have gone to a judge or jury, said Searle
spokeswoman Kay Bruno.
   ``We've won 15 of the 19. Of the four losses, two are completed
cases and two are on appeal,'' she said. ``Unfortunately, there are
still cases pending against the company.''
   Although most of the cases thus far have favored Searle, the
company was ordered last year to pay damages to a Minnesota woman
in the amount of $8.75 million, which was later reduced by a judge
to $8.15 million.
   Ms. Nickerson's attorney, Anil Madan, said an appeal is being
considered. She criticized defense attorneys' conduct.
   ``We felt that the defendants, particularly Searle, made the
plaintiff a victim and paraded her sexual and personal history
before the jury,'' Madan said.
   Searle maintains that its product is safe when used properly.
   ``The product is still approved by the FDA as safe and effective
when used by its label.'' Bruno said. ``While we have not been in
the IUD market for three years now, we have said that we would
vigorously defend this product.''
   Three years ago, Searle discontinued its IUD business in the
United States citing difficulty in getting product liability
insurance and the cost of defending against suits.
   Searle, a wholly owned subsidiary of the Monsanto Co., is a
research-based company that develops, manufactures and markets
prescription phamarceuticals.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
