<FIRST>r f PM-Eastern Bjt   05-18 0779</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eastern, Bjt,0800</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chances For Sale of Eastern Dimming, Some Say</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Lead prospects uncertain</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines' proposed plan to rebuild as a
smaller carrier and sell $1.8 billion in assets could gain critical
support at a meeting today of the committee representing its major
creditors.
   The creditor panel's financial advisers, investment firm
Goldman, Sachs &amp; Co. and accountants Ernst &amp; Whinney, have
concluded that Eastern's restructuring plan may be feasible and are
expected to present that view to the committee, sources close to
the situation said Wednesday.
   That would add to the building momentum in favor of the
strikebound carrier's proposed plan, as prospects for a sale of
Eastern as a whole appear to dim, some observers and sources said.
   Court officials have labeled as inadequate the buyout proposals
submitted so far by two investor groups; a federal bankruptcy judge
has approved the idea of selling the airline's prized Northeast
shuttle, and Eastern has moved further along with its own plan to
sell assets and reorganize as a smaller carrier.
   The judge on Wednesday gave Eastern permission to lease 14
Boeing 727-200s to Pan American World Airways for $57.9 million
over three years as part of its restructuring plan. Eastern had
signed a tentative agreement with Pan Am to lease the jets for
$96.6 million over five years. Eastern has announced similar
agreements with other carriers in recent weeks, but the Pan Am deal
was the first approved by the bankruptcy court.
   Some union representatives admitted privately that the recent
developments were a setback for the unions because of the
likelihood the airline would be broken up _ something the unions
have opposed strongly.
   ``They (Eastern) seem to sort of win by default,'' said one
union operative who asked not to be named.
   ``The longer it drags on, the less value Eastern brings to a
buyer,'' said Paul Karos, an airline analyst for First Boston Corp.
``Something has to happen very quickly.''
   Miami-based Eastern has been under Chapter 11 protection from
creditors since March 9, five days after the start of a paralyzing
strike by its Machinists union that was supported by pilots and
flight attendants. The bankruptcy court must approve any sale of
Eastern or any of its assets, including the shuttle service.
   David I. Shapiro, the court-appointed examiner for Eastern, said
at a bankruptcy hearing Tuesday there were no ``real live offers''
to buy the entire carrier and challenged suitors who have made
proposals to risk at least $100 million of their own cash for any
purchase.
   Two investor groups, one headed by Chicago commodities trader
Joseph Ritchie and the other headed by former Piedmont Airlines
chairman William Howard, have submitted formal bids. In response to
Shapiro's request, the Ritchie group said it planned to revise its
proposal with a new plan that would include ``substantial equity
capital.''
   Also on Tuesday, U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Burton R. Lifland said
Eastern had provided valid reasons for its plan to sell the New
York-Washington-Boston shuttle. Eastern already has an agreement to
sell the shuttle to developer Donald Trump for $365 million, but
Lifland gave the airline until Monday to consider a higher bid by
America West Airlines.
   Joel Zweibel, the attorney representing Eastern's major
creditors, said they supported a prompt sale of the shuttle.
   The growing likelihood of a shuttle sale, coupled with the
apparent lack of credible buyout offers for the whole airline,
bolster Eastern's proposed plan to cut its size and sell another
$1.4 billion or so in assets separately, some observers say.
   Eastern's unions tried to put a good face on the developments.
   Shapiro's statements on the inadequacy of the offers are ``a
blessing in disguise'' because they will draw out improved bids
from the suitors and speed up the process of reviving Eastern,
pilots union spokesman Dan Ashby said Wednesday in New York.
   However, some union sources suggested privately that a sale of
the shuttle, which long has been vigorously opposed by the unions,
could crush their morale and may even prompt Eastern pilots to
return to work.
   Eastern's parent Texas Air Corp. had no comment on the matter,
spokesman Art Kent said.
   Phoenix-based America West has offered to pay $415 million for
the shuttle and $336 million for 10 Boeing 757s in a total package
worth $751 million.
   Trump's $365 million agreement with Texas Air Chairman Frank
Lorenzo expires on May 27. Under their contract, the developer
would receive $8 million from Eastern if the shuttle deal collapses.
   America West has said it would not employ Eastern employees if
it purchased the shuttle, while Trump has recognized the Eastern
unions for his shuttle.
</TEXT>
