<FILEID>AP-NR-05-18-89 0753EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-ReservationsSystem     05-18 0581</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Reservations System,0598</SECOND>
<HEAD>DOT Raises Concerns About American, Delta CRS Merger</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN A. BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The proposed combination of the computer
reservations systems of two of the nation's major airlines is
troublesome, but could produce more competition if properly
structured, the Department of Transportation says.
   In a letter, and accompanying summary, to Attorney General
Richard Thornburgh, Transportation Secretary Samuel Skinner raises
concerns about the proposed merger of the CRS operations of
American Airlines and Delta Air Lines.
   But Skinner says assurances that the new partnership would be
operated separately and would not favor either carrier could remedy
his department's concerns about the deal.
   Both American and Delta said Wednesday they viewed the letter as
a favorable development.
   ``We have said from the beginning that we wanted other
partners,'' said Bill Berry, spokesman for Atlanta-based Delta.
``We are talking to several foreign and domestic carriers who want
to buy as little as 1 percent and as much at 10 percent.''
   ``It won't even be like a subsidiary,'' said John Hotard, a
spokesman for Fort Worth-based American. ``It will be keeping an
arm's length from each of the other owners,'' and make marketing
decisions on its own.
   ``The proposed transaction now before you has the potential to
adversely affect competition in the CRS industry and the airline
industry,'' Skinner said in his letter, dated Monday.
   ``The merger could combine the largest and smallest of the five
firms in the CRS industry, which are controlled by two of the
largest and most successful members of the airline industry.
   ``While we do not believe that competition in the CRS market is
threatened so seriously that the transaction should be challenged
on that basis, we do believe that the transaction as currently
structured poses a substantial likelihood of producing an adverse
effect on airline competition'' by being used as an unfair
marketing weapon for American and Delta, the nation's number one
and number three carriers respectively, Skinner said.
   ``Thus we believe the transaction should be challenged unless it
is modified to include at least one additional airline owner, and
to assure separate management and marketing'' of the surviving
system.
   In a summary of its findings, however, DOT says, ``With adequate
assurances that (the new company) will be controlled and operated
in a `carrier-neutral' manner ... the transaction could actually
benefit airline competition if it makes the largest U.S. CRS a
truly neutral distribution tool.''
   American and Delta announced the joint partnership in February.
Under the deal, Delta would pay American $650 million and they each
would own half of the resulting company.
   Initially, the airlines said they would sell up to half of their
shares in the partnership for $20 million for each percentage
point. Three months later, they cut the price to $15 million for
the first 20 percent to spur interest in gaining another partner.
   Under the still-unnamed partnership, American's SABRE system
would eventually absorb Delta's DATASII system, an acknowledged
weak point of the airline.
   Computer reservations systems are used by travel agents to book
airline tickets. SABRE has been the industry leader, but also has
been the target in the past of government complaints that it
unfairly favored American flights.
   American subsequently changed the program to answer those
complaints and now operates as a ``neutral, unbiased CRS that sells
a whole assortment of travel products,'' Hotard said.
   The Justice Department is expected to decide by early June
whether it will challenge the merger on antitrust grounds.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
