<FILEID>AP-NR-05-18-89 0836EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-PennyStocks     05-18 0570</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Penny Stocks,0589</SECOND>
<HEAD>Comptroller Moves to Kick Blinder, Robinson Out of Florida</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SANDRA WALEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Blinder, Robinson &amp; Co. Inc. has been accused by
Florida officials of scheming to defraud its customers, and the
comptroller moved to stop the company from doing any business in
the state.
   Florida Comptroller Gerald Lewis announced Wednesday that the
Denver-based company, with offices nationwide, was ordered to
immediately stop its alleged violations of Florida securities laws.
   Blinder, Robinson could lose its Florida license and faces more
than $5 million in fines as a result of the state's 2{-year
investigation into alleged market manipulation of penny stocks.
   Lewis charged that the firm, licensed in Florida since 1973,
made millions of dollars in illegal profits by inflating the
purchase price of certain stocks beyond the legal limit, conducting
excessive stock trades just to earn commissions and buying and
selling stock without clients' permission.
   Penny stocks are low-priced, thinly traded securities that
generally cost less than $5 per share and are traded over the
counter.
   In a statement issued Wednesday, company officials said Blinder,
Robinson was in full compliance with Florida law and would
vigorously defend itself against the charges.
   Rick Rouse, director of compliance for Blinder, Robinson, said
the Florida Department of Banking and Finance had acted
irresponsibly in its action.
   ``Whenever there have been problems, we have addressed them. I
cannot rationalize how the department could neglect to ask for our
cooperation before instituting such an action,'' he said. ``We
intend ... to pursue all appropriate recourse.''
   The Florida action cited numerous infractions of state
securities laws, including sale of unregistered securities,
unreasonable markups, failure to maintain proper records,
unauthorized trading and scheming to defraud.
   It also named 29 former and current employees, including the
company's president, Meyer Blinder, and vice president Larry
Blinder, his son.
   The case has been turned over to the statewide prosecutor's
office for possible criminal prosecution, Lewis said.
   Blinder, Robinson has 21 days to ask for a hearing to stop its
Florida license from being revoked, which would prohibit the
company from conducting any securities business in Florida. The
firm has 10 branch offices and 423 agents in Florida.
   ``The history of their company is one of litigation,'' Lewis
told a news conference in Miami. ``We're ready for battle.''
   The firm has been under investigation in other states and by
federal authorities. State securities officials say thousands of
investors in Florida may have been victims of Blinder, Robinson's
practices.
   An example of the firm's alleged market manipulation involved
the sale of shares of Onnix Financial Group Inc., Lewis said. In
addition to selling the original shares at up to a 112 percent
markup, Blinder, Robinson allegedly sold nearly 42,000 nonexistent
shares, he said.
   The company's troubles with the Securities and Exchange
Commission date to 1980, and include a massive probe initiated by
the SEC in April 1987 into allegations that it defrauded customers.
   The SEC has been investigating allegations stretching back to
August 1983 that Blinder, Robinson violated federal law by
marketing nine distributions of unregistered securities, by falsely
representing the business prospects of the companies involved, and
by excessively marking up the prices of the securities.
   The SEC had two other actions pending against the company for
alleged bookkeeping violations.
   Company attorneys have contended that the government had a
vendetta against the firm. Blinder said negative publicity
devastated business in 1988.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
