<HEAD>Upjohn Begins New Rogaine Ads</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KALAMAZOO, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Men too embarrassed to discuss hair loss
in person will be able to gain information by telephone through a
toll-free service offered by Upjohn Co., maker of the baldness drug
Rogaine.
   Upjohn will run a series of television and print advertisements
beginning this week urging men concerned about hair loss to see
their physicians.
   A call to the toll-free telephone number will give a consumer
more information about male pattern baldness, treatment options and
physicians in the caller's area.
   The campaign replaces advertising showing a man walking on a
beach talking about male pattern baldness. The current ad and the
new one, with a man looking into a mirror, are prohibited by law
from mentioning the name of the prescription drug.
   Upjohn, which received federal approval to market Rogaine in
August 1988, has refused to talk about sales of the drug.
   Ronald Nordmann, an analyst with PaineWebber Inc., estimated
that domestic sales of the drug accounted for about $11 million of
the $755 million the company reported in revenues for the first
three months of this year.
