<FILEID>AP-NR-05-18-89 0911EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-GasolinePrices     05-18 0459</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Gasoline Prices,0475</SECOND>
<HEAD>State To Investigate Price Increases</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state Office of Energy Resources will
investigate why wholesale gasoline prices rose 22 cents a gallon
from March 10 to April 21.
   Energy Secretary Sharon Pollard said among the issues to be
examined is whether the oil industry is exploiting the March 24
Exxon Valdez oil spill in Alaska.
   ``The goal of this investigation will be to get to the bottom of
this issue and determine whether the oil companies are just lining
their pockets or whether these increased prices are justified,''
Pollard said.
   ``Consumers are outraged, and we intend to give them some
answers,'' she said.
   Prices at the pump have increased 9 to 15 cents per gallon,
indicating some of the wholesale price increases have been absorbed
by the companies and not passed on to consumers.
   Oil company executives and some independent energy analysts said
the Valdez spill had little or nothing to do with the price
increase.
   ``I don't think you'll find that more than 5 percent of the
increase was related to the Valdez accident,'' Henry Lee, director
of Harvard's Energy and Environmental Policy Center and former head
of the state Energy Office, told The Boston Globe.
   ``Companies seized the opportunity to raise prices faster and
higher than they would have, and it made a huge financial impact,''
said Edwin Rothschild, a consumer activist who organized a
nationwide boycott of Exxon.
   ``They probably would have tried to pass those increases through
gradually, but this was sudden and extreme.''
   Lee said one factor in increased prices was the loss of 420,000
barrels of oil a day because an oil platform in the North Sea
broke. ``That has panicked all the gasoline refiners in Europe,''
from which Northeast states get a lot of their fuel, he said.
   Frank Tivnan, director of the Massachusetts Petroleum Council,
which represents gasoline refiners and sellers, said investigations
in Massachusetts and New York should prove that policies of the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries, air pollution
regulations, increased demand, and expensive changes at European
refineries led to the price increases.
   He said the OPEC price increase accounts for 8 to 9 percent of
the retail price increase.
   The demand by Northeast states for gasoline that is slower to
evaporate, and so will cut summer emissions of dangerous organic
compounds, makes fuel ``more difficult to get and more expensive,''
Tivnan said.
   He said oil executives and a study by the U.S. Environmental
Protection Agency said prices would rise because of the new
gasoline.
   ``If the Valdez had any effect on oil prices, it was simply a
psychological effect on the West Coast for a few days or week,''
Tivnan said. ``After a week or so, tanker traffic returned to
normal.''
</TEXT>
