<FIRST>u f PM-Blueberries 1stLd-Writethru   05-18 0517</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Blueberries, 1st Ld - Writethru,0530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Germans Provide Market for Georgia Berries</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf pvs, Last year... to CORRECT to 105,000 pounds
sted 105 pounds. Picks up 3rd graf, This year...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELLIOTT MINOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALMA, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three days after blueberries are plucked from
the bushes in Bacon County, clerks place them on shelves in West
German supermarkets so winter-weary shoppers can satisfy their
craving for fresh fruit.
   Last year south Georgia growers exported 105,000 pounds of
rabbiteyes _ native blueberries bred from wild plants. The 1988
crop totaled 5.2 million pounds and was valued at about $4 million.
   This year growers are shipping Southern highbush varieties such
as Georgia Gems, an early ripening berry that goes to market about
two weeks ahead of rabbiteyes when prices are highest. Freezing
temperatures last winter has cut this year's crop roughly in half,
but export efforts continue.
   A few hours after harvesting, the berries are packed in plastic
baskets and trucked to Jacksonville, Fla., for a flight to
Frankfurt.
   ``There's a demand for fresh blueberries in that part of the
world. We're trying to cash in on it,'' said Danny Stanaland, the
county extension agent in Alma, an agricultural community of about
5,000 that bills itself as the ``Blueberry Capital of Georgia.''
   Georgia's blueberry industry has been growing since the early
1970s when farmers began experimenting with the fruit as an
alternative crop.
   While tobacco is still the top cash crop in the area, Stanaland
said blueberries have gained in importance. ``Corn and soybeans
wouldn't pay the bills, but fortunately we have blueberries to pick
up the slack,'' he said.
   Currently about 3,000 acres are devoted to blueberries.
   Trade experts point to blueberry exports as an example of new
business opportunities for south Georgia, a rural region plagued by
poverty and high infant mortality. The area has been described as
``the other Georgia'' because it has lagged behind Atlanta in
sophistication and economic growth.
   ``The world is growing smaller, and even an area like south
Georgia can be involved in international trade if you have the
right product,'' said horticulturist Gerard Krewer, a fruit
specialist with the Georgia Extension Service.
   Athens, Ga., economist Keith Scearce said forestry and farming
can provide many export opportunities, but businesses will have to
make a special effort to develop new markets.
   ``You've got to get people thinking bigger than they have in the
past,'' said Scearce.
   Shipping blueberries to Germany would have seemed like an
impossible task a decade ago, but now it's viewed as a growing
opportunity for farmers.
   Stanaland said local officials are seeking federal funds to
improve Alma's airport, and growers are considering the possibility
of using the community's 5,000-foot runway to ship their berries
directly to Germany.
   ``We would like to say that one day we can pick our berries and
take them to our local airport,'' he said. ``That way we might be
able to pick them today and sell them tomorrow, wherever there is a
demand.
   ``We know we have something good,'' he said. ``We hope the world
likes it.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
