<FIRST>r f BC-Britain-RanksHovis     05-18 0359</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Britain-Ranks Hovis,0369</SECOND>
<HEAD>Group Linked with Rothschild and Goldmsith Agree to Buy Stake</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sunningdale Holdings Ltd., a group linked with
British investors Jacob Rothschild and James Goldsmith, said
Thursday it has agreed to buy a 29.9 percent stake in Britain's
Ranks Hovis McDougall PLC currently held by Goodman Fielder Wattie
Ltd. of Australia.
   Sunningdale said it agreed to buy the stake at 400 pence, or
$6.48, a share, contingent on the failure of a current takeover bid
by Ranks Hovis for Goodman Fielder. If the bid succeeds,
Sunningdale will be entitled to a payment of 50 pence, 81 cents, a
share.
   Last month, Ranks Hovis, a baking and foods concern, offered the
equivalent of about $2.1 billion for Goodman Fielder, the biggest
food processor in Australia and New Zealand.
   The bid represented a turnaround in a longstanding battle which
last year saw the Australasian group's $2.8 billion takeover bid
for Ranks Hovis thwarted by a British government investigation into
its impact on competition in the foods sector.
   The entry of Sunningdale to the fray represents the first joint
investment venture by Goldsmith and Rothschild since the pair
announced plans to create Anglo Leasing PLC in March. Anglo Leasing
is to be owned equally by Goldsmith and Rothschild companies, which
also have holdings in Sunningdale.
   Rothschild and Goldsmith have said the aim of their new company
would be to acquire one or more large publicly quoted British
companies which could benefit from restructuring.
   Goodman Fielder, which has been seeking a buyer for its 29.9
percent stake in Ranks Hovis since its bid for the British foods
group lapsed last August, stands to make a windfall gain on the
sale.
   In its recent talks with Ranks Hovis, Goodman Fielder has
indicated it might be willing to proceed with a merger, but only on
its own terms. It has rejected the initial Goodman Fielder offer,
saying it doesn't adequately reflect the value of the company.
   Ranks Hovis, which currently holds a 14.9 percent stake in
Goodman Fielder, said the sale breached one of the conditions of
the bid, adding that it was still considering what actions to
pursue.
</TEXT>
