<TEXT>
   The stock market turned downward today following
a government report on inflation that was slightly worse than
expected.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials slipped 4.95 to 2,457.48
in the first half hour of trading.
   Losers outnumbered gainers by about 5 to 3 in nationwide trading
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 331 up, 551 down and
498 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 24 million shares as of 10 a.m.
on Wall Street.
   The Labor Department reported that the consumer price index rose
0.7 percent in April, bringing the increase in the index so far in
1989 to an annual rate of 6.6 percent.
   The monthly number came in near the high end of advance
estimates on Wall Street, and apparently disappointed some traders
who had been hoping for a pleasant surprise in the data.
   Still, analysts noted that much of the increase came, as
expected, from a jump in energy prices that is not expected to be
repeated in coming months.
   That left the door open for stock-market bulls who contend that
the Federal Reserve has a good chance of succeeding in its effort
to restrain inflation without pushing the economy into a recession.
   Losers among the blue chips included Ford Motor, down { at 49\;
American Telephone &amp; Telegraph, down [ at 34{; Eastman Kodak, down
[ at 43], and International Business Machines, down } at 110}.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks
dropped .37 to 176.61. At the American Stock Exchange, the market
value index was down .28 at 351.56.
   On Wednesday the Dow Jones industrial average rose 8.98 to
2,462.43.
   Advancing issues outnumbered declines by more than 9 to 5 on the
NYSE, with 958 up, 505 down and 508 unchanged.
   Big Board volume totaled 191.21 million shares, against 173.10
million in the previous session.
