<FIRST>u f PM-Dollar-Gold 1stLd-Writethru   05-18 0377</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold, 1st Ld-Writethru,0391</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Surges on Inflation Report</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates with dollar rising against some currencies after central
bank intervention.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A surge in U.S. consumer prices sent the dollar
sharply higher in Europe today despite a coordinated move by
central banks to reverse the currency's advance.
   Gold was slightly higher.
   The U.S. Labor Department said an all-time record increase in
gasoline prices fueled a large, 0.7 percent jump in consumer
inflation in April. The spurt in the Consumer Price Index followed
advances of 0.5 percent in March and 0.4 percent in February.
   The dollar jumped after the announcement as traders anticipated
the U.S. Federal Reserve would further tighten credit in an attempt
to choke off inflation.
   The U.S. currency rose against the West German mark and the
Swiss and French francs after the banks' concerted intervention. It
fell against the Japanese yen and the British pound.
   The central banks of France, Italy, Austria and Switzerland
confirmed that they sold dollars, primarily against West German
marks, and some confirmed it was a concerted effort aimed at
pushing the dollar lower.
   The Bank of England also participated, dealers said. Other
participants reportedly included the Federal Reserve and the West
German Bundesbank.
   In London, the British pound cost $1.6170 at midmorning,
compared with $1.6140 late Wednesday.
   Other dollar rates at midafternoon, compared with late
Wednesday's prices, included: 1.9690 West German marks, up from
1.9675; 1.7600 Swiss francs, up from 1.7580; 6.6675 French francs,
up from 6.6607; 2.2183 Dutch guilders, up from 2.2150; 1,435.50
Italian lire, up from 1,433.00; and 1.1930 Canadian dollars, up
from 1.1925.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends as Europe's business day begins,
the dollar rose for the sixth consecutive trading day, closing at
an 18-month high of 138.88 yen. Later, in London, it was quoted at
138.93.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $371.25 a troy ounce,
compared with late Wednesday's $370.75. At midmorning, the city's
five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $371.00.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $371.00, up from $370.25 late
Wednesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell $3.01 to close at a bid $371.73.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $5.43 a troy
ounce, down from Wednesday's $5.46.

</TEXT>
