<FILEID>AP-NR-05-18-89 1143EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a f BC-CreditWatching Adv22   05-18 0744</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Credit Watching, Adv 22,0767</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv22</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Monday, May 22 and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Unraveling The Mystery Of Credit Ratings</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Credit Watching-Law</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When Roseanne Barr sizes up a stack of bills
swamping her television-show husband she tells him: ``Pay the ones
marked `final notice' and throw the rest out.''
   The advice from the ABC comedy star on a recent episode was
meant as a joke, but many real-life bill payers sometimes do just
that, unaware they could possibly create a black-mark on their
credit rating, that mysterious dossier used by everyone from banks
to employers to decide whether you're responsible.
   While most people know a file on them exists somewhere they're
not sure exactly who keeps it, what's in it or how to track it down.
   ``It's a real web,'' said Robert Morton, head of the United
Consumer Credit Alliance, a Miami-based consulting group. ``A lot
of people are confused.''
   Credit files exist on nearly all adult Americans and are kept
primarily by four large private credit bureaus with offices
nationwide. These bureaus get their information from lenders, and,
in turn, sell it to creditors evaluating consumer-loan applications.
   Each file contains three types of information: personal data,
such as a social security number and address; record of payment;
and legal records, such as court judgments involvings debts or
insolvency.
   ``Your credit file will reveal whether you have paid your bills
on time ... if collection agencies were hired to dun you, or if
you've gone through bankruptcy,'' Bankcard Holders of America, a
consumer group based in Herndon, Va., states in a pamphlet it
publishes on understanding credit bureaus.
   What the credit file usually won't include is salary
information, late payments within a 60-day grace period, or records
on utility bills, said Mike Van Buskirk, a vice president for TRW
Information Systems Group, which runs the nation's largest credit
bureau.
   ``It's a little like a library, only it has the unusual problem
of not having direct ability to validate the information,'' Van
Buskirk said. ``If there's an error in the file most people won't
find out about it until they've suffered a damage or
embarrassment.''
   Consumer fear of reputation-tainting information in a credit
file, especially at crucial times such as when applying for a
mortgage, has helped TRW sell its ``Credentials'' service to nearly
750,000 subscribers across the country.
   Lately, the company has been advertising heavily, with ``Mission
Impossible'' star Peter Graves as spokesman in TV ads, in large
markets such as New York.
   For a $35 annual fee Credentials offers consumers unlimited
access to their files, notification whenever someone checks on
them, the release of credit data to authorized lenders and a
credit-card registration service to protect against theft or loss.
In the process, TRW also collects extra financial information that
may not included in the files it already has.
   While some people describe the service as a convenience, others
call it a slick gimmick, since all consumers are entitled under law
to a copy of their credit file from a bureau for free or a nominal
fee.
   Consumers also are entitled to receive from any credit bureau
the identities of those who have sought their file, although in
most cases they'll already know an inquiry is imminent since
federal law strictly limits access to credit files to anyone other
than lenders to whom you've applied for credit.
   ``If you're a busy executive and you're buying a home, a boat, a
car and applying for a person loan all in one year, Credentials
would be a good deal,'' said Elgie Holstein, executive director of
Bankcard Holders of America. ``(But) it's unlikely most consumers
would have the need to apply for major credit loans enough times in
the course of the year to make this worthwhile.''
   Morton agreed, ``It's a service that's little, if any, value for
the consumer but a high value for TRW. Consumers are paying to give
TRW more information.''
   Morton recommends that average consumers check their credit
report for accuracy at least once a year.
   To do that consumers must write to a major credit bureau in
their area, which may be appear under ``credit bureaus or
credit-reporting agencies'' in the telephone directory. Besides TRW
the big bureaus are Trans Union Credit Information, CSC Credit
Services Inc. and Credit Bureau Inc. CSC and CBI recently agreed to
merge their data services, although they operate separately.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Adv Monday May 22
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890518-0257 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-18-89 1144EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a f BC-CreditWatching-Law Adv22   05-18 0242</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Credit Watching-Law, Adv 22,0251</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv22</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Monday, May 22 and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Fair Credit Reporting Act Spells Out Rights</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Credit Watching</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The Fair Credit Reporting Act, enacted in 1971, gives Americans
the right to know what's in their credit file and to challenge
whatever information they believe to be inaccurate.
   If you're denied credit, you're entitled to know what's in your
file within 30 days of receiving a rejection letter. That notice
will contain the name and location of the credit-reporting bureau
contacted in evaluating your file.
   At any other time, you can write to or visit the credit bureau
to inspect your file for a nominal fee, usually between $5 and $10.
The FCRA requires the bureau to help you if there's something in
your file you don't understand.
   The FCRA also allows access to your credit file by those
authorized in writing, such as lenders to whom you are applying for
credit, potential employers or insurers. Every time someone
requests a copy of your report, it's noted as an ``inquiry'' on
your credit file.
   You can dispute information in your file by providing evidence
to prove an error or by insisting on an investigation.
   You can also submit statements to your file explaining why
negative credit remarks were accumulated. Negative information can
remain on your report for up to seven years, while bankruptcies are
reported for 10 years.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Monday May 22</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
