<FILEID>AP-NR-05-18-89 1154EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   05-18 0328</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0341</SECOND>
<HEAD>Corn and Soybean Prices Rise on Forecasts of More Rain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures opened mostly higher
today on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   Corn and soybean prices rose in the wake of the six- to 10-day
forecast released Wednesday by the National Weather Service. It
calls for below-normal rain and above-normal temperatures in much
of the Corn Belt.
   Prices also were helped by the belief that corn and soybeans
have been oversold in recent sessions.
   There are too many uncertainties in the weather this time of
year, says Jon Horton, an analyst with Research Department Inc. in
Chicago.
   ``Everyone remembers the drought last year,'' he said. ``Without
perfect growing conditions, prices at these levels aren't
justified.''
   Wheat prices dropped as traders noted there hadn't been much
export of the grain recently. However, there has been good
commerical buying, spurred by the Agriculture Department's
announcement yesterday that the export bonus program would continue
as long as other nations subsidize their grain sales.
   In early trading, wheat was { cent lower to 1{ cents higher with
the contract for delivery in May at $4.09 a bushel; corn was a {
cent to 1{ cents higher with May at $2.78 a bushel; oats were
unchanged to { cent higher with May at $1.83{ a bushel; soybeans
were 1 cent to 3 cents higher with May at $7.31 a bushel.
   Livestock futures were mixed and meat prices lower in early
trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .45 cent lower to .12 cent higher with June at
71.32 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .18 cent to .53 cent higher
with May at 77.45 cents a pound; hogs were .02 cent to .25 cent
lower with June at 48.17 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were
.32 cent lower to .13 cent higher with May at 35.80 cents a pound.
   Livestock futures settled lower Wednesday, while pork prices
were higher.
</TEXT>
