<FIRST>u f PM-Ruder 1stLd-Writethru   05-18 0597</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ruder, 1st Ld-Writethru,0615</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ruder Quitting as SEC Chairman</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Combines pvs files; SUBS 8th graf pvs, Under Ruder's, to CLARIFY
that Wall Street investigation begun by Shad; ADDS 7 grafs background;
ADDS byline</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NANCY BENAC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   David S. Ruder is resigning as chairman of the
Securities and Exchange Commission to return to the faculty of the
Northwestern University School of Law, the agency announced today.
   In a letter to President Bush, Ruder said he plans to return to
Northwestern at the end of August. The date of his resignation will
depend on the timing of the selection of a successor.
   Ruder assured the president that he will continue to perform his
duties actively until his return to Northwestern and will work with
the administration to secure a smooth transition.
   Ruder, a nominee of former President Reagan, was appointed to
the commission in August 1987 for a five-year term.
   There had been widespread speculation that Ruder would be
replaced by the Bush administration and a search already was under
way for a successor.
   Among the names that have been mentioned as possible successors
to Ruder are John M. Richman, chairman of Kraft Inc. of Chicago;
John J. Creedon, president of Metropolitan Life Insurance Co.;
Harvey L. Pitt, of Fried Frank Harris Shriver &amp; Jacobsen in
Washington; Thomas A. Russo, former director of the trading and
markets division at the Commodity Futures Trading Comission; and
SEC Commissioner Edward H. Fleischman.
   Other changes also are considered likely in the make-up of the
five-member commission.
   Under Ruder's command, the SEC conducted a massive investigtion
into insider trading on Wall Street. The investigation, which was
launched under Ruder's predecessor John Shad, resulted in charges
against a string of financiers including speculator Ivan Boesky,
junk bond wizard Michael Milken and Milken's firm, Drexel Burnham
Lambert Inc.
   In his letter to Bush, dated Wednesday, Ruder said he thought it
was crucial that the commission have ``vigorous and strong
leadership.''
   ``The chairman of the SEC should have the capacity to manage the
commission well, to deal effectively with Congress, the
administration, other administrative agencies, and the securities
industry and to understand the complicated statutes administered by
the commission,'' he wrote.
   Ruder said he planned to resume teaching law in the 1989-90
academic year.
   It was the second big resignation announcement at the SEC within
a week. SEC Enforcement Director Gary G. Lynch last week announced
he would resign in mid-July to seek other job opportunities.
   Lynch, who had led the insider trading probe, said his decision
to leave was influenced in part by the fact that his cases had been
concluded or had reached a point where he could leave without
jeopardizing them.
   Ruder, 60, proved himself a skilled administrator from 1977 to
1985 as dean of Northwestern's law school, where he helped organize
two annual institutes for corporate and securities lawyers.
   Ruder, described by associates as a moderately liberal
Republican, had never held a previous government position, but had
taught courses in SEC enforcement, insider trading and tender
offers, and had written more than 40 articles on corporate
securities matters.
   He also practiced law for four years at Quarles &amp; Brady and five
years at Schiff, Hardin &amp; Waite, a prestigious Chicago firm with a
Washington branch.
   Born in Wausau, Wis., Ruder graduated with honors from Williams
College in Williamstown, Mass., in 1951, and received his law
degree with honors from the University of Wisconsin in 1957.
   He was an associate at Quarles &amp; Brady from 1957 to 1961 before
accepting a faculty position at Northwestern.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
