<FIRST>u f AM-Japan-USTrade     05-18 0585</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-US Trade,0603</SECOND>
<HEAD>Official Says U.S. Trade Retaliation Could Cause Strong Reaction
In Japan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID THURBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan may react strongly if the U.S. government
lists it among countries deemed to seriously violate free trade
principles, a Foreign Ministry official said Thursday.
   Under U.S. trade law, the Bush administration must decide by May
30 which countries maintain high trade barriers to U.S. products.
Japan topped a preliminary list, released last month by U.S. Trade
Representative Carla Hills, of 34 countries deemed to have such
barriers.
   ``This is a matter that has already created quite a reaction in
this country,'' Foreign Ministry spokesman Taizo Watanabe told a
regular press briefing.
   If Japan is listed as a serious free trade violator, he said,
``The reaction could be rather emotional.''
   The New York Times reported from Washington earlier this week
that the American Embassy in Tokyo had recommended that the U.S.
government use restraint in pressuring Japan to eliminate trade
barriers.
   It quoted secret embassy cables as warning there might be ``an
emotional outburst in Japan'' if the country is included in the
list of most serious free trade violators.
   Many Japanese feel their country has done a great deal in recent
years to open its markets to foreign products and that the United
States has not tried hard enough to sell high-quality products in
Japan or to reduce its massive government budget deficit.
   Some Japanese officials also were embittered by the U.S.
handling of a recent agreement to jointly produce Japan's next jet
fighter. U.S. congressmen demanded a renegotiation of the pact and
contended Japan was using it to acquire U.S. technology, even
though Japan had hoped to develop the plane alone.
   The Foreign Ministry spokesman said Japan might retaliate if the
United States violated international trade regulations in
attempting to reduce its trade imbalance with Japan.
   ``If there is any action taken on the part of the United States
in violation of the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade, we have
to think of what we should do'' in response, Watanabe said.
   According to figures released Wednesday by the U.S. Commerce
Department, Japan accounted for 67 percent of the U.S. trade
deficit in March, up from 53 percent in February. Many observers
say Japan is likely to be included in the ``hit list'' of serious
free-trade violators because of its large portion of the trade
deficit.
   Other Asian nations, including South Korea and Taiwan, were
included in the preliminary listing of alleged unfair traders and
have been lobbying in Washington to avoid being included in the
upcoming list. Workers and farmers in South Korea have demonstrated
against the U.S. trade pressure.
   Under U.S. trade law, nations on the final list will be targeted
for intensive negotiations aimed at removal of alleged trade
barriers. If the barriers continue, the law provides for
retaliation, including duties of up to 100 percent on imports from
those nations.
   Watanabe said all of the charges against Japan in the Trade
Representative's report were ``based on erroneous understandings or
simply not based on facts.''
   He said the United States would realize ``there is no foundation
for putting those items as candidates on the list'' if it
investigates the charges further.
   U.S. officials acknowledge that Japan has one of the lowest
average tariff rates in the world, but say cultural and other
factors make it difficult to sell here.
   Last year, the United States had a $52 billion trade deficit
with Japan, according to U.S. figures.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
