<FIRST>u f PM-Chrysler-Thrifty     05-18 0410</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Chrysler-Thrifty,0427</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chrysler to Acquire Thrifty Rent-A-Car</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JACK SCHREIBMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chrysler Corp. will acquire Thrifty
Rent-A-Car System Inc. for $263 million under an agreement
announced today by Chrysler Chairman Lee Iacocca.
   Iacocca told stockholders at the nation's No. 3 automaker's
annual meeting here Chrysler would pay $27.75 a share in a tender
offer for the Tulsa-based rental company.
   With its planned purchase, Chrysler was joining other automakers
_ including General Motors Corp. and Ford Motor Co. _ that have
acquired ownership of or stakes in car rental firms.
   ``Thrifty is a solid player in the car rental business and in
our dealing with Thrifty in the past six years we have been
impressed with the strength of the company and its management,''
Iacocca said.
   ``That played a key role in our decision to take this step in
what is a natural alliance cementing a good relationship.'' he said.
   Thrifty, with more than 650 locations worldwide and an average
fleet size of more than 33,000 vehicles, is the fifth-largest auto
rental company in North America.
   Thrifty's revenue for the fiscal year ending June 30, 1988, was
$79.3 million. The company earned $9.1 million.
   ``We are delighted by the prospect of joining forces with
Chrysler,'' said Thrifty Chairman William E. Lobeck Jr. ``Our board
of directors recommends unanimously that stockholders tender their
shares.
   ``With Chrysler's resources behind us in the future, we can
expect additional growth for the company.''
   Iacocca said Thrifty's management would remain in place and
continue operations from Tulsa.
   The tender offer will be subject to various government
approvals. The transaction will be managed by Merrill Lynch Capital
Markets.
   Ford, the nation's No. 2 automaker, holds 55 percent of the
stock of Hertz Corp., the nation's largest automobile renter. In a
deal announced earlier this month with Volvo North American Corp.,
Volvo acquired a portion of Ford's equity which would reduce Ford's
ownership to 49 percent of the Hertz stock.
   Last October, Ford agreed to provide $324 million in financing
for the acquisition of Budget Rent a Car Corp. by Beech Holdings
Corp. That deal went through in March.
   Ford's equity in that deal involved nonvoting preferred shares.
   GM acquired a minority interest last October in National Car
Rental. Between the mid-1920s and 1953, GM held an interest in a
Hertz predecessor company. GM, larger than Ford or Chrysler, has
declined to reveal the amount of that interest or its cost.
</TEXT>
