<FILEID>AP-NR-05-18-89 0630EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a f AM-BusinessMirror Adv19   05-18 0600</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Business Mirror, Adv 19,0618</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv19</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release AMs Friday, May 19</HEAD>
<HEAD>The Housing Barometer and Recession</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When housing starts begin to fall recession
fears rise.
   The relationship might be less now than it used to be, but a
decline in housing has preceded and accompanied most recessions in
recent years. And that makes housing a very sensitive economic
barometer.
   There are good reasons for following that barometer because, as
housing people point out, the building of just one single-family
house generates 1.8 worker-years of employment in construction or
construction-related industries.
   Understandably, houses are built by crews rather than 1.8
workers, but it averages out to that. Stated a bit differently, one
house provides 1.8 jobs of 40 hours a week for one full year and
two-thirds of another year.
   The National Association of Home Builders, which makes that
estimate from government figures, strives to show that housing is
good not only for them but good for the country, not only good for
builders but for other trades, too.
   Working from official government figures, the NAHB estimates
that 1,000 single-family homes generate $39.3 million in wages and
$16.1 million in combined federal, state and local taxes.
   Those amounts are just for single-family houses. Add in
multi-family housing and the impact of 1,000 units comes to 882
worker-years, $19 million in wages and $7.8 million in combined
federal, state and local revenues.
   When you consider that there are more than a million housing
starts each year _ more than 2 million in 1978 and probably 1.4
million this year _ the impact grows to enormous proportions.
   From 1983 through 1987, home builders say they built 8.6 million
units, creating 2.5 million full-time jobs and generating $55
billion in wages each year and a five-year total of $113 billion in
tax revenues.
   The impact even goes further. Who needs to be reminded that when
a house is purchased a series of big-ticket items are sure to
follow, including furniture, appliances, fuel contracts, lawn
mowers and more?
   No wonder that housing construction is an economic barometer; no
wonder that when the barometer falls it sends a warning about the
economy's direction as surely as its meteorological counterpart
signals inclement weather.
   Housing construction has fallen for three straight months,
enough to spur members of the NAHB to pay a visit this week to Alan
Greenspan, chairman of the Federal Reserve Board. Their message:
Ease up.
   What builders fear, and many professional economists too, is
that any further increase in interest rates could pitch the economy
into a recession before the year is out. Heed our barometer, they
said.
   Conceivably, Greenspan already had taken notice. After about 14
months of fighting inflation via higher interest rates, the Fed
seems to have let up, if only for an assessment. In fact, home
mortgage rates have been falling.
   A decline in mortgage rates, coming as it does at the height of
the buying season, could pump some energy into the industry,
especially into the single-family home market. That market already
has shown renewed signs of life.
   It is the multimarket category of housing that shows the
greatest weakness, and that weakness is generally attributed to the
elimination or reduction of tax incentives, such as accelerated
depreciation.
   Recession? The housing barometer hasn't yet made that
declaration.
   What is has indicated is that some stormy weather lurks not far
away, and that we should be mindful lest it come our way. Another
monthly decline in housing, the barometer says, and it might.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv AMs Friday, May 19</NOTE>
</DOC>
