0400</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Exxon Meeting-Demonstrations, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0410</SECOND>
<HEAD>Demonstrators Gather Peacefully At Exxon Corp. Meeting</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 5th graf to delete reference to Nader, who was not able
to attend.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Exxon Meeting Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HENRY STERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARSIPPANY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Demonstrators assembled peacefully today
at Exxon Corp.'s annual shareholders meeting, carrying protest
signs and accusing the company of lying about its disastrous
Alaskan oil spill.
   More than three dozen police officers watched as about 250
demonstrators lined the entranceway to the Aspen Manor Hotel in
this suburban community 35 miles west of Exxon's corporate
headquarters in New York City.
   Speaker Barry Commoner, a former presidential candidate and
long-time ecologist, said the spill in Alaska's Prince William
Sound points out the United States' overreliance on fossil fuels.
   ``We are here to pass judgment on a crime against nature and the
American people,'' Commoner told the crowd. ``That is the only
adequate description for what Exxon has done in Alaska.''
   Consumer activists and leaders of national and state
environmental groups also planned to address the crowd, which
assembled peacefully outside the hotel and displayed signs that
read ``Overthrow Exxon'' and ``Clean up your entire mess'' as
stockholders arrived.
   Isabel Byrd of Trenton was dressed in an overstuffed tuxedo,
wore a pig's nose and walked on stilts. She identified herself as a
``pig from Exxon,'' and said her outfit represented the company's
corporate mentality.
   ``We just came to say we don't have to care, because we're
Exxon,'' said Ms. Byrd. ``We're greedy and we're pigs.''
   Steve Kosnac of Somerville said he had worked on laying Alaska
pipeline during the 1970s. He accused Exxon of deliberately
spilling the oil that poured from the grounded tanker Exxon Valdez
on March 24 in Alaska's Prince William Sound, saying that spoiling
the area's coastline would render it useless for anything but oil
exploration.
   ``Oil companies are oil companies,'' Kosnac said. ``They're big
money and they'd walk through your property and just fight you in
court at a later date.''
   Weldon Monsport of Boonton carried a sign that said, ``Exxon PR
Is More Viscous Goo On The Truth.'' He said he blamed Exxon, the
people of Alaska who ``bought the safety of oil exploration hook,
line and sinker'' and the federal government for the pollution
along the Alaskan coastline.
   ``Exxon has lied from the start and the government has dragged
their feet and knuckles,'' said Monsport.
</TEXT>
