<DOCNO> AP890518-0268 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-18-89 1415EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-TankerSpill     05-18 1045</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tanker Spill,1084</SECOND>
<HEAD>Company Documents Indicate Hazelwood Skilled, but Troubled</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto AG1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN S. AKRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Company documents describe the former
captain of the Exxon Valdez as an intelligent, skilled seaman who
failed to live up to his potential and suffered from depression and
alcoholism.
   The previously confidential documents were released Wednesday
during hearings into the March 24 tanker accident in which nearly
11 million gallons of crude oil spilled into Prince William Sound.
   The third days' testimony before a National Transportation
Safety Board panel opened today with Second Officer Lloyd LeCain
Jr., who was asleep when the wreck occurred. He was questioned
about the ship's navigational equipment.
   LeCain said the wheel would not change the ship's course if
turned while the vessel was on autopilot, and no alarm would sound.
   Third Mate Gregory Cousins, who was in charge on the bridge when
the tanker ran aground, had testified this week that he set off the
autopilot about 12 minutes before the wreck, but the ship did not
respond to his course changes.
   Earlier, during the second day of the five-day hearings, the
NTSB panel heard testimony that:
   _Capt. Joseph Hazelwood's blood-alcohol content may have been
more than five times the legal limit when the tanker ran aground,
and bottles of low-alcohol beer were found in his cabin shortly
after the accident.
   _The chief mate feared for his life when he discovered how much
oil was gushing into the water. He said Hazelwood told him, ``Well,
this is one way to end a career.''
   _Coast Guard radar failed to identify the tanker's position in
the minutes before the wreck, and may have been out of calibration.
   An Exxon Shipping Co. disability report dated May 14, 1985,
details the reasons for Hazelwood's admission to a hospital for
alcohol treatment. A doctor wrote that Hazelwood, then 38, had been
drinking excessively, causing problems at home and work.
   The doctor described Hazelwood as ``depressed and demoralized,''
and recommended a 28-day treatment program. The doctor concluded
that Hazelwood should take a leave of absense to get involved in
Alcoholics Anonymous.
   Work evaluations from 1982 to 1987 describe Hazelwood as getting
along well with his crew and meeting the ``normal requirements of
the position,'' but lacked creativitity or interest in running a
ship.
   ``Joe does not try to achieve the true potential his gifted
intelligence warrants,'' one supervisor wrote.
   Three of the four evaluations recommended at least temporary
shore assignment, but there's no indication company officials acted
upon the suggestions.
   The last evaluation, in 1987, said Hazelwood ``handles unusual
situations well'' and rated him above average on decision-making
ability. A 1984 report ranked him high on ``safety consciousness.''
   In testimony Wednesday, toxicologist Mike Peat said Hazelwood's
blood-alcohol level would have been 0.22 percent when the vessel
ran aground, assuming he did not drink any alcoholic beverage from
then until his blood was tested nearly 11 hours later.
   Peat, director of a Sacramento, Calif., laboratory that tested
Hazelwood's blood and urine samples, said the blood sample showed
an alcohol level of 0.061 percent.
   The Coast Guard considers commercial vessel operators illegally
intoxicated at 0.04 percent.
   Mark Delozier, chief warrant officer at the Coast Guard marine
safety office in Valdez, was the third witness to testify that he
had smelled alcohol on Hazelwood's breath.
   ``I would describe it as very intense,'' Delozier said. ``It
smelled like someone who had been sitting in a bar drinking for
quite some time.''
   Delozier and Lt. Cmdr. Thomas Falkenstein were among the first
officials to board the ship after it ran aground. Falkenstein also
said he smelled alcohol on the captain's breath.
   Delozier said Hazelwood tried to mask his breath by placing his
hand over his mouth, drinking coffee and smoking a cigarette, which
the Coast Guardsman asked him to extinguish because of the volatile
oil fumes.
   Like previous witnesses, Delozier and Falkenstein said Hazelwood
did not appear drunk. But Peat said that's not unusual for someone
with a history of alcoholism. Even at 0.22 percent, a person's
judgment and vision would be impaired regardless of physical
appearance, he said.
   Hazelwood has pleaded innocent to misdemeanor charges of
operating a vessel while drunk and has declined to testify at the
NTSB hearings.
   The vessel's chief mate, James R. Kunkel, said he grabbed his
survival suit and thought he would die after the ship ran aground.
   ``I don't mind telling you that at the time, I knew that my
world would never be the same again,'' Kunkel said. ``I never knew
if I'd see my wife again.''
   He said he considered wearing a respirator after the odor of
crude oil filled the ship's passageways.
   ``I'm walking around wondering if I'm going to see the
sunrise,'' he recalled.
   The two ship traffic monitors testified that the Exxon Valdez
only showed up sporadically on radar after it left Valdez Narrows.
   Gordon Taylor testified that ships appeared and disappeared on
the radar, possibly because of a ``tuning problem'' with the
equipment.
   The ship radioed to the Coast Guard traffic center in Valdez
that it was going outside the normal shipping lanes to avoid ice,
but it never radioed back to say it was changing course again to
avoid Bligh Reef.
   Taylor said he lost sight of the tanker on radar and had no
indication it was in trouble. Minutes before it struck Bligh Reef,
Taylor was handing over his duties to controller Bruce Blandford.
   ``When I relieved Mr. Taylor, there was no reason for me to
believe there was anything out of place,'' Blandford said.
   Exxon representative William J. Deppe, who has rarely questioned
witnesses during the hearings, suggested to Taylor that inadequate
radar coverage may have contributed to the accident.
   ``If you were to see a vessel that was about to go aground, you
might recommend they change course?'' Deppe asked.
   ``Right,'' Taylor replied.
   Blandford testified that a test performed about 14 hours after
the wreck showed he had consumed alcohol, but he said it was from
``a couple of drinks to more or less calm down'' after his long
shift.
   ``After I'd finished my eight-hour watch and put in four more
hours of mayhem, I was pretty stressed out and pretty tired by the
time I came home,'' he said.
</TEXT>
