<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreet2pm     05-18 0304</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street 2pm,0319</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market pushed ahead today, unfazed by
a government report on inflation that was slightly worse than
expected.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, down about 5 points in
the early going, was up 7.33 at 2,469.76 by 2 p.m. on Wall Street.
   Gainers outnumbered losers by about 5 to 4 in nationwide trading
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 745 up, 606 down and
549 unchanged.
   The Labor Department reported that the consumer price index rose
0.7 percent in April, bringing the increase in the index so far in
1989 to an annual rate of 6.6 percent.
   The monthly number came in near the high end of advance
estimates on Wall Street, and apparently disappointed some traders
who had been hoping for a pleasant surprise in the data.
   Still, analysts noted that much of the increase came, as
expected, from a jump in energy prices that is not expected to be
repeated in coming months.
   That left the door open for stock-market bulls who contend that
the Federal Reserve has a good chance of succeeding in its effort
to restrain inflation without pushing the economy into a recession.
   Avon Products led the active list, down 6{ at 33|. Amway Corp.
withdrew a $39-a-share takeover bid for the company after Avon's
board rejected the offer.
   Gainers among the blue chips included International Paper, up 1}
at 49}; American Telephone &amp; Telegraph, up [ at 34}; Philip Morris,
up } at 136\, and International Business Machines, up { at 112.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks
gained .44 to 177.42. At the American Stock Exchange, the market
value index was up .38 at 352.22.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 129.53 million shares with two
hours to go.
</TEXT>
