<HEAD>Eds: New throughout</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stocks closed sharply higher Thursday for the
second straight session, strengthened partly by takeover
speculation.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index rose 21.5
points, or 1 percent, to 2,177.3.
   The Financial Times 30-share index was up 17.9 points at 1,810.1
at the close. The Financial Times 500-share index rose 13.29 points
to close at 1,235.66.
   Volume totaled 633.2 million shares, vs. 548.6 million shares
Wednesday.
   The market opened higher, emboldened by speculation that Ranks
Hovis McDougall PLC, a major British food company, might be the
target of a takeover by investors Jacob Rothschild and James
Goldsmith.
