<FIRST>u f PM-JapanFighter 2ndLd-Writethru   05-18 0637</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan Fighter, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0652</SECOND>
<HEAD>Administration Renews Opposition To FSX Restrictions</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: SUBS 2nd graf to insert dropped word ``infronging,'' SUBS 4th
graf pvs to update with committee action postponed until Tuesday</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARTON REPPERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration today renewed its
strong opposition to Senate-passed restrictions on the $6 billion
FSX fighter jet del, with Secretary of State James A. Baker III
saying they would put the entire warplane agreement with Japan at
risk.
   In a letter to the House Foreign Affairs Committee, Baker urged
the panel not to adopt the Senate legislation sponsored by Sen.
Robert C. Byrd, D-W.Va. Baker said the Byrd resolution
``establishes an unacceptable precedent infringing on the
president's constitutional authority with respect to the conduct of
negotiations with foreign powers.''
   He added, ``The conditions stated in the resolution would put
the entire FSX program and our agreement with Japan at risk.''
   House critics of the FSX deal initially had planned to go before
the Foreign Affairs Committee today to urge adoption of the
restrictions embodied in the Byrd resolution. But the panel instead
heard from several administration officials who underscored the
opposition stated in Baker's letter. Committee action on the
resolution was postponed until next Tuesday.
   Byrd's measure directs the White House to bar the transfer of
sophisticated jet engine technology to Japan and to guarantee that
American companies will get at least 40 percent of the work on the
FSX, an advanced version of the U.S. F-16 fighter.
   Earlier, the White House had said it has ``grave concerns'' that
the Byrd amendment could erode presidential authority. The State
Department said the provision could force renegotiation of the
agreement with the Japanese government.
   The Senate voted by a 52-47 margin Tuesday to defeat a
resolution that would have scrapped the FSX deal. But it then voted
72-27 to adopt Byrd's restrictions.
   General Dynamics is to join with Japan's Mitsubishi Heavy
Industries to codevelop and coproduce the next-generation fighter,
for deployment by Japan in the late 1990s. General Dynamics has
headquarters in St. Louis, but most of the FSX work would be done
at its F-16 plant in Fort Worth, Texas.
   In the House, Rep. Richard Gephardt, D-Mo., who campaigned for
the Democratic presidential nomination last year on a platform
urging retaliation against unfair trade practices by Japan, said it
is essential that Congress adopt the amendment because ``we don't
want some vague promise that doesn't get fulfilled.''
   Rep. Mel Levine, D-Calif., another outspoken opponent of the
FSX, declared that ``it is important to hold the administration's
feet to the fire. We're saying that when you negotiate a deal,
demonstrate that we are really going to get the 40 percent you were
talking about.''
   The Senate passed the Byrd amendment by a margin that would
override a presidential veto and Levine said there is a good chance
the House can follow suit.
   Rep. Dana Rohrabacher, R-Calif., said the Byrd amendment was a
classic example of ``micromanagement'' by Congress. He described it
as ``a sour-grape amendment by those who lost the vote against FSX
in the Senate.''
   However, Rep. Helen Delich Bentley, R-Md., predicted that a
number of Republicans would join the House's Democratic majority in
supporting the restrictions.
   At the White House, press secretary Marlin Fitzwater said Bush
told House Republicans his administration would work against the
Byrd amendment when the measure gets to a House-Senate conference
committee to resolve differences between the measures passed by the
two chambers.
   Fitzwater said Bush was concerned about the amendment because
``it creates a system of congressional approval over these kinds of
projects that we consider to be erosive of presidential power.''
   House Republican Leader Bob Michel of Illinois said Bush had
asked Republicans to support him on the FSX even though they face
opposing pressure from back home.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
