<DOCNO> AP890518-0273 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-18-89 1522EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f BC-Dollar-Gold     05-18 0410</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Dollar-Gold,0428</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Succumbs to Intervention, Gold Steady</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar succumbed to a barrage of central bank
intervention and ended sharply lower from earlier peaks in
volatile, nervous European trading Thursday.
   Gold prices steadied.
   Foreign exchange dealers said that while underlying demand for
the dollar remained strong, a sense of disarray pervaded the market.
   The dollar entered the European trading day on a weaker note,
after at least three rounds of Bank of Japan intervention earlier
Wednesday, dealers said.
   The U.S. currency then surged to its session highs late in the
morning, when the West German Bundesbank's central bank council
decided to leave its key interest rates unchanged.
   The dollar was supported further by news that U.S. consumer
prices rose a seasonally adjusted 0.7 percent in April, slightly
above average market forecasts.
   Later, a wave of concerted intervention started the dollar on
its downward move to its late levels.
   Joining the U.S. Federal Reserve, which intervened three times,
were the central banks of Britain, Switzerland, France, Belgium,
Austria, Italy and Canada, dealers said. The Bundesbank was
conspicuously absent, they said.
   ``The dollar was overbought, although there is still good
support underneath,'' said the chief dealer at a U.S. investment
bank. ``People are nervous over what the central banks have up
their sleeves.''
   ``The intervention put a temporary top on the dollar but it
hasn't turned sentiment, said a corporate dealer at an American
bank in London.
   In London, the dollar fell against the British pound. It cost
$1.6180 to buy one pound, dearer than $1.6140 late Wednesday.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Wednesday:
1.9660 West German marks, down from 1.9675; 1.7552 Swiss francs,
down from 1.7580; 6.6490 French francs, down from 6.6607; 2.2240
Dutch guilders, up from 2.2150; 1,439.50 Italian lire, up from
1,433.00; 1.1927 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1925.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends as Europe's business day begins,
the dollar rose 1.18 yen to close at 138.88 yen. Later in London it
was quoted at 138.60 yen.
   Gold held steady in London to a late bid price of $370.75 a troy
ounce, unchanged from late Wednesday.
   In Zurich, gold rose slightly to close at a bid $370.50,
compared with $370.25 late Wednesday.
   Earlier in Hong Kong gold fell $3.01 to close at a bid $371.73.
   Silver fell on the London market where the metal was trading at
a late bid price of $5.43 a troy ounce, compared with $5.46
Wednesday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890518-0274 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-18-89 1525EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   05-18 0292</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0302</SECOND>
<HEAD>Quiet Trading in Wake of Dry Weather Forecasts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices closed mixed
Thursday in modest trading on the Chicago Board of Trade, as
traders discounted rains in western crop states and looked forward
to expected dry conditions next week.
   Corn and soybean futures rose following word that the National
Weather Service's six- to 10-day forecast released Wednesday calls
for below-normal rain and above-normal temperatures in much of the
Corn Belt.
   ``There were some rumors that the Soviet Union has purchased
soymeal and soy oil out of South America,'' said Ted Mao, an
analyst with Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc., adding that the rumors
were not confirmed.
   Wheat prices dropped over concern that there hasn't been much
export of the grain recently. However, the Agriculture Department's
announcement Wednesday that the export bonus program would continue
as long as other nations subsidize their grain sales offered some
lift, analysts said.
   Mao noted that the action in the market has not varied much in
recent sessions.
   ``A lot of traders have memories of last year's market and are
trying to tie it in with this year's,'' said Mao. ``The volitility
is not there. The weather is not bad enough and there are more
acres planted. Traders will have to adjust to conditions as they
are today.''
   At the close, wheat was a { cent lower to 1 cent higher, with
the contract for delivery in May at $4.08{ a bushel; corn was 1\
cent lower to 3 cent higher with May at $2.76 a bushel; oats were a
{ cent to } cent lower with May at $1.83{ a bushel; soybeans were 3
cents to 8{ cents higher with May at $7.37{ a bushel.
