<DOCNO> AP890518-0276 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-18-89 1957EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Britain-GoldFields     05-18 0332</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Britain-Gold Fields,0344</SECOND>
<HEAD>Minorco Appealing Judge's Refusal to Lift Injunction</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Minorco SA said Thursday it was appealing a U.S.
judge's refusal to lift a preliminary injunction that scuttled its
hostile $5.7 billion attempted takeover of Consolidated Gold Fields
PLC.
   The Luxembourg-based, South African-controlled Minorco said the
appeal was filed Wednesday to the U.S. Court of Appeals for the
Second Circuit.
   The preliminary injunction blocked Minorco from buying more than
30 percent of the British gold mining giant's shares.
   Minorco owns 29.9 percent of the shares and had received
acceptances for its takeover offer that would have taken its
holding to 55 percent. A merger of the two companies would have
created the noncommunist world's largest gold producing concern.
   Repeated attempts by Minorco to have the injunction lifted were
denied by Judge Michael Mukasey of the U.S. District Court for the
Southern District of New York.
   The offer expired Wednesday under British takeover regulations
and Minorco must wait a year before it can make another bid for
Gold Fields, if it wants to. However, if another suitor makes a bid
for Gold Fields, Minorco can make a competing offer.
   The suit that resulted in the injunction was brought by Gold
Fields and by its 49-percent owned subsidiary Newmont Mining Corp.
Gold Fields later withdrew from the action, leaving just Newmont to
pursue the case.
   Minorco said it is defending itself against Newmont's lawsuit.
Further action in the U.S. courts, including the appeal, doesn't
suggest any decision has been taken regarding its pursuit of Gold
Fields, the company said.
   Minorco's continued efforts to overturn the U.S. court
injunction could be an attempt to clear up any antitrust concerns
in the United States in case the company decides to seek future
expansion in the U.S. natural resource sector.
   Minorco is 39.1 percent owned by Anglo American Corp. and 21
percent owned by De Beers Consolidated Mines Ltd., which are,
respectively, the gold and diamond mining interests of South
African Oppenheimer family.
</TEXT>
