<FILEID>AP-NR-05-18-89 1621EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-ExxonMeeting-Demonstrations     05-18 0568</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Exxon Meeting-Demonstrations,0585</SECOND>
<HEAD>Demonstrators Protest At Exxon Meeting, Peacefully</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Exxon Meeting Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos NY20, NY21, NY23</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HENRY STERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARSIPPANY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Singing ``What do you do with a drunken
sailor, make him skipper of an Exxon tanker,'' more than 250
demonstrators protested outside the oil company's annual
shareholder meeting Thursday.
   Demonstrators wearing costumes and holding signs reading
``Overthrow Exxon'' and ``Clean up your entire mess'' lined the
entranceway as Exxon Corp. stockholders arrived for the meeting at
the Aspen Manor Hotel, where about 80 police officers corralled
protesters in a parking lot.
   Protesters acted peacefully but spoke angrily about the March 24
spill of millions of gallons of crude oil from the tanker Exxon
Valdez into Alaska's Prince William Sound, the nation's worst oil
spill ever.
   ``Our environment is going to hell in a bucket,'' said Rae
McLaughlin, a 30-year-old office manager and member of New Jersey
Citizen Action, one of the environmental groups sponsoring the
protest. ``They're not even attempting to clean it up.''
   She and many others blamed Exxon for hiring Joseph Hazelwood,
captain of the Exxon Valdez. The Coast Guard has said Hazelwood
tested above the legal limit for alcohol nine hours after the
accident, but Hazelwood has pleaded innocent to charges of
operating a vessel while drunk.
   ``The whole thing was ridiculous,'' Ms. McLaughlin said. ``There
was no reason to have a drunk person at the helm.''
   Five demonstrators perched on stilts wore pig tails and pig
noses to complement their overstuffed tuxedos and briefcases
festooned with Exxon stickers and bulging with fake money.
   ``We just came to say we don't have to care, because we're
Exxon,'' said Isabel Byrd, a 51-year-old theater worker from
Trenton, who identified herself as a ``pig from Exxon.''
   One speakers addressing the crowd, many of whom wore black arm
bands and waved rags saying, ``Clean Energy Now,'' was Barry
Commoner, the environmentalist and former presidential candidate
from the Citizen's Party.
   He and other protesters said the spill points out the oil
industry's failure to prepare for such disasters, the United
States' overreliance on fossil fuels and a need to convert to solar
energy.
   Commoner also drew cheers from the crowd, which basked in sunny
80-degree weather, when he laughed at Exxon's proposal to add an
environmentalist to its board of directors.
   ``If the dying sea otters could talk, if the American people,
aghast at the criminal incompetence of the Exxon management could
be heard, if justice is to be done, the proper punishment is not
adding one environmentalist to the board of directors,'' Commoner
said. ``The proper punishment is to replace every one of them.''
   Steve Kosnac, a 63-year-old retiree from Somerville who said he
helped lay the Alaska pipeline during the 1970s, accused Exxon of
deliberately spilling the oil. Spoiling the coastline of Prince
William Sound would render it useless for anything but oil
exploration, he said.
   ``Oil companies are oil companies,'' Kosnac said. ``They're big
money and they'd walk through your property and just fight you in
court at a later date.''
   Others said the time had passed to lay blame and hoped the
disaster would spur Congress to pass legislation halting oil
exploration in the Alaskan Wildlife Refuge.
   Township Mayor Frank Priore said his sympathies lay with the
protesters and that he would ask Exxon to pay the police overtime
costs, which he estimated between $12,000 and $18,000.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
