<FILEID>AP-NR-05-18-89 1621EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreetClosing     05-18 0156</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street Closing,0166</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market climbed to a new post-crash
high today, unfazed by a government report on inflation that was
slightly worse than expected.
   The Labor Department reported that the consumer price index rose
0.7 percent in April, bringing the increase in the index so far in
1989 to an annual rate of 6.6 percent.
   The monthly number came in near the high end of advance
estimates on Wall Street, and apparently disappointed some traders
who had been hoping for a pleasant surprise in the data.
   Still, analysts noted that much of the increase came, as
expected, from a jump in energy prices that is not considered
likely to be repeated in coming months.
   That left the door open for stock-market bulls who contend that
the Federal Reserve has a good chance of succeeding in its effort
to restrain inflation without pushing the economy into a recession.
</TEXT>
