<FIRST>u f AM-MoneyFunds     05-18 0354</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Money Funds,0365</SECOND>
<HEAD>Money Funds Rose $4.9 Billion in Latest Week</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Interest rate figures reported by Donoghue's Money Fund Report
are for week ended Tuesday. All other figures are for the week ended Wednesday.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Assets of the nation's 468 money market mutual
funds rose $4.9 billion in the latest week, the Investment Company
Institute said Thursday.
   The rise, to a record total of $311.95 billion in the seven-day
period ended Wednesday, followed a $2.9 billion increase in the
funds' assets the previous week, according to the Washington-based
mutual fund trade group.
   The funds' assets hit the previous record high of $307.06
billion in the week ended May 10.
   The Investment Company Institute said that in the latest week,
assets of 231 general purpose funds rose $644 million to $101.42
billion, assets of 95 broker-dealer funds increased $1.91 billion
to $131.38 billion, and assets of 142 institutional funds rose
$2.35 billion to $79.14 billion.
   The seven-day average yield on money market mutual funds rose in
the week ended Tuesday to 9.16 percent from 9.15 percent the
previous week, according to Donoghue's Money Fund Report, a trade
journal based in Holliston, Mass.
   The 30-day average yield was 9.17 percent, unchanged from the
previous week, Donoghue's said.
   The average maturity of the portfolios held by money funds was
36 days, up from 34 days, Donoghue's said.
   Separately, the newsletter Bank Rate Monitor said its survey of
100 leading commercial banks, savings and loan assocations and
savings banks in the nation's 10 largest markets showed the
effective annual yield available on money market accounts was 6.63
percent as of Wednesday, unchanged from a week earlier.
   The North Palm Beach, Fla.-based newsletter said the effective
annual yield available on special savings accounts, called Super
NOW accounts, was unchanged at 5.15 percent.
   Bank Rate Monitor said the effective annual yield was 9.27
percent on six-month certificates of deposit, down from 9.31 the
previous week. Yields were 9.42 percent on 1-year CDs, down from
9.48 percent; 9.23 percent on 2{-year CDs, down from 9.27 percent;
and 9.14 percent on 5-year CDs, down from 9.18 percent.
</TEXT>
