<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     05-18 0236</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0244</SECOND>
<HEAD>Close Slightly Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Crude oil prices edged higher in uneven trading
Thursday as the market failed to respond forcefully to any outside
news.
   The June contract for West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark
grade of U.S. crude, rose 7 cents to $20.20 a 42-gallon barrel on
the New York Mercantile Exchange. On Wednesday, the June contract
fell 57 cents.
   ``It's choppy and very erratic,'' said Jim Fiedler, a trader
with E.D.&amp;F. Man International Futures Inc. ``The market is not
reacting to bullish news at this point.''
   A handful of developments that normally would move prices higher
were largely ignored Thursday, including a fire at an oil facility
in West Germany and flooding that could hamper the movement of
crude in East Texas, Fiedler said.
   Prices of refined products traded on the mercantile exchange
were mixed as traders responded to seasonal supply-demand
influences.
   The June contract for wholesale gasoline rose 1.26 cents a
gallon to close at 64.53 cents. On Wednesday, the contract plunged
2.53 cents as traders decided there was an oversupply of gasoline,
but on Thursday, after reassessing the situation, the market
anticipated increased demand during the summer driving season,
Fiedler said.
   The June contract for home heating oil fell 0.41 cent to 47.55
cents a gallon Thursday as traders believed there would be ample
supply of the fuel, he said. The contract fell 1.23 cents on
Wednesday.
</TEXT>
