<FILEID>AP-NR-05-18-89 1820EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Chrysler-Thrifty     05-18 0570</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chrysler-Thrifty,0593</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chrysler Agrees to Buy Thrifty; All Big Three in Auto Rental Business</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chrysler Corp. said Thursday it has agreed to
acquire Thrifty-Rent-A-Car Systems Inc. for $263 million, becoming
the last of the Big Three automakers to take a stake in the rental
car business.
   The agreement, announced by Chrysler Chairman Lee Iacocca during
the company's annual meeting in San Francisco, calls for Chrysler
to pay $27.75 a share for all of the Tulsa, Okla.-based Thrifty's
stock.
   Thrifty's five major shareholders have granted options to
Chrysler for acquisition of 54 percent of the outstanding shares.
   The news sent Thrifty's stock price up $9.25 a share to $27.25
in national over-the-counter trading. In trading on the New York
Stock Exchange, Chrysler rose 37{ cents a share to $24.75.
   Ford Motor Co. has interests in Hertz Corp. and Budget Rent A
Car Corp., and General Motors Corp. owns part of National Car
Rental.
   Iacocca called Thrifty, the fifth-largest car rental company in
North America, ``a solid player in the car rental business.''
Thrifty's management would remain in place.
   ``We are delighted with the prospect of joining forces with
Chrysler,'' said Thrifty Chairman William E. Lobeck Jr. ``Our board
of directors recommends unanimously that stockholders tender their
shares.''
   Chrysler is epected to make a tender offer starting by Wednesday
for Thrifty stock. Chrysler supplies 75 percent to 80 percent of
the cars in Thrifty's fleet.
   The rental car business is appealing to the automakers for
several reasons.
   Rental cars make up a substantial portion of each automaker's
fleet sales. They also provide added exposure of the products away
from the showroom that could turn into sales later.
   On a smaller scale, sales of cars to rental car companies can
help inventories of some models and serve as a testing ground for
new trim packages or options.
   ``Obviously, it's a defensive move to keep its access to fleet
markets,'' auto analyst Ron Glantz of Montgomery Securities Inc. of
San Francisco said of the Chrysler-Thrifty deal. ``But defensive
moves don't necessarily make you money.''
   Ford, the nation's No. 2 automaker, had held 55 percent of Hertz
Corp., the nation's largest automobile renter. In a deal announced
earlier this month, Volvo North American Corp. acquired a portion
of Ford's equity which would reduce Ford's ownership to 49 percent
of Hertz's stock.
   In March, a financing package was completed in which Ford would
provide $324 million for the acquisition of Budget Rent a Car
Corp., the third-largest car rental company in the nation, by Beech
Holdings Corp. Ford's equity in that deal involved non-voting
preferred shares of Beech.
   Ford supplies about 70 percent of Budget's cars and a majority
of the 180,000-car fleet operated by Hertz, which refused to say
exactly how many cars were Ford products.
   GM, the nation's largest automaker, acquired a ``significant
minority interest'' last September in National Car Rental, the
nation's fourth-largest car renter. GM spokesman Peter Peterson
declined to say how much interest GM held in National.
   GM provides National with about 75 percent of its cars.
   Avis Inc., the nation's second-largest automobile renter, is
privately held.
   Thrifty, which licenses more than 650 outlets worldwide,
reported $2.6 million in profit on revenues of $28.6 million during
the first three months of this year. For the fiscal year ended June
30, 1988, the company made $9.1 million on revenues of $79.3
million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
