<DOCNO> AP890518-0282 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-18-89 1836EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     05-18 0638</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0663</SECOND>
<HEAD>Strong Dollar Pushes Gold, Platinum Lower</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HERBERT G. McCANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Precious metals futures prices fell sharply
Thursday on New York's Commodity Exchange as investors continued
bailing out of the market because of the strong dollar.
   On other markets, grain and soybeans were mixed, livestock and
meat prices settled mostly lower, and energy futures were mostly
higher.
   Precious metal prices dropped as the dollar continued to display
strength despite coordinated dollar selling by central banks in
Europe and Japan. A stronger dollar generally tends to attract
speculators from other investment such as precious metals.
   Prices were pressured as the dollar remained firm following the
government's report that consumer price inflation soared 0.7
percent in April, the sharpest advance in more than two years.
   Gold settled $3.20 to $3.60 lower with the contract for delivery
in May at $369.70 a troy ounce and silver was 2.8 cents to 3.0
cents lower with May at $5.401 a troy ounce.
   Platinum prices also moved sharply lower, at one time falling
$19.90 from Wednesday's close before rallying to finish $7.20 to
$7.70 lower with July at $502.70 a troy ounce.
   Bette Raptopoulos, an analyst for Prudential-Bache Securities
Inc. in New York, said despite recent reports that demand for
platinum outpaces supply, many speculators are not convinced and
are unloading the metal.
   Livestock and meat futures closed mostly lower on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange.
   Live and feed cattle prices drifted lower in reaction to
Wednesday's Agriculture Department cattle-on-feed report showing
higher than expected April marketings and feedlot placement.
   Lower cash prices can be expected later this year because of the
high feed lot placement, analysts say.
   Hog prices slipped with lower cash bids, and prospects of
increased marketing in coming days, said Dale Durchholz, an analyst
with Agri-Visor Services Inc. in Bloomington, Ill.
   Frozen pork belly futures were down because of deteriorating
cash prices.
   Live cattle were .53 cent to .80 cent lower with June at 70.67
cents a pound; feeder cattle were .30 cent to .90 cent lower with
May at 76.97 cents a pound; hogs were .10 cent to .37 cent a pound
with June at 48.27 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were .65 cent
lower to .10 cent higher with May at 35.10 a pound.
   Grain and soybean futures closed mixed in modest trading on the
Chicago Board of Trade, as traders discounted rains in western crop
states and looked forward to expected dry conditions next week.
   Corn and soybean futures rose following word that the National
Weather Service's six- to 10-day forecast released Wednesday called
for below-normal rain and above-normal temperatures in much of the
Corn Belt.
   Ted Mao, an analyst with Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc., also said
prices were supported by unconfirmed rumors that the Soviet Union
had purchased soymeal and soy oil from South America.
   Wheat prices dropped over concern that there hasn't been much
export of the grain recently. However, the Agriculture Department's
announcement Wednesday that the export bonus program would continue
as long as other nations subsidize their grain sales provided some
support, analysts said.
   Wheat settled 1{ cents lower to 1 cent higher, with May at
$4.08\ a bushel; corn was 1\ cents lower to 3 cents higher with May
at $2.76 a bushel; oats were a { cent to 1 cent lower with May at
$1.83 a bushel; soybeans were 4\ cents to 8\ cents higher with May
at $7.37{ a bushel.
   Energy prices moved higher on the New York Mercantile Exchange.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil was 7 cents to 14 cents higher
with June at $20.20 a barrel; heating oil was .37 cent to .44 cent
lower with June at 47.55 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline was .30
cent lower to 1.26 cents higher with June at 64.53 cents a gallon.
</TEXT>
