<FILEID>AP-NR-05-18-89 1839EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Exxon-Meeting 1stLd-Writethru   05-18 0806</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Exxon-Meeting, 1st Ld-Writethru,0833</SECOND>
<HEAD>Exxon Chairman Rejects Call For His Resignation</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout with drug-testing plan; fresh quotes from shareholders;
vote on director slate; details thruout.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JULIA C. MARTINEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARSIPPANY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Exxon Corp. Chairman Lawrence G. Rawl
rejected a call for his resignation Thursday but assured company
shareholders that he and other Exxon management would be part of
major policy changes at the company, including random drug testing.
   ``I want you to know there's going to be equity,'' Rawl told
about 1,700 Exxon shareholders attending the first annual meeting
since the March 24 spill by the tanker Exxon Valdez. ``We will have
random testing of our people and of senior management, including
me.''
   Addressing stockholders at the start of the meeting, Rawl
repeated his apologies for the disaster and pledged again to clean
up the fouled waters and beaches in and around Alaska's Prince
William Sound.
   Rawl showed a brief film made by Exxon about its cleanup efforts
and later fielded shareholder questions for nearly four hours in
what turned out to be a quieter meeting than company officials had
anticipated.
   Dozens of local police and company security patrolled inside and
outside the meeting hall, bags were checked and people attending
had to pass through metal detectors.
   A crowd of orderly demonstrators carried signs and chanted
slogans outside but were kept at least 50 yards from the entrance.
Some sang, ``What do you do with a drunken sailor, make him skipper
of an Exxon tanker.''
   Parsippany police and Exxon officials estimated the crowd at
about 150, while other estimates were as high as 250. Exxon
officials said they had expected at least 600 demonstrators.
   Five demonstrators perched on stilts wore pig tails and pig
noses to complement their overstuffed tuxedos and briefcases
festooned with Exxon stickers and bulging with fake money.
   ``We just came to say we don't have to care, because we're
Exxon,'' said Isabel Byrd, a 51-year-old theater worker from
Trenton, N.J., who identified herself as a ``pig from Exxon.''
   Inside, Ed Rothschild, director of the consumer group Citizen
Action, called on Rawl to resign.
   ``We think that the shareholders and the board need to have a
new set of people to deal with these circumstances and to set the
company on a new course,'' said Rothschild, who owns one share of
stock. ``The question is, will you resign and if not why not?''
   ``The answer is, no I won't,'' Rawl replied to a chorus of boos
mixed with applause. Rawl said the best thing Exxon could do was
abide by the promises the company has already made.
   Jay D. Hair, president of the National Wildlife Federation and a
wildlife biologist, called on Exxon to set up a multibillion-dollar
cleanup trust fund starting with $1 billion immediately and annual
contributions of $1 billion a year thereafter.
   Rawl rejected that proposal last week, saying the company has
already committed to doing everything possible to clean up the
spill.
   Hair, representing holders of 48,000 shares of Exxon stock, told
Exxon management that areas already designated as cleaned by Exxon
remain badly soiled.
   ``It's an absolute joke,'' Hair said of the cleanup. ``You can
pick up a rock and it drips oil.''
   Robin Dexter, a commercial salmon fisherman whose livelihood has
depended on the now-fouled Alaska waters, said he purchased 10
shares of Exxon stock just to be able to attend Thursday's meeting.
   ``My intention is to convince people in the (fishing) industry
to accumulate shares so we can seriously put an issue before
shareholders that will result in some changes,'' Dexter said later.
   Several large pension funds had threatened in the weeks leading
up to the meeting to vote against management if it didn't
demonstate its willingness to avert future spills.
   In the final tally, 976.6 million shares, or 77.8 percent, were
voted in favor of electing the current slate of directors.
   Exxon President Lee Raymond said the number of customers who had
returned their Exxon credit cards was up to 18,000 out of a total
of 7 million.
   Among the demands by the institutional shareholders were the
appointment to the board of an environmental expert and the
formation of a committee to review Exxon policies on the
environment and worker safety and health.
   Rawl, who has agreed to both requests, said the company was
reviewing a list of candidates and that an environmentalist would
begin serving on the board before next year's shareholders meeting.
   Despite jibes and name-calling by dissident stockholders, Rawl
told reporters afterward it wasn't as bad as he had expected.
   Rawl called the recommendations useful and fair.
   ``I don't feel beat upon,'' he said.
   ``We've got to communicate better,'' he said. ``It's incumbent
on me to communicate better. We have to keep working on this
problem. But we're going to get our reputation back.''
</TEXT>
