<FIRST>u f AM-Xerox     05-18 0387</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Xerox,0400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Xerox Says No Takeover In Sight, Earnings Will Improve</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN A. BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Xerox Corp. Chairman David T. Kearns predicted
Thursday the company's restructuring would improve pre-tax profit
by $50 million to $60 million this year and more in coming years.
   The restructuring of business products and systems, announced in
January, will cut costs enough to increase pre-tax profits by $100
million to $120 million in 1990 and following years, Kearns said at
the company's annual meeting.
   Kearns also said the company intends to remain independent.
   ``The board of directors has no plan or intention for the
company to be acquired,'' Kearns said. ``The board believes that
the best interests of our shareholders, customers and employees
would be served by continuing to pursue our strategic direction as
an independent company.
   ``We believe the most effective way of increasing the return to
our shareholders is through improved financial returns,'' he said.
   Kearns also indicated that the company has not been approached,
and noted that no one shareholder has as much as 5 percent of the
Stamford, Conn.-based company's stock.
   In 1988, the company had pre-tax income of $1 billion, with a
net income of $388 million, and per-share earnings of $3.50, both
declines from previous years.
   Under its restructuring, Xerox is scaling back its electronic
typewriter business, cut about 2,000 jobs and ending the marketing
of medical hardware that combines xerography and radiography. The
changes resulted in a pre-tax charge of $275 million.
   ``Assuming a reasonably stable economic environment, which I
believe we have, and barring any major catastrophe or dislocation
in financial markets, our total corporate earnings should continue
to grow in 1989,'' Kearns said.
   Also at Thursday's meeting, the shareholders re-elected 14
members of the board, and turned aside several shareholder
resolutions, including ones from pension funds that the company
sever all ties with South Africa and adopt the MacBride principles,
which seek to assure equal employment opportunity for Catholics in
Northern Ireland.
   In addition to computers and office products, the company also
includes a financial services group, led by Crum and Forster Inc.
insurance company, Xerox Credit Corp.; Van Kampen Merritt Inc., a
specialized investment banking firm; Furman Selz, a investment bank
and stock broker; Xerox Financial Services Insurance Co.; and a
number of joint ventures.
</TEXT>
