<SECOND>AM-Macy-Investment,0270</SECOND>
<HEAD>Macy Chairman Denies Plans to Divest Divisions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of R.H. Macy &amp; Co. Thursday said
the retailer feels its financial footing is secure since it went
private in 1986 and it doesn't intend to divest any department
store divisions.
   Edward S. Finkelstein said there have been persistent rumors
that Macy's might be planning to sell off some assets.
   Some of the speculation in publications and circulating in the
retail industry suggests Macy's may be contemplating divestitures
due to concerns about servicing the heavy debt load it took on in
its leveraged buyout.
   ``We have no intention of selling off any divisions and when we
have been approached we have immediately indicated that our
divisions are not for sale,'' Finkelstein stated in a letter to
investors involved in Macy's LBO.
   He also stated that Macy's has received inquiries from
``interested parties about making an investment in our company.''
   ``We listen to and consider all serious ideas,'' he said. ``Thus
far, none have been appropriate for our investors.''
   The letter did not identify who has approached Macy's. The Wall
Street Journal reported Thursday that specialty apparel retailer
Limited Inc. has expressed interest and had preliminary talks with
Macy's about making an investment in the New York-based company.
   Finkelstein also said Macy's debt structure is sound.
   ``The company is well financed and has sufficient liquidity to
fund its on-going business as well as capital expenditures for new
stores and renovations,'' he said.
   Macy's debts are said to total more than $5.2 billion currently.
