<FIRST>u f AM-Argentina-Economy     05-18 0292</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Argentina-Economy,0301</SECOND>
<HEAD>Austral Plunges on Rumors of New Currency</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED McCULLOUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The austral plunged again
Thursday and interest rates soared as rumors swept the market that
a new currency might be introduced.
   ``No government official at any moment has even thought about
that,'' Treasury Secretary Oscar Merbilhaa said. But the austral
fell by 23 percent, selling for 170 per 1 dollar compared with
131-1 on Wednesday.
   The newspaper La Razon reported in a front-page story that the
government was preparing to introduce a new currency, one unit of
which would equal 100 australs.
   The austral has fallen by 38 percent since national elections
last Sunday, and 90 percent since early February. Interest rates
reached 200 percent a month as banks scrambled to prevent investors
from removing deposits to buy dollars.
   At the close of the business day, the government announced that
effective immediately, bus fares, gasoline, telephone and other
utility rates would be increased by 40 percent. The latest
projections indicate that inflation may top 50 percent this month.
   ``There is little doubt that the Argentine economy is entering
in full a stage of hyperinflation,'' the daily newspaper La Nacion
said in its lead editorial. ``It must be acknowledged that
hyperinflation always has unleashed corrosive political and social
situations.''
   On Sunday, the opposition Peronist Party was returned to power
after an absence of 13 years. The fluctuations stemmed from fears
that the economy was teetering out of control, and worries about
what Peronist economic policies will be.
   ``Our government is not going to embargo deposits, nor
confiscate foreign exchange, nor open security boxes, or anything
like that,'' said Eduardo Menem, a national senator and key adviser
to his brother, president-elect Carlos Menem.
</TEXT>
