<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold Bjt   05-18 0769</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold, Bjt,0797</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Succumbs to Intervention, Gold Falls</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: RETRANSMITS to restore bjt slug.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Central banks battered down the dollar Thursday
in a battle with currency dealers who had driven the currency
sharply upward in recent weeks.
   Traders shrugged off the central bank dollar sales at first but
the rally broke by late-morning trading in New York, when the
dollar hit its highest point in years against key currencies.
   Still, the dollar finished the day less than half a percent
below its levels of late Wednesday, indicating that traders
remained willing to challenge the resolve of government bankers and
finance officials.
   ``We have a market that still wants to test the upside potential
for the dollar,'' said Nicholas Sargen, a Salomon Brothers Inc.
analyst.
   He said estimates of the official dollar sales ranged from $1.5
billion to $3 billion, including heavy sales by the Bank of Japan
during Tokyo trading hours.
   In precious metals trading, gold plunged in late activity to
levels not seen since August 1986. Republic National Bank of New
York quoted gold at $368.30 a troy ounce as of 4 p.m. EDT, down
from $371.75 late Wednesday.
   The dollar peaked at 1.9880 West German marks and 139.60
Japanese yen _ approaching what traders consider to psychologically
important levels of 2 marks and 140 yen. Reaching those levels
could incite further speculative buying, dealers say.
   Analysts grasped for explanations for the dollar's strength. The
biggest factor appeared to be momentum of the market itself, which
often moves independently of underlying economic factors.
   A Labor Department inflation report was mildly positive for the
dollar. Consumer prices rose 0.7 percent in April, or 0.2 percent
excluding food and energy. The report slightly diminished
expectations of an interest-rate cut by the Federal Reserve, which
would make returns less attractive on dollar-denominated
investments.
   Also helping the dollar was word that the West German central
bank had decided against raising interest rates to defend the mark.
   Several analysts said central banks would have a hard time
depressing the dollar without interest-rate increases in Japan and
West Germany or rate cuts in the United States.
   But many traders doubt how serious the Federal Reserve and
Treasury Department are about restraining the dollar.
   A strong dollar helps U.S. policymakers fight inflation by
holding down import prices and cooling off exports, said Raymond
Worseck, an economist for A.G. Edwards &amp; Sons Inc. in St. Louis.
   Worseck said the dollar should remain strong indefinitely
because global investors believe the United States is a good place
for their investments.
   But Andrew F. Brimmer, a former Federal Reserve governor, said
the dollar eventually will be dragged down by the huge U.S. trade
deficit, which is funneling dollars overseas.
   ``I am convinced that the dollar is responding to short-run
transitory factors and not to long-run factors,'' said Brimmer, who
runs a Washington-based consulting firm, Brimmer &amp; Co.
   Joining the Federal Reserve were the central banks of Britain,
Switzerland, France, Belgium, Austria, Italy, Canada and Japan,
dealers said. The West German Bundesbank was conspicuously absent,
they said.
   In London, the British pound rose to $1.6180 from $1.6140 late
Wednesday. In New York, sterling rose to $1.6175 from $1.6115.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends as Europe's business day begins,
the dollar rose 1.18 yen from Wednesday to close at 138.88 yen.
Later in London the dollar was quoted at 138.60 yen. In New York
the dollar fell to 138.65 yen from Wednesday's 139.22.
   Other late dollar rates in New York compared with late
Wednesday's rates included: 1.9670 West German marks, down from
1.9715; 1.7568 Swiss francs, down from 1.7615; 1.1927 Canadian
dollars, up from 1.1908; 6.6585 French francs, down from 6.6760;
and 1,433 Italian lire, down from 1,435.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Wednesday,
included: 1.9660 West German marks, down from 1.9675; 1.7552 Swiss
francs, down from 1.7580; 6.6490 French francs, down from 6.6607;
2.2240 Dutch guilders, up from 2.2150; 1,439.50 Italian lire, up
from 1,433.00; 1.1927 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1925.
   Gold held steady in London at a late bid of $370.75 a troy
ounce. In Zurich gold rose to $370.50 an ounce from $370.25.
Earlier in Hong Kong gold fell $3.01 from Wednesday to close at a
bid of $371.73.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold bullion for current
delivery fell to $369.70 a troy ounce from $373.20.
   Silver fell on the London market to a late bid of $5.43 a troy
ounce from $5.46 Wednesday. On New York's Comex, silver for current
delivery fell to $5.401 an ounce from $5.429.
</TEXT>
