<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Navistar     05-18 0265</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Navistar,0275</SECOND>
<HEAD>Navistar Reports Drop in Earnings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Navistar International Corp. on Thursday reported
its net income for the second quarter fell 50 percent from a year
ago because of higher costs and high capacity at factories.
   In the fiscal quarter ended April 30, net income totaled $35
million, or 11 cents a share, down from $70 million, or 24 cents a
share on sales of $1.08 billion in the year-ago period.
   James C. Cotting, Navistar's chairman and chief operating
officer, attributed the decline in earnings to costs associated
with having operations at near-capacity. He also cited the cost of
introducing new truck models and lower parts sales.
   Navistar, a medium and heavy truck and diesel engine
manufacture, reported a 3 percent increase in truck sales during
the second period, a 12 percent increase in shipments of diesel
engines and a 6 percent decline in parts sales.
   Officials said market share of the company's medium and heavy
trucks increased to 27.9 percent in the second quarter of 1989,
compared with 27 percent for the year ago quarter.
   For the first six months of its 1989 fiscal year, Navistar
reported net income of $72.8 million, or 23 cents a share, compared
with $114.9 million, or 39 cents a share a year ago.
   Net income for the first half of 1988 included a one-time
after-tax gain of $24 million from the settlement of Canadian
pension obligations and a $15 million charge to discontinued
operations.
   Sales for the first half of 1989 totalled $2.04 billion,
compared with $1.97 billion for the same period last year.
</TEXT>
