<FILEID>AP-NR-05-18-89 2142EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-US-Korea     05-18 0369</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Korea,0382</SECOND>
<HEAD>South Korea Agrees to Ease Import Restraints</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: also on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GENE KRAMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South Korea, hoping to head off threatened
U.S. trade sanctions, has reached agreement on a package of import
liberalization measures sought by the Bush administration,
officials announced Thursday.
   Under the agreement, to be signed next week, South Korea pledged
to ease conditions on foreign investments and open its market to
foreign-owned travel and advertising agencies and wholesalers of
pharmaceuticals and cosmetics.
   U.S. Trade Representative Carla Hills praised the actions taken
by South Korea's negotiators but said the United States still
intends to push for the removal of other trade barriers, especially
those affecting U.S. agricultural products.
   ``Korea's market-opening measures will bring real and
substantial benefits to American and other exporters and
investors,'' she said in a statement.
   Under the 1988 Omnibus Trade Act, Hills must by May 28 decide
whether to include South Korea in a list of countries that are
possible targets for U.S. retaliation because it has erected unfair
trade barriers against American products.
   Hills' statement did not indicate whether South Korea's action
would be enough to keep it off the target list, but South Korean
officials indicated that they hoped that would be the case.
   ``Chances are higher than a month ago that Korea will be
excluded'' from the list of target countries, said Kim Chil-su,
assistant South Korean trade minister.
   In the agreement, South Korea said it would replace an advance
approval requirement for foreign investment with simple
notification rules, phasing in the change from 1991 through 1993.
South Korea also agreed to admit foreign travel agencies starting
in January 1991, officials said.
   Ms. Hills said the agreements ``create a useful precedent'' for
the current round of global trade liberalization negotiations which
are scheduled to be completed in 1990.
   But she said the United States remains ``committed to further
marketing opening in Korea, especially in agriculture.''
   The Korean side last month announced plans to remove or lower
import barriers by 1991 on 243 farm and fishery products, but in
the latest round it rejected U.S. demands for the opening of its
market to nine more foodstuffs including oranges, officials said.
</TEXT>
