<DOCNO> AP890518-0299 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-18-89 2204EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-S&amp;LBill 1stLd-Writethru a0680 05-18 0741</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-S&amp;L Bill, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0680,0757</SECOND>
<HEAD>Industry Share of Bailout Raised by $600 Million; Surtax Rejected</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: RECASTS lede to show that bulk of payments over three-year period
would be in 1991 and 1992, and to show surcharge is on taxes; SUBS 4th
graf to show surcharge on income taxes; INSERTS one graf after 11th pvs,
Bush's proposed..., to give administration reaction; also moving general
news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congressional tax writers voted Tuesday to
make savings and loan associations add $600 million to their share
of an industry bailout through 1992 but rejected an income tax
surcharge last used in the Vietnam War to finance the government's
$50 billion share.
   The House Ways and Means Committee amended the S&amp;L legislation
to remove a provision that would have allowed S&amp;Ls to escape $300
million annual industry contributions in 1991 and 1992 toward the
costs of financing the bailout, the biggest in the nation's history.
   That provision had been slipped into President Bush's bailout
bill two weeks ago by House Banking Committee Chairman Henry B.
Gonzalez, D-Texas, at the urging by some of the industry's 12
district Federal Home Loan Banks.
   Before approving the bill on a 26-10 vote, the tax-writing Ways
and Means panel also fought off an attempt to pay for the
government share of the bailout through a five-year 1.5 percent
surtax on personal and corporate income taxes.
   The defeated surtax would have been the first time such a
revenue-raising device was utilized by the government since the
late President Lyndon Johnson used one in the late 1960s to finance
the Vietnam War.
   Its purpose was to save an estimated $200 billion in interest
costs that taxpayers will have to absorb over the next 30 years by
financing the government's share of the bailout through increased
borrowing.
   ``We've got garbage and none of us wants to carry it out,'' said
Rep. Sam Gibbons, D-Fla., who proposed the surtax. ``So what we're
saying is that our children and grandchildren are going to carry it
out. That's just morally and ethically wrong.''
   Gibbons' surtax would have added another $150 in taxes a year
for every $10,000 in federal income taxes paid by an individual,
family or company. It also would have violated President Bush's
pledge of ``no new taxes.''
   It was defeated on a 10-13 vote after Rep. Frank J. Guarini,
D-N.J., said it would only ``derail everything that's been done''
in view of President Bush's campaign pledge of ``No new taxes.''
   Over Bush's objection, however, the committee reaffirmed its
vote last week to make the S&amp;L bailout part of the federal deficit,
defeating his elaborate scheme to finance it through private market
bond sales.
   Bush's proposed bond sales would increase the government's total
debt but would have added a total of only $3.5 billion to the
yearly deficits in fiscal 1989, 1990 and 1991, allowing the
appearance of overall annual reductions.
   ``The Ways and Means Committee vote to waive
Gramm-Rudman-Hollings sets a precedent that would render its budget
discipline meaningless,'' said Treasury Secretary Nicholas F. Brady.
   The Congressional Budget Office and others have estimated that
Bush's plan would cost taxpayers an additional $4.5 billion in
interest costs over the next 30 years than if the money was
borrowed directly from the Treasury.
   Under the direct government borrowing alternative approved by
the House tax writers, the deficit would swell by $9.3 billion this
year, $23.3 billion in fiscal 1990 and $13.8 billion in fiscal
1991. Those amounts would be exempted from Gramm-Rudman deficit
reduction targets of $100 billion in fiscal 1990 and $64 billion in
fiscal 1991.
   On a voice vote, the committee said that S&amp;Ls have to contribute
$600 million more to the bailout's cost in 1991 and 1992 and
potentially billions of dollars more over the next three decades by
indexing increases in a required $300 million annual contribution
to inflation.
   Bush in February had proposed the industry pay $300 million of
the estimated $4 billion to $5 billion of the annual interest costs
over the next 30 years for the bailout's costs.
   The $300 million is in addition to approximately $6 billion in
up-front money that the nation's 3,000 thrift institutions have to
contribute to the plan.
   But even with those amounts, the Congressional Budget Office
(CBO) estimates that taxpayers will absorb 70 percent of the total
estimated bailout tab of $280 billion, including interest, over the
next 30 years.
</TEXT>
